[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Welcome to the 1...d6 Against Everything course!  We are Grandmasters Mircea Parligras and Leon Livaic, and in this course, we'll show you a complete repertoire for Black starting with  1...d6  . One fine point of  1...d6  is that it can be used against any reply from White. It leads to fighting positions, where Black even has good chances to fight for a win.   On the other hand, White has many possible setups and has to make decisions early on. It's worth mentioning that the players with White will spend most of their time preparing against main openings like the Ruy Lopez, Sicilian, Nimzo-Indian, and so on and will only briefly look at  1...d6  . }
1. e4
{ White's most popular move. Basically, in this course, we recommend four setups for Black, depending on what White plays.   Against  1.e4  ,  we'll get the Philidor by playing ...d6 @@StartBracket@@of course!@@EndBracket@@, ...Nf6, ...e5 and ...Nbd7.   Against  1.d4  --  2.Nf3  --  3.c4  --  4.Nc3  --  5.e4  ,  we'll go for a King's Indian setup with ...Bg4. By trading the light-squared bishop for the knight and going ...e5 afterwards, we're actually heading for a more strategic battle.   Another popular line for White is the King's Indian with g3 after  1.d4  --  2.c4  --  3.Nf3  --  4.g3  , or  4.Nc3  --  and  5.g3  . This is a solid line for White, and here we recommend the KID setup with ideas  of ...Bf5 in order to play ...Ne4.   Finally, against the English Opening or  1.d4  --  and  2.c4  we recommend @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq d3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...d6  and  2.c4  e5  , and depending on what White does  we can go ...f5 before playing ...Nf6. }
1... d6
{ Just to keep things simple, we'll go  1...d6  against everything!  Here, we intend to attack the e4-pawn with ...Nf6, and first, we need to make sure it cannot advance further. }
2. d4 { White gets full control of the center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're developing and at the same time attacking the e4-pawn. } 3. Nc3
{ The main move here. Don't worry; all the other replies like  3.Bd3  ,  3.f3  , or even  3.Nd2  are covered as well. }
3... e5 { We're getting a foothold in the center. } 4. Nf3
{ The main and most ambitious move for White. White defends the d4-pawn and attacks e5.  4.Nge2  is covered as well, while  4.dxe5  leads to an endgame where Black doesn't experience any particular problems. }
4... Nbd7
{ This is the Philidor Defense. We're defending the e5-pawn, and we may develop with ...Be7 and ...O-O next.   Here we covered many moves like  5.Bc4  ,  5.Rg1  ,  5.g4  ,  5.a4  just to name some of them. Actually, in White's main line with  5.Bc4  ,  we give two alternatives for Black so that it won't be easy for your opponents to prepare against you.  We put a lot of work into this course and we analyzed the lines and made the comments together. If possible, we tried to avoid very forced lines where you need to remember the moves precisely. Instead, we gave some typical setups, and we explained in detail the plans in the position.  Very often, when the line ends, we give 2-3 possible moves for Black so that you know how to continue from there on. Leon used the lines from this course with a lot of success in practice, and you can find many of his games in the Model Games chapter.  We hope you'll enjoy studying and playing 1...d6 as much as we enjoyed making this course! }
