[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nd2
{ A very rare move, which you'll probably never see at the board. However, it's quite solid, and the plan is to go Ngf3, c3, and Bd3. }
3... e5 { We follow the Philidor plan. } 4. c3 { This is White's idea. } 4...
g6 { Here we can just fianchetto the bishop to g7. } 5. Ngf3
{ 5.dxe5  is possible, but Black is fine. For example,  5...dxe5  6.Ngf3  Qe7  7.a4  Bh6  with a balanced and symmetrical position. }
5... exd4
{ Now, this is the right moment to take, as White has committed the knight to f3. If we had taken on the previous move, White could have played Bd3 and Ne2. }
6. cxd4 Bg7 7. Bd3 { Both sides continue with their plans. } 7... O-O 8. O-O c5
{ An important move to remember − we want to activate the g7-bishop. } 9. d5
{ Otherwise, Black takes on d4. } 9... Bg4
{ Considering we transposed to some Benoni structure, we want to exchange pieces since we have less space. }
10. h3 { Forcing the trade. } 10... Bxf3 11. Nxf3 Nbd7
{ With a normal position. It's important that we traded the light-squared bishop and now we have good squares for the pieces. A sample line can go  12.Bf4  c4  13.Bxc4  Nxe4  . }
