[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.f3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. f3
{ White is defending the e4-pawn and keeps an option to go c4. This line is quite popular because it leads to different kinds of positions compared to the main move  3.Nc3  . If Black doesn't react correctly, White will gain a nice space advantage. }
3... e6
{ A very interesting rare sideline intending quick development with ...Be7 and ...O-O and later breaking with ...c5.   3...e5  is the main move and a sound alternative. }
4. Be3
{ The most flexible move, the bishop belongs here anyway. White can later decide on whether to go c4 or Nc3. }
4... Be7
{ Quick development is essential. It may look passive, but we'll get nice counterplay with ...c5. }
5. Nc3
{ The idea is to go Qd2, O-O-O, and then push on the kingside with g4, h4, and so on. }
5... O-O 6. Qd2 a6
{ Change of plans! We anticipate White's long castle, so we want to have ...b5 ready.   There is nothing wrong with the less ambitious  6...c5  7.dxc5  dxc5  8.O-O-O  Nc6  9.Qxd8+  Rxd8  10.Rxd8+  Nxd8  with an equal but quite boring position. }
7. O-O-O { White is ready to push g4. } 7... b5
{ Both sides go on with their plans. } 8. g4 b4
{ Black needs to advance quickly. Now it's a race − both sides push their pawns in front of their opponents' kings. }
9. Nce2 { Not an ideal square, but it keeps the knight in play. } 9... a5
{ We need to push and we defend b4 as well. } 10. g5
{ White is also pushing and hoping for  10...Nh5?  11.Ng3  . } 10... Nfd7
{ The only move, but useful for us − we want ...c5. } 11. h4
{ White keeps pushing, and g6 is already a threat. } 11... c5
{ Disrupting White's center, and we want to follow up with ...Nc6. } 12. g6
{ A typical Sicilian motif, speeding up the attack at the cost of a mere pawn. }
12... Nc6
{ It's probably best to ignore White's threats for now and follow our own play. The position is open to all 3 results, but we like Black's chances here. }
