[Black "1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.f3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. f3
{ White is defending the e4-pawn and keeps an option to go c4. This line is quite popular because it leads to different kinds of positions compared to the main move  3.Nc3  . If Black doesn't react correctly, White will gain a nice space advantage. }
3... e6
{ A very interesting rare sideline intending quick development with ...Be7 and ...O-O and later breaking with ...c5.   3...e5  is the main move and a sound alternative. }
4. Be3
{ The most flexible move, the bishop belongs here anyway. White can later decide on whether to go c4 or Nc3. }
4... Be7
{ Quick development is essential. It may look passive, but we'll get nice counterplay with ...c5. }
5. c4
{ This was the idea of @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.f3  . White seizes space in Sämisch style. }
5... O-O { Getting ready to play ...c5. } 6. Nc3 c5
{ Finally, we're challenging the center, intending ...cxd4 or ...Nc6. } 7. Nge2
{ White refrains from d5 for now and is ready to take on d4 with the knight. }
7... Nc6
{ We're forcing White to react in the center; otherwise, we'll go ...d5. The endgames after dxc5 are always good for us, as we cover d5 with the pawn and we have access to the d4-square. }
8. d5 { The only reasonable move. } 8... Ne5 { Attacking c4. } 9. Ng3
{ Probably the best square for the knight @@StartBracket@@until we play ...h5@@EndBracket@@. }
9... h5
{ A typical move in these kinds of positions; we want to hit the knight with...h4 and weaken White's kingside. For Black, pushing the h-pawn is not a big weakness. }
10. Be2
{ White makes room for the knight on f1 in case of ...h4. Now f4 is already a threat. }
10... exd5
{ It's essential to trade the pawns now as we open up the c8-bishop and stop White from playing f4 @@StartBracket@@we'll have ...Neg4@@EndBracket@@.   The rushed  10...h4?!  is refuted by  11.f4! }
11. cxd5 h4 { Now we go for this to dislodge the white knight. } 12. Nf5
{ Not a typical move, but it's possible here since we don't have ...g6.   12.Nf1  Ng6  leads to an unclear position, where we have ideas to prepare  the ...b5 push by ...a6, ...Bd7, ...Rb8, or ...Nh5 if White plays Nd2 @@StartBracket@@so that they don't have Qd2@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Bxf5 { We have to get rid of this dangerous knight. } 13. exf5
{ White would have a big advantage if they had time to consolidate the position. }
13... b5
{ A well-timed pawn sac! We want to create counterplay and open up the b-file as soon as possible. }
14. Bxb5
{ White has to take this pawn. Otherwise, we're going to play ...b4 or ...Nc4. }
14... Rb8
{ This is the point. The rook is actively placed on the b-file. Some of our ideas are ...Qc8 to take the f5-pawn, or ... a6 to take on b2, or even ...c4 to threaten ...Nd3. The position is very sharp, but it's much harder to play for White. }
