[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Bd3
{ This sideline is quite popular among positional players. White wants to develop with c3, Nf3, O-O and Nbd2 and play like in a Ruy-Lopez − Re1, Nf1-g3. White is staying flexible not playing Nc3, so that they can reinforce the d4-pawn with c3. }
3... e5 { The classic Philidor plan, gaining a foothold in the center. } 4. c3
{ This is the point of White's play. White wants to keep the pressure in the center and doesn't want to push d5. }
4... Nbd7
{ This rare sideline will certainly surprise your opponent. The point is to protect e5 with the knight and try to push ...d5 on the next move. If White prevents this, we can switch to the ...g6 and ...Bg7 setup.   We recommend  4...Nbd7  over  4...d5  or  4...Nc6  in order to play some fresh positions, where we can even fight for a win with Black. }
5. f4 { An aggressive move, trying to stop our idea to play ...d5. } 5... c5
{ We're trying to put pressure by playing reversed symmetry! Of course, it's a risky approach, but White has to make some decisions.   5...Be7  is possible but a bit passive, and Black will have to play dynamically later on to avoid getting suffocated. }
6. Nf3
{ The most logical move to put pressure on Black's center. White managed to get an ambitious setup, including f4, and in the longer term, is hoping for an edge. }
6... cxd4
{ We want to go ...d5, but it's useful to include ...cxd4 and cxd4, as we may have ...Bb4+. }
7. cxd4 d5
{ What a spectacular position! White has many options but none of them lead to an advantage. Our idea is to get a pawn on e4 with a fork, either by taking ...dxe4 or pushing ...e4. As it happens, this is new territory; the position hasn't been met in practice yet. }
8. fxe5
{ One of the possible captures, ignoring the fork but attacking our knight. }
8... dxe4 { The only move − we got the fork. } 9. exf6 exf3
{ Only like this; it's important to weaken the d4-pawn. } 10. fxg7
{ This is very tempting. White loses a tempo but wins a pawn. However, we bring one more piece into play.  10.Qxf3  Nxf6  11.Nc3  Be7  is fine for Black. }
10... Bxg7 11. Qxf3 O-O
{ We're a pawn down, but we managed to castle, and d4 is probably going to fall. We have ideas like ...Re8+ or ...Qh4+.   If  12.Be3  to defend the pawn, there is the strong  12...Nc5!  And if @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1n1pbp/8/8/3P4/3B1Q2/PP4PP/RNB1K2R w KQ - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.O-O  Bxd4+  13.Kh1  Ne5  , neutralizing any attacking hopes White might have had.   We like Black's chances in this position.  11...Qh4+  is also good,  trading the queens and taking the d4-pawn afterwards. }
