[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Bd3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Bd3
{ This sideline is quite popular among positional players. White wants to develop with c3, Nf3, O-O and Nbd2 and play like in a Ruy-Lopez − Re1, Nf1-g3. White is staying flexible not playing Nc3, so that they can reinforce the d4-pawn with c3. }
3... e5 { The classic Philidor plan, gaining a foothold in the center. } 4. c3
{ This is the point of White's play. White wants to keep the pressure in the center and doesn't want to push d5. }
4... Nbd7
{ This rare sideline will certainly surprise your opponent. The point is to protect e5 with the knight and try to push ...d5 on the next move. If White prevents this, we can switch to the ...g6 and ...Bg7 setup.   We recommend  4...Nbd7  over  4...d5  or  4...Nc6  in order to play some fresh positions, where we can even fight for a win with Black. }
5. Nf3
{ This is what White wants to do, continuing with the development plan. } 5...
d5
{ A timely break in the center, exploiting the fact that e4 is unprotected. This is the main point of the line. }
6. dxe5 { The other possible capture, attacking our knight. } 6... dxe4
{ The only way to go.  6...Nxe4  looks like a very bad version of the Open Spanish, as White has a nice development lead. }
7. exf6 exf3
{ We take the knight in order to have access to the e5-square with our knight. }
8. fxg7
{ The greedy approach. White is taking the pawn but, at the same time, developing our pieces. }
8... Bxg7 9. Qxf3
{ The natural move. White keeps the pawn structure intact but will have to deal with ...Ne5.   9.gxf3  looks extremely risky, neglecting development. We can follow up with  9...Qe7+  10.Be3  Bh6  with great counterplay. }
9... Ne5 { Double attack! } 10. Bb5+ { The only move to save the bishop. }
10... Bd7
{ 10...c6  11.Qg3!  is also possible, but we want to develop as quickly as possible  and bring our king to safety with ...O-O-O. }
11. Qe2
{ This is White's best reply, pinning the knight on e5 and protecting the bishop. }
11... c6
{ A smart reply, White doesn't have time to move the bishop away. It is also possible to play  11...Bxb5  . }
12. O-O { The only move; otherwise, ...Bg4 or ...Qh4 wins the game. } 12...
cxb5 13. f4 { This is how White takes the piece back. } 13... Bg4
{ This is tempting because it comes with tempo. We want to continue with ...Qd5, ...O-O-O, and ...Rhe8. Black has a good compensation for the pawn.   Other moves like  13...Qb6+  or  13...Be6  are also possible. }
