[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nge2
{ White is ready to take on d4 with the knight. There are several plans − f3, Be3 or h3, g4, Bg2 or even g3, Bg2. }
4... c6 { Trying to get ...b5. } 5. a4 { White is stopping ...b5. } 5... Be7 6.
g3 { White wants to fianchetto the bishop on g2. } 6... exd4
{ This is more precise than ...O-O followed by ...exd4, as now we can meet  7.Qxd4  with  7...d5  . }
7. Nxd4 { The more logical recapture. } 7... O-O
{ We will go ...d5 on the next move. } 8. Bg2 d5
{ This is the point. We need to break in the center before White coordinates their pieces. }
9. e5 { Gaining some space but allowing us a solid pawn chain c6-d5. } 9... Ng4
{ A concrete move − the knight is more active here than on d7. } 10. f4
{ 10.e6  fails tactically due to the positional sacrifice  10...Nxf2!  After  11.Kxf2  fxe6+  12.Nf3  Bc5+  13.Ke1  e5  ,  Black's material investment will bring dividends given the powerful center and White's miserable king on e1. }
10... f6
{ It's important to undermine White's pawn chain right away; h3 was a threat. }
11. e6
{ An attempt to complicate matters. The e6-pawn can be strong but also vulnerable. }
11... f5
{ The only move. We need the f6-square for the knight. We have ideas such as ...Bc5, ...g6 or ...Nf6. White cannot keep the e6-pawn. The position is complex, but Black is doing well. }
