1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. dxe5
{ White is trying to play for a better endgame, as our king will stay in the center. However, we're very confident in Black's resources. }
4... dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ The king in the center can be a little exposed, but it can also be an asset in the long term. If we manage to develop and coordinate our pieces, we'll get a good endgame. }
6. Bc4
{ The best and most played move. White is attacking f7 and developing with tempo. }
6... Ke8
{ Defending the pawn. We choose not to play  6...Be6  and ruin our pawn structure.  6...Bb4  is recommended by Pepe Cuenca in his Chessable course on the Philidor. It is an interesting option but more forcing.   After  6...Ke8  , there is no need to worry about  7.Nb5  , as we can count on  7...Bb4+  8.c3  Ba5  , and if  9.Nf3  a6  10.Na3  b5  11.Bd3  Nbd7  , with a fighting endgame ahead. }
7. Nf3
{ This is the most played move, developing with tempo. Black has to be careful about the Ng5 threat as well. }
7... Bd6 { Defending e5 and having ...Rf8 to defend f7. } 8. Bg5
{ Threatening to take on f6 and double the pawns. } 8... Nbd7
{ Making sure we can recapture with the knight on f6. } 9. O-O-O
{ The most ambitious move, not allowing us to play ...c6. If  9.O-O  , we can go  9...c6  and restrict  the c3-knight. It's hard now to give a standard recipe for Black, as it always depends on White's play as well.  Generally, we have the ...b5 and ...a5 ideas to expand on the queenside while playing on the other side of the board with ...h6 is also an option. The king will be nicely placed on e7, and ...Nc5 followed by either ...Ne6 or ...Be6 can be considered as well. }
9... a6 { Stopping Nb5 and preparing ...b5. } 10. a4
{ Stopping ...b5. If White plays anything else, we can go ...b5 followed by ...h6 and Black is totally fine. }
10... h6
{ A useful move to include. We want to see on which diagonal the bishop goes. If  11.Be3  , we have  11...Ng4  . }
11. Bh4 Nh5
{ This is a very rare move, but a strong one. It has several ideas like ...g5, ...f6 to shut off the bishop, or ...Nf4. Another useful move in the position is ...Rb8 to prepare ...b5. }
12. a5 { White prevents ...b5, and will try to play Ba2, Nd2-c4. } 12... Rb8
{ Always a useful move if we want to push ...b5. } 13. Ba2
{ White follows the plan and frees the c4-square in order to play Nd2-c4. }
13... f6
{ Restricting the h4-bishop. It's also good to secure the e5-pawn so that if we play ...b5, after axb6 and ...Nxb6, there is no Nxe5. }
14. Nd2 { Heading to c4. } 14... b5
{ The last accurate move, we're stopping Nc4. } 15. axb6 Nxb6
{ Again, c4 is under control. Despite the worse pawn structure on the queenside, we have active pieces. The knight can come into play on f4. }
