[Black "Philidor 4.Nf3 Nbd7 5.Rg1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. Rg1
{ The modern approach. White is preparing g4 with a kingside attack. } 5... c6
{ We make a useful move, preparing ...b5 and ...Qa5. This also diverges from Pepe's LTR, which covers  5...g6  . }
6. g4 { This is the idea of White's last move. } 6... h6
{ It's important to stop g5 in order to secure the f6-knight. } 7. h4
{ This looks tempting, but you will soon learn why we're happy to see it. }
7... exd4
{ The old principle − when your opponent plays on a flank, you react in the center. }
8. Nxd4
{ The more ambitious approach. White is one move away from playing g5. } 8...
Ne5
{ The only move, but definitely good enough. We get access to the g4-square and have ideas of playing ...d5. }
9. g5 { Just continuing to push. } 9... hxg5 { It's good to open the h-file. }
10. hxg5
{ After  10.Bxg5?!  Qb6  threatening ...Qxd4, Black is already slightly better. }
10... Nfg4 { There is no going back. } 11. f4 { Trying to win on the spot. }
11... Qb6
{ A very nice tactical way of defending, as  12.fxe5  runs into  12...dxe5  . The immediate threat  is ...Qxd4.  After  13.Rxg4  exd4  14.Nb1  , it is important to include  14...Bb4+  intermediate check to provoke  15.c3  . We'll understand soon why.  Following  15...Bxg4  16.Qxg4  Bd6  17.g6  dxc3  18.gxf7+  Kf8  19.Nxc3  Rh2  20.Qf3  Rd8  , Black has a powerful initiative. If, instead, we go for the immediate @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp3pp1/1qp5/6P1/3pP1R1/8/PPP5/RNBQKB2 b Qkq - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Bxg4  , White will suddenly get counterplay:  15.Qxg4  Bd6  16.g6  and Black isn't as fast in creating threats as in the previous variation. }
12. Be2 { The only good move, keeping an eye on the f3-square. } 12... Nh2
{ Renewing the threat of ...Qxd4. The knight is exposed on h2, but it controls important squares like f3 and g4, and it's not easy for White to attack it. }
13. Be3 { Developing and covering the g1-a7 diagonal. } 13... Neg4
{ We prefer this knight jump here, as it gives Black chances to fight for an advantage. }
14. Qd2
{ The only move.  14.Bxg4  fails to  14...Nxg4  15.Rxg4  Qxb2  , which is even stronger than  15...Bxg4  immediately; at least, that's what the engine claims. }
14... Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Rh3
{ Forcing White to trade the rooks, as  16.Qd2  runs into  16...Qxb2  with a double attack on a1 and c3. }
16. Rg3 { Forced. } 16... Rxg3 17. Qxg3 Qxd4
{ We managed to trade the h2-knight for the one on d4. } 18. Qxh2 g6
{ Black is more comfortable because of the bishop pair. } *

