[Black "Philidor 5.Bc4 Be7 6.Ng5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. Bc4
{ The most played move. White is already threatening Ng5. } 5... Be7
{ Now we can parry Ng5 with ...O-O. } 6. Ng5
{ White is going for tricks early on, but this will backfire with correct play. }
6... O-O { The only way to defend f7. } 7. Bxf7+
{ The only way to justify the early knight jump. If White doesn't go for this, the g5-knight is misplaced, and we can take on d4, for example. }
7... Rxf7 8. Ne6 { This was the point. } 8... Qe8 9. Nxc7 Qd8
{ We want to control c7 so that the knight doesn't get out. } 10. Nxa8
{ There is no repetition with Ne6 because the queen gets out to a5 or b6. White got some material but will lose the a8-knight, and we have a huge development lead. }
10... b5 { The important move to remember. This is how we get an advantage. }
11. O-O
{ This is the better option. In most of the games, White played  11.dxe5  , but then White is immediately worse after  11...Nxe5  . Of course, opening up the position is not a good idea against the minor pieces and also when you lack development. }
11... Bb7 { Targeting e4, and also we want to take the knight. } 12. f3
{ White needs to protect e4 and wants to block the position with d5. } 12... b4
{ The first step in opening up the position.  12...Qxa8  is also good. } 13.
Ne2 d5
{ The a8-knight will surely not escape, so we can stop White from playing d5 first. Black has easy play and White needs to be precise not to get a bad position. }
*

