{ One of the two options we recommend against White's setup  @@StartBracket@@  7...exd4  is the other choice, which is also covered in the course@@EndBracket@@.  We still want to take on d4, but not immediately. We will also prepare it by playing ...a5 and securing the c5-square for the knight. }
8. Re1 { This is the main move. } 8... a5
{ We make sure that White never has b4 after we take on d4 and play ...Nc5. }
9. Ba2 { A prophylactic move. Play will be similar to the 9.h3 lines. } 9...
exd4 { We stick to our original plan. } 10. Nxd4 { The principled capture. }
10... Nc5 { Just following our idea with ...Nc5 and ...Be6. } 11. Qf3
{ This was tried sometimes, but it doesn't give an advantage. } 11... Be6
{ The typical reply. } 12. Nf5 { This is the point of White's play. } 12...
Bxf5 { We need to get rid of the strong knight. } 13. Qxf5 { Forced. } 13...
Qb6 { Keeping an eye on the b2-pawn. } 14. Rb1 Qb4
{ The queen is active here, and there is a threat of ...Nxa4. } 15. Bd2 Rae8
{ Black has a good position. A sample line goes  16.e5  dxe5  17.Qxe5  Bd8  18.Qd6  Nfd7  with an equal position.   Just don't play  15...Nxa4?  right away because of  16.e5!  and White wins. }
