1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. Bc4
{ The most played move. White is already threatening Ng5. } 5... Be7
{ Now we can parry Ng5 with ...O-O. } 6. O-O O-O 7. a4
{ A good prophylactic move. White can play a5 to gain some more space on the queenside, and also after ...c6, there is no ...b5. }
7... c6
{ One of the two options we recommend against White's setup  @@StartBracket@@  7...exd4  is the other choice, which is also covered in the course@@EndBracket@@.  We still want to take on d4, but not immediately. We will also prepare it by playing ...a5 and securing the c5-square for the knight. }
8. Re1 { This is the main move. } 8... a5
{ We make sure that White never has b4 after we take on d4 and play ...Nc5. }
9. h3 { A logical move, preparing Be3. } 9... exd4
{ The time has come to take on d4. } 10. Nxd4
{ The threat is Nf5 with pressure on d6. } 10... Nc5
{ We want to finish development with ...Be6, and sometimes even ...Re8. } 11.
Ba2 { A prophylactic move, but it doesn't change our plan. } 11... Be6
{ Obviously. } 12. Bxe6
{ White wasted a tempo with Ba2 and Bxe6 but wants to go e5 next. } 12... fxe6
{ We want to open the f-file. } 13. e5 { Damaging our pawn structure. } 13...
dxe5 14. Rxe5 Bd6
{ We're activating the bishop with tempo and want to follow up with ...Nd5. }
15. Rxe6 { It's tempting to grab the pawn. } 15... Qc7
{ Going for counterplay after ...Rad8, or ...Be5 first or after ...Bh2+. Black has good compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
