[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "1.d4 d6 2.g3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. g3
{ White doesn't stop ...e5, but this is a tricky move order, and it was played several times by GM Nils Grandelius. }
2... e5
{ Considering White hasn't stopped us from doing it, we go for it! If you don't remember the details of this line, or if you want to avoid some forced variations, you can go for  2...Nf6  , and it will probably transpose to the other lines. }
3. dxe5
{ The most principled move. This is one of the best cases when White can take on e5, as there is no pawn on c4 that may be weak. }
3... dxe5 4. Qxd8+
{ Of course, White trades the queens, hoping for a better endgame. } 4... Kxd8
5. Nc3
{ This is more flexible than Bg2, as in some cases the bishop may go to h3. White intends to continue f4, or develop the bishop and go O-O-O. }
5... Nd7
{ The idea is to delay ...Nf6 for a moment so that White doesn't have Bg5. } 6.
f4
{ The critical continuation. White is intending to put a lot of pressure on the center with f4 and Nf3. }
6... Ngf6
{ We need to develop the knight quickly. If we manage to stabilize the position, we'll have a great game, but for now, we need to be precise; every tempo counts. }
7. Nf3 { Renewing the threat on e5. } 7... exf4
{ We must go for this; otherwise, we get a worse position.  7...Bd6  doesn't work because of  8.Nb5  . }
8. Bxf4
{ White is playing for a quick development but leaves weaknesses in the pawn structure. }
8... Bb4 { We want to take the knight before it comes to b5. } 9. O-O-O
{ Continuing the quick development. } 9... Bxc3
{ Destroying White's pawn structure even more. } 10. bxc3 Ne4
{ The knight is great here, and it's keeping our position together. White still has some lead in development, but in the longer term, we can take advantage of the weak pawn structure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "1.d4 d6 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. Nf3 { White is stopping ...e5 and does not want to commit to e4 yet. } 2...
Nf6
{ Now we stop e4, and we want to play ...g6 and ...Bg7 and reach a King's Indian where White's options are limited because the knight is already on f3. }
3. g3
{ White is going for the King's Indian Fianchetto. You will see this very often especially when playing positional players. White wants to play for a small advantage with no risk. }
3... g6 { Following the King's Indian plan to fianchetto the bishop. } 4. Bg2
Bg7 5. O-O
{ White completed kingside development and will decide between several different setups like c4, b3, Re1, or Nc3. }
5... O-O
{ We finished kingside development, and now we'll see what plan White will choose. It is also possible to play the rare  5...Bf5!?  , but in most cases, it could just transpose. }
6. Nc3 { Preparing e4. } 6... Nbd7 { The usual setup − we're going for ...e5. }
7. e4 e5 8. a4
{ It's useful for White to include this move. White wants to continue with a5 and gain some space on the queenside.   8.Re1  c6  9.a4  a5  would transpose. }
8... a5
{ We're stopping White from playing a5. We want to follow up with ...c6 and ...Re8. }
9. Re1
{ It was possible to reach this position via multiple different move orders. }
9... c6
{ It's also possible to play this position in another way, with  9...b6  and ... Bb7. }
10. h3 { Preparing Be3. } 10... exd4 { Now it's the right time. } 11. Nxd4 Re8
{ The rook is useful on the open file. } 12. Bf4 { Attacking the pawn on d6. }
12... Nb6
{ An important move to remember − we want to break through with ...d5. } *

