[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. Nf3 { White is stopping ...e5 and does not want to commit to e4 yet. } 2...
Nf6
{ Now we stop e4, and we want to play ...g6 and ...Bg7 and reach a King's Indian where White's options are limited because the knight is already on f3. }
3. g3
{ White is going for the King's Indian Fianchetto. You will see this very often especially when playing positional players. White wants to play for a small advantage with no risk. }
3... g6 { Following the King's Indian plan to fianchetto the bishop. } 4. Bg2
Bg7 5. O-O
{ White completed kingside development and will decide between several different setups like c4, b3, Re1, or Nc3. }
5... O-O
{ We finished kingside development, and now we'll see what plan White will choose. It is also possible to play the rare  5...Bf5!?  , but in most cases, it could just transpose. }
6. b3
{ This was also possible to reach via @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3P4/5NP1/PPP1PPBP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.b3  b5  .  White wants to go for a double fianchetto after Bb2.   6.a4  a5  would most likely transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/3P4/5NP1/PPP1PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Re1  or  6.Nc3  , as  we'll play ...Nbd7 and ...e5, while White will play Nc3 and e4. }
6... b5
{ We also want to go for the double fianchetto, and we seize some space on the queenside. White cannot make good use of the discovered attack on the h1-a8 diagonal. }
7. Bb2
{ The most played move in the position. However, it doesn't prevent our plan.  7.Qd3  can be met by  7...a6  . }
7... Bb7
{ Now White doesn't have tricks on the long diagonal anymore. We want to continue with ...Nbd7. }
8. Nbd2 { White brings the last piece into play. } 8... Nbd7
{ We're also finishing development. We're ready to play ...c5. } 9. c4
{ Seizing some space in the center. } 9... bxc4
{ This is necessary. We want to open the b-file for the rook, and if White takes with the knight, we can go ...a5, stopping Na5. }
10. Nxc4
{ The most often played move, but it gives Black easy moves and active play. }
10... a5
{ Making sure the white knight never gets to a5, and preparing ...a4 at the right moment. }
11. Rc1
{ White activates the rook on the semi-open file.  11.a4  wouldn't change our plan. We go  11...Ra6  with the same ideas. }
11... Ra6
{ The idea is to go ...Qa8, ... c5, ...Rb8, ...a4 with a nice counterplay on the queenside.   11...c5  played in Carlsen-Meier 2019 is also fine, but the text move is more ambitious. }
