[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "London/Jobava Setups 2.Bf4 Nd7 3.Nf3 Ngf6 4.e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. Bf4
{ Very often, White players go for the London setup against everything. Considering we play ...d6, we're immediately trying to exploit White's setup by getting ...e5 with tempo. }
2... Nd7 { Preparing ...e5 at the right moment. } 3. Nf3
{ White parries ...e5 and develops the pieces. } 3... Ngf6
{ Considering we can't play ...e5 anymore, we switch to the ...c5 idea. We're also stopping e4 for now. }
4. e3
{ A normal development move, but now we can get the dark-squared bishop. } 4...
Nh5
{ Of course, we go for it since the bishop has no squares to retreat. That's why in the London systems, White usually includes h3 before. }
5. Bg5
{ White is trying to get a better version of the trade. If Bg3 or any other move, we can just capture the bishop without having to weaken our pawn structure. }
5... h6 { We go hunting down the bishop. } 6. Bh4 g5
{ Completing the strategic idea. } 7. Bg3 { The most natural move. } 7... Bg7
{ There is no need to take on g3 yet, as the bishop has nowhere to go. In the meantime, we can complete development with ...e6 and ...Qe7. }
8. Bd3 { White is also developing their pieces. } 8... e6
{ This looks like a good idea to make room for the queen to e7. } 9. Nbd2 Qe7
{ Black is slightly preferable because we'll get the bishop pair. Black has two plans − one is to go ...f5 and ...O-O; the other one is ...b6 and ...Bb7. White has good control over the center, but in the long term, the bishop pair may come in handy. }
*

