[Black "London/Jobava Setups 2.Bf4 Nd7 3.Nf3 Ngf6 4.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. Bf4
{ Very often, White players go for the London setup against everything. Considering we play ...d6, we're immediately trying to exploit White's setup by getting ...e5 with tempo. }
2... Nd7 { Preparing ...e5 at the right moment. } 3. Nf3
{ White parries ...e5 and develops the pieces. } 3... Ngf6
{ Considering we can't play ...e5 anymore, we switch to the ...c5 idea. We're also stopping e4 for now. }
4. Nc3
{ This is an ambitious and concrete move. White is already threatening to play e4 and take full control over the center. }
4... c5
{ We have to react quickly in the center; otherwise, we just get suffocated. }
5. d5
{ The principled reply, seizing some space and renewing the threat of e4. }
5... Qa5
{ It's important to remember this move. Although usually it's not recommended to move the queen early in the game, we're stopping e4 and preparing ...Ne4 or ...b5 to seize some space. }
6. a4
{ Probably the best move, stopping ...b5. If  6.Nd2  or  6.Bd2  , we just go  6...b5  with a good position. Afterwards, we can fianchetto the bishop  with ...g6 and ...Bg7.   Even  6.Qd3  doesn't stop  6...b5  because the d5-pawn is hanging after the queen trade. }
6... Ne4 { White can stop one of our ideas but not both. } 7. Qd3
{ The critical move. If  7.Bd2  , we can just take  7...Nxd2  followed by ...g6 and ...Bg7 with a pleasant position. }
7... f5
{ The best move, although it looks risky. We are supporting the strong knight on e4. Given time, we want ...g6 and ...Bg7 to reinforce the pressure on the c3-knight. }
8. Bd2 { A safe move, which is likely to be seen in practice. } 8... Nxd2
{ Of course, we always capture the bishop pair. } 9. Nxd2
{ The knight is heading for c4. } 9... g6 { In order to activate the bishop. }
10. Nc4 { Chasing the queen away, and hoping for ...Qc7 and ...Qd8. } 10... Qb4
{ It is important to keep the queen active and be prepared against e4. Don't worry, White cannot trap the queen. }
11. Ra3 { Trying to trap the queen anyway. } 11... Nb6
{ The most precise move. The queen is saved, and Black enjoys a nice position because of the strong dark-squared bishop on the long diagonal. }
