[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "KID 5.e4 Bg4 6.Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. Nf3 { White is stopping ...e5 and does not want to commit to e4 yet. } 2...
Nf6
{ Now we stop e4, and we want to play ...g6 and ...Bg7 and reach a King's Indian where White's options are limited because the knight is already on f3. }
3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4
{ By far the main line of the King's Indian Defense, seizing the whole center. }
5... Bg4
{ This is the move we recommend. We chose a sideline with a clear strategic plan, in which, with precise play, White will be a bit better, but Black will always have good winning chances. We aim for positions where the center gets blocked after ...e5 and d5, and we trade the light-squared bishop for the knight. }
6. Be3 { One of the two main moves, reinforcing d4. } 6... Nc6
{ Quite a rare move, so again, we'll benefit from the surprise element. The idea is to go ...e5 and fight for the center. In some lines, we'll need to sacrifice a pawn for piece activity. }
7. Be2
{ This was played in almost all the games. White is just completing development. }
7... Bxf3
{ We follow our strategic idea − we trade the bishop for the knight and fight for the d4-square.   We can also switch the move order and play  7...e5  8.d5  Bxf3  9.Bxf3  Nd4  which transposes. }
8. Bxf3 e5
{ Fighting for the d4-square. We need to do this now; otherwise, White can go d5. }
9. d5 { The only way to fight for an advantage. } 9... Nd4
{ Active play is required. We're sacrificing a pawn to make our dark-squared bishop extremely strong. Any other knight retreat would lead to a strategically lost position. }
10. Bxd4 { White takes the pawn at once but gives up the strong bishop. } 10...
exd4 11. Qxd4
{ White's queen is exposed on d4, but we don't have a good way to take advantage of it. }
11... O-O { Threatening ...Nxe4. } 12. O-O
{ 12.Qd2  doesn't change anything, as we can go  12...Nd7  13.O-O  Qf6  and transpose. }
12... Nd7
{ Opening up the bishop. Our minor pieces are more active than White's. } 13.
Qd2 { The most logical square for the queen. } 13... Qf6
{ Reinforcing the pressure on the long diagonal. } 14. Rac1
{ A prophylactic move, defending the c3-knight. The idea is to meet  14...Nc5  with  15.b4  .  Also, Bg4 is a threat. }
14... h5 { A useful move, stopping Bg4. } 15. Bd1
{ White is rerouting the bishop and prepares f4 while also making sure ...Re8 doesn't work due to Ba4. }
15... Qd4 { Offering a queen trade. } 16. Qxd4
{ White hopes to grind out a long endgame being a pawn up. If  16.Qe2  , we can go  16...a6  to stop Nb5, then ...Nc5 and so on. Black has good compensation for the pawn. }
16... Bxd4
{ Even though we're a pawn down, we have compensation due to our active pieces. The idea is to go ...Nc5 to put pressure on e4. If allowed, even ...h4 and ...Kg7 can be interesting. }
