[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "KID 5.e4 Bg4 6.Be2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. Nf3 { White is stopping ...e5 and does not want to commit to e4 yet. } 2...
Nf6
{ Now we stop e4, and we want to play ...g6 and ...Bg7 and reach a King's Indian where White's options are limited because the knight is already on f3. }
3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4
{ By far the main line of the King's Indian Defense, seizing the whole center. }
5... Bg4
{ This is the move we recommend. We chose a sideline with a clear strategic plan, in which, with precise play, White will be a bit better, but Black will always have good winning chances. We aim for positions where the center gets blocked after ...e5 and d5, and we trade the light-squared bishop for the knight. }
6. Be2
{ The main and most logical move. White wants to recapture with the bishop on f3. }
6... Bxf3
{ This is the strategic point of the line. We get rid of the knight in order to go ...e5 afterwards. }
7. Bxf3
{ The natural recapture, not spoiling the pawn structure. It was played in almost all the games. }
7... e5 { We're fighting for the center and we want to play ...Nc6. } 8. dxe5
{ Considering we haven't castled, White is hoping for a favorable endgame since our king is in the center. }
8... dxe5 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ The endgame is fine for Black, but still, some accuracy is required. } 10.
Be3
{ A logical move. The bishop controls the d4-square, and White wants to go O-O-O next. }
10... h5
{ An important move, stopping g4-g5 ideas and also preparing ...Bh6 to trade the bishops. }
11. O-O-O+ Nbd7
{ We parry the check by developing a piece. We want to follow up with ...c6 to stop Nd5 or ...Bh6 to trade the bishops. }
12. Nd5
{ White goes for this while they still can; otherwise, the knight will be restricted by the c6-pawn. }
12... Nxd5 { The easiest solution is to just trade this knight. } 13. cxd5
{ If  13.Rxd5  , we continue with  13...c6  and ...Kc7, with an equal position. }
13... Bh6
{ We trade the dark-squared bishops, which leaves us with a good knight vs. a bad bishop. We already prefer Black's position. }
