[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "KID 5.e4 Bg4 6.Be2 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. Nf3 { White is stopping ...e5 and does not want to commit to e4 yet. } 2...
Nf6
{ Now we stop e4, and we want to play ...g6 and ...Bg7 and reach a King's Indian where White's options are limited because the knight is already on f3. }
3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4
{ By far the main line of the King's Indian Defense, seizing the whole center. }
5... Bg4
{ This is the move we recommend. We chose a sideline with a clear strategic plan, in which, with precise play, White will be a bit better, but Black will always have good winning chances. We aim for positions where the center gets blocked after ...e5 and d5, and we trade the light-squared bishop for the knight. }
6. Be2
{ The main and most logical move. White wants to recapture with the bishop on f3. }
6... Bxf3
{ This is the strategic point of the line. We get rid of the knight in order to go ...e5 afterwards. }
7. Bxf3
{ The natural recapture, not spoiling the pawn structure. It was played in almost all the games. }
7... e5 { We're fighting for the center and we want to play ...Nc6. } 8. d5
{ The logical move, stopping ...Nc6. } 8... h5
{ Without this move, our strategy makes no sense. We will get rid of the dark-squared bishop by playing ...Bh6. }
9. Qb3
{ The most dangerous move, but not an obvious one. White's idea is to provoke ...b6 so that we don't have ...c6 in the future @@StartBracket@@White can just take dxc6@@EndBracket@@. The worst white piece  (the light-squared bishop)  can come to d1-a4 in the future if we have b6 on the board.   The moves  9.Rb1  and  9.b3  were also played, but they don't pose problems and we just continue with our  plan: ...Nbd7 followed by ...Bh6. }
9... Qc8
{ We don't want to weaken our position with ...b6. We want to follow up with ...Nbd7-c5 and claim that the b3-queen is exposed. }
10. a4
{ White's idea is to go a5 to gain space on the queenside. If White plays something else, we can go ...Nbd7 and ...Bh6 to continue our normal plan. }
10... a5
{ Stopping White's counterplay and threatening to stabilize the position on the queenside after ...Nbd7. }
11. c5
{ The point of White's play; otherwise, White would be in a strategically bad position after ...Nbd7 and ...Bh6. }
11... Nbd7
{ With this move, we'll put the knight to c5 where it will be very strong.   Surprisingly, after  11...dxc5  , White has a much better position. White will castle long, and the queenside is blocked. Afterwards, White can prepare to push on the kingside, and we lack counterplay. A sample line goes  12.Be3  Nbd7  13.O-O-O  O-O  , which was seen in ½-½ Bhambure-Nevednichy, Sitges 2022, and here White gets an advantage after  14.Be2  . }
12. cxd6 { The logical continuation, creating a weakness on d6. } 12... cxd6
13. Nb5
{ Very tempting, immediately attacking our pawn. Instead,  13.Be3  would lead to similar positions after  13...Nc5  14.Qc2  Ke7  . }
13... Ke7
{ Obviously! The king is safe on e7, defending the pawn on d6. We intend to follow up with ...Nc5 and ...Bh6 if possible. }
14. O-O
{ White finishes development, leaving the c1-bishop on the starting position so that after ...Bh6, White will be a tempo up. }
14... Nc5 { Attacking the queen and making room for our queen to go to d7. }
15. Qc2
{ A natural retreat. Other moves like  15.Qa3  are possible, but our plan remains the same:  15...Qd7  16.Be3  Rhc8  17.Rac1  b6  followed by ...Kf8. }
15... Qd7 { We are ready to put a rook to c8 and keep options to play ...Bh6. }
16. Be3 { Pressuring the c5-knight. } 16... Rhc8
{ The problem with ...Bh6 is that White could take it and play Qd2-g5 with an annoying pin. That's why we put this rook on c8, and we can follow up with ...Kf8-g8-h7. The king will be safer there and supporting ...Bh6.  Black has no real weaknesses, and the queenside is fairly closed. We are hoping for an advantage in the endgame if we manage to exchange the dark-squared bishops. }
