[Black "English Rat Defense 1.d4 d6 2.c4 e5 3.Nc3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. c4
{ White's idea is to play Nc3 and e4, and delay the development of the knight to f3. We are already happy to see this because it allows us to play ...e5. }
2... e5
{ Of course, we go for this. The whole point of ...d6 is to go ...e5 whenever possible and control the center. }
3. Nc3
{ This move was popular back in the day. White is trying to go for a quick development. However, people understood recently that Black is totally fine, but we need to be precise. }
3... exd4 { We take the pawn because our next move will come with tempo. } 4.
Qxd4 Nc6
{ This is our idea, forcing White to move the queen again. By putting the knight on c6, we won't have such good control over d5 in the longer term, so that's why we need to act quickly. }
5. Qd2
{ The most natural retreat; the queen is already developed here. White's idea is to go b3, Bb2 and get a grip on the position. }
5... Nf6
{ An important move to remember, but also the most logical one.  5...g6  allows White to achieve their setup after  6.b3  . In some  lines, we need the bishop to go to b4, as you will see further on. }
6. b3
{ The main line by far. White wants to develop the bishop on b2 quickly and defends the c4-pawn in advance to be ready for ...Be6. }
6... a5
{ We need to create immediate problems for White without allowing a grip after Bb2. We're already threatening ...a4. }
7. Bb2
{ White holds on to their idea − e4 and Rd1 would be the next useful moves. }
7... a4
{ Continuing our idea and setting a trap because the pawn cannot really be taken. }
8. Nxa4
{ This is tempting, and it happens in many internet games. White wants to get rid of the annoying pawn. However, now Black is much better. }
8... d5
{ This is the point. We break open the center with multiple threats like ...Ne4, ...Rxa4, or ...Bb4. We can see why it was useful to keep the bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal. }
9. cxd5
{ The only move for White. All the other moves lose immediately; for example,  9.Nc3?  loses a piece after  9...d4! }
9... Rxa4 { A nice move, although  9...Ne4  or  9...Qxd5  is also good. } 10.
a3
{ The only move not to lose on the spot. We must credit White's resourcefulness in defense if they find this over the board. White parries ...Bb4 and both the c6-knight and the a4-rook are hanging. }
10... Rb4
{ We couldn't resist not making this fun move! It's quite a rare opportunity to play such a move in a game. Black is doing well after  11.dxc6  Qxd2+  12.Kxd2  Ne4+  with an initiative.   Objectively  10...Ne4  11.Qd3  Nc5  12.Qd1  Re4  is probably best due to  13.dxc6?  Nd3+  . }
