{ White's idea is to play Nc3 and e4, and delay the development of the knight to f3. We are already happy to see this because it allows us to play ...e5. }
2... e5
{ Of course, we go for this. The whole point of ...d6 is to go ...e5 whenever possible and control the center. }
3. Nf3
{ The main move, immediately putting pressure on e5. This is more likely what stronger players will do. }
3... e4
{ We accept the challenge and chase away the knight; it would have been too passive to defend the e5-pawn. }
4. Nfd2 { A more passive approach, but the knight is not exposed here. } 4...
f5 { We seize space and protect e4, intending ...Nf6. } 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. e3
{ White is preparing f3 already. } 6... c5
{ After this move, the knight on d2 remains passive, and we're fighting for control of the center.  6...Be7  is also fine, but it allows  7.f3  . }
7. Be2
{ The only move that makes sense, although the other two moves  @@StartBracket@@  7.Nb3  and  7.d5  @@EndBracket@@ are more frequently played. }
7... Nc6 { We're putting pressure on d4, developing at the same time. } 8. Nb3
{ White defends the pawn on d4. } 8... b6
{ 8...Be7  was seen in most of the games, but we want to stay flexible and keep ideas to  play ...g6 and ...Bg7 with the c5-pawn being defended. }
9. O-O g6
{ An ambitious approach. Black wants to have the bishop on the best diagonal. }
10. f3 { Obviously, White has to do something quickly. } 10... Bg7
{ It's important to finish development as soon as possible. } 11. fxe4 fxe4
{ We're going to castle on the next move, with a good position. If  12.Nd2  , we castle anyway  12...O-O  because if White takes on e4, the d4-pawn is hanging in the end.  In case of  13.d5  Ne5  14.Ndxe4  , Black can choose to give another pawn for initiative with  14...Bd7  or opt for the immediate  14...Nxe4  15.Rxf8+  Qxf8  16.Nxe4  Qe7  , which also offers plenty of play for the material investment.  White's pieces have a tough time developing, and ...Nxc4 is a threat that needs to be addressed. }
