[Black "English Rat Defense 1.d4 d6 2.c4 e5 3.Nf3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. c4
{ White's idea is to play Nc3 and e4, and delay the development of the knight to f3. We are already happy to see this because it allows us to play ...e5. }
2... e5
{ Of course, we go for this. The whole point of ...d6 is to go ...e5 whenever possible and control the center. }
3. Nf3
{ The main move, immediately putting pressure on e5. This is more likely what stronger players will do. }
3... e4
{ We accept the challenge and chase away the knight; it would have been too passive to defend the e5-pawn. }
4. Ng5
{ The most played continuation, trying to keep the knight active. However, it has its drawbacks, as we'll be able to gain some tempi with ...Be7 or ...h6, attacking the knight. }
4... f5
{ We support the e4-pawn.  4...Nf6  is not so good because White can attack  the e4-pawn with  5.Nc3  Qe7  6.Qc2  . }
5. Nc3
{ White plays a normal developing move. Here, the knight controls good squares in the center. }
5... c6
{ This is a flexible move; we keep the c3-knight in check. In the future, we can even play ...d5. }
6. Nh3
{ White is rerouting the knight to f4 and is also trying to play Bg5 in some lines. }
6... Nf6
{ Continuing our development and preparing ...d5 later on.  6...Be7  is also possible, with the idea to  avoid Bg5. However, we are not impressed with White's plan of Bg5. }
7. e3
{ White chooses to leave the bishop behind the pawns, hoping it will be more active on b2 in the future. }
7... Be7 { Normal development.  7...g6  would weaken our kingside. } 8. Nf4 Na6
{ That's the way to develop the knight; ...O-O will be a useful move. We also want to go ...Nc7-e6, but White will reply d5. }
9. h4
{ White secures the knight on f4 and gains some space on the kingside.  9.Be2  is possible, but besides  9...O-O  we can even consider  9...g5  . }
9... O-O
{ We first bring the king to safety, and then we can follow with ...Nc7-e6. }
10. Be2 { This was played most often. } 10... d5
{ The right moment to go for this, as White spent a tempo on Be2 already, so it's a worse version of taking on a6. If allowed, our next move is ...Nc7 followed by ...Bd6, hitting the f4-knight with a great position.   The immediate  10...Nc7  is also possible, but White has  11.d5  . }
11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Qb3 { White attacks the pawn but leaves our a6-knight. }
12... Nc7 { The knight is ideally placed here, defending the d5-pawn. } 13.
Ncxd5
{ The only attempt for an advantage, counting on Bc4. After the more restrained  13.Bd2  , we can go for the typical maneuver  13...Bd6  14.Rc1  Bxf4  15.exf4  Ne6  with a good position. Note that  14.Nfxd5?  would be a blunder, as after  14...Nfxd5  15.Nxd5  Be6  16.Bc4  b5  , we win a piece. }
13... Nfxd5
{ It's better to capture with this knight, as the c7-knight supports ...b5 in the future. }
14. Bc4 { This is the whole point, pinning our knight. } 14... Kh8
{ We move away from the pin. } 15. Nxd5
{ If  15.Bxd5  , then  15...Bd6  16.Bc4  b5  is good for Black. } 15... b5
{ Opening up the position. } 16. Nxe7
{ Forced, as after  16.Nxc7  bxc4  17.Qxc4  Rb8  , White's pieces are awfully placed. }
16... bxc4 17. Qa3
{ The only move, defending the knight. On b4 the queen would have been more exposed. }
17... Bb7
{ Taking away the c6-square for the knight, hoping to trap it with ...Rf7, or ...Qd7 and ...Rae8. Black has a great position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "English Opening 1.c4 d6 2.Nc3 e5 3.g3"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English Opening. This move fights for the center, and also allows White more flexible setups. }
1... d6 { We're not impressed. We go  1...d6  against everything. } 2. Nc3
{ A flexible move. White keeps the option to play g3 followed by Bg2 or push the pawns in the center.  2.g3  or  2.Nf3  would surely transpose to the lines in the course after  2...e5  . }
2... e5
{ The main point of 1...d6. We gain a foothold in the center and want to follow up with ...f5. }
3. g3
{ The typical English setup. White develops the bishop on g2 to put pressure on our position. }
3... f5 { Whenever possible, we get this setup. } 4. Bg2
{ White continues with the typical English setup. There are many transpositions in this chapter, as White has different ways to reach the desired setups. If  4.Nf3  , we can go  4...Be7  . }
4... Be7
{ Our plan is to go ...Nf6, ...O-O, ...Qe8, ...c6, and so on.  4...Nf6  is the most played move and leads to the same thing. }
5. Nf3
{ White wants to castle as quickly as possible and is not afraid of ...e4 as long as the d4-square is available for the knight. }
5... Nf6 { The same plan as always. } 6. O-O
{ White keeps the options to go d3 or d4 open. } 6... O-O 7. d3
{ This position can be reached via different move orders. So far, both sides are following their setup on their side of the board. }
7... Qe8
{ The most played move in the position. The queen is heading towards h5. We want to follow up with ...c6, ...Na6.   7...a5  is a good move as well, but White could have  played b4 the previous moves. }
8. b4 { The typical plan, seizing space on the queenside. } 8... a6
{ We want to delay b5, considering that now White has to play a4 and Rb1/Bb2 and then b5.   8...Qh5  is tempting with the idea to get an attack  after ...f4, but White can respond with  9.e3!  ,  intending Nd2 to swap the queens. So it's better to keep the queen on e8 for now.   Also,  8...c6  doesn't stop  9.b5  . On the contrary, it enhances it since we've just weakened  the a8-h1 diagonal, very much to the happiness of the bishop on g2. White is given scope on the queenside and can start increasing the pressure with Rb1, bxc6, Qa4, etc. }
9. a4 { White keeps pushing on the queenside. } 9... h6
{ We want to play ...Be6, and it's important that White doesn't have Ng5. } 10.
Bb2 { White is preparing b5. } 10... Be6
{ Putting the bishop on the best square, and intending ...c6, ...Nbd7, ...Qh5 and ...f4. }
11. b5 { White just pushes. } 11... c6
{ We take control of the d5-square and restrict the g2-bishop a bit. If possible, we want to go ...Nbd7 next. If White stops us by playing  12.Nd2  , we go  12...f4  with attacking possibilities. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Nimzo-Larsen Attack 1.b3"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3 d6 { We intend to play ...e5 and shut off the bishop. } 2. Bb2
{ If White continues  2.d4  , we play  2...e5  . } 2... e5 3. d4
{ A very rare sideline. White tries to open up the bishop immediately but, in return, gives us a tempo with ...Nc6. }
3... exd4 { It's good to open up the center; ...Nc6 will be next. } 4. Qxd4
{ Taking like this keeps more options open. } 4... Nc6
{ We develop with tempo. } 5. Qd2
{ The natural retreat, intending Nc3 and O-O-O. } 5... d5
{ Usually, it's not good to move a pawn twice in the opening, but here we gain some space. Also, our dark-squared bishop could go to b4. }
6. Nc3
{ White continues their plan, hoping for  6...d4  , when after  7.Nb5  ,  the d4-pawn could become a target. }
6... Nf6 { Not falling for the trap and defending the pawn. } 7. O-O-O
{ Renewing the threat. } 7... Be6
{ Again, defending the pawn and developing a piece. } 8. e4
{ The most critical continuation. White opens up the center while still having a lead in development. }
8... Nxe4 { The most forcing continuation, getting rid of the knights. } 9.
Nxe4 dxe4 10. Qe3
{ Other queen moves don't make much of a difference because we can play ...Bd6 anyway. This is what White was counting on in order to get the pawn back and also try to take advantage of our king in the center. }
10... Bd6
{ A good developing move, and counting on a small trap: if  11.Bxg7?  , there is  11...Ba3+!  and Black wins. }
11. Qxe4 { White takes the pawn back. } 11... Qg5+
{ Now we take advantage of our development by means of this move. } 12. Kb1
O-O-O
{ This was our idea. The king is safe on c8 and the rook suddenly becomes active on d8. We already prefer Black. }
13. Nf3 { White develops with tempo. } 13... Qa5
{ One of the several good retreats for the queen. We want the queen close to the white king in order to create some threats, like ...Nb4 or ...Bf5. }
*

