1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. Nf3 Nf6 { Attacking the e4-pawn. } 3. Nc3 { Defending the e4-pawn. } 3... e5
{ We're getting our Philidor setup. } 4. Bc4
{ Of course,  4.d4  here and on the next moves would transpose to the Philidor. }
4... Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. d3
{ White is trying to play some kind of an Italian with the knight on c3. } 6...
Be6 { We're getting rid of White's active bishop. } 7. Bxe6
{ Let's see what happens if White weakens our structure.   If  7.a4  , we'll follow up with  7...c6  with the idea ...d5.  And if @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/ppp1bppp/3pbn2/4p3/2B1P3/2NP1N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Re1  , we can just take  7...Bxc4  8.dxc4  Nbd7  and the knight gets  to c5.   After  7.Re1  , we can no longer count on  7...c6  in view of  8.Bxe6  fxe6  9.d4  exd4  10.Nxd4  Qd7  11.e5!  , which is now  possible thanks to the rook on e1. }
7... fxe6 { The doubled pawns are controlling the central squares nicely. } 8.
Ne2 { Trying to regroup with Ng3 and c3. } 8... c5
{ We want to seize more space in the center and stop d4. We want to follow up with ...Nc6, ...Qd7, and so on. Black is doing great. }
