[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) 1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Bd3 and 3.f3"]
[Black "1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Bd3 e5 4.Nf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Bd3
{ This sideline is quite popular among positional players. White wants to develop with c3, Nf3, O-O and Nbd2 and play like in a Ruy-Lopez − Re1, Nf1-g3. White is staying flexible not playing Nc3, so that they can reinforce the d4-pawn with c3. }
3... e5 { The classic Philidor plan, gaining a foothold in the center. } 4. Nf3
{ Reinforcing the d4-pawn and keeping the c3-square for the knight. Usually White plays c3, but this move is also playable.   4.Ne2  leads to the same thing because we take on d4:  4...exd4  . }
4... exd4
{ Considering that White cannot recapture with a pawn, it's a good idea to take. }
5. Nxd4 g6 { Now the bishop will be better placed on the long diagonal. } 6.
O-O
{ Always a useful move. White can decide afterwards how to develop their pieces. }
6... Bg7 7. Nc3
{ The knight belongs here. This is the most promising option for White.   7.c4  reinforces the grip in the center but gives up control  over the d4-square. After  7...O-O  8.Nc3  Nc6  ,  the knight on d4 is loose, and we'll be able to attack the white pawns. }
7... O-O { We want to follow up with ...Re8. } 8. Bg5
{ The critical line. White hopes to get the initiative quickly by going Kh1 and f4. }
8... h6 { It's useful to include this. } 9. Bh4 { White keeps the pin. } 9...
c6
{ We stop  10.f4?  for now, in view of  10...Qb6  11.Bf2  Ng4  . At the same time,  we want to push ...b5 and get counterplay on the queenside. }
10. Kh1
{ White gets ready to play f4.  10.a4  was also possible to stop ...b5. However, we're in time to get enough counterplay after  10...Re8  11.Kh1  d5!  12.exd5  cxd5  followed by ...Nc6. }
10... b5
{ Following the plan. Sometimes we want to play ...b4 to remove the knight from the center. }
11. f4 { Threatening e5, either immediately or after Nf3. } 11... Qc7
{ An important move to get out of the pin, stop e5, and defend c6 so that we can play ...Nbd7. White keeps some attacking chances, so we need to play accurately for the next few moves. }
12. Qf3
{ With the idea to have e5 after ...Nbd7 and exploit the weak c6-pawn. White wants to follow up with Rae1 and then e5. }
12... a6
{ We defend the b5-pawn, which is important in the line ...Nbd7 and e5. We want to follow up with ...Nbd7, and then we may have ideas to play ...c5. }
13. Rae1
{ Finally White is ready for e5.  13.e5?  is bad in view of  13...dxe5  14.fxe5  Ng4! }
13... Nbd7
{ We prevent e5, and our next moves could be ...b4 or ...Bb7. The position remains extremely sharp, but Black can easily take over if White doesn't react quickly. }
