[White "2) 1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Bd3 and 3.f3"]
[Black "1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Bd3 e5 4.d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Bd3
{ This sideline is quite popular among positional players. White wants to develop with c3, Nf3, O-O and Nbd2 and play like in a Ruy-Lopez − Re1, Nf1-g3. White is staying flexible not playing Nc3, so that they can reinforce the d4-pawn with c3. }
3... e5 { The classic Philidor plan, gaining a foothold in the center. } 4. d5
{ It might be tempting to seize space. However, we have a great version of the King's Indian Defense. }
4... Nbd7
{ The knight is heading to c5 to attack e4 and take the bishop on d3. } 5. Be3
{ In case of ...Nc5, White wants to take the knight and destroy our structure. }
5... c6 { Undermining the center. } 6. c4 Qa5+
{ The idea is to follow up with ...Nc5 without spoiling our pawn structure. }
7. Nc3
{ A normal developing move. White shouldn't trade the queens with  7.Qd2  , as after  7...Qxd2+  8.Nxd2  Ng4  9.Bg5  , Black is already for choice. One way to enjoy the position is  9...Be7  10.Bxe7  Kxe7  11.Ne2  Nc5  12.Bc2  a5  , with a slightly better endgame. }
7... Nc5
{ That is the point. Both the e4-pawn and the d3-bishop are attacked. } 8. f3
{ White consolidates the e4-pawn. } 8... cxd5
{ Sooner or later we need to take on d5, and this is a good moment to do this. With this, we want to determine the pawn structure in the center and open up the c-file. }
9. cxd5 Nxd3+ { We need to take the bishop as we lack space. } 10. Qxd3
{ Threatening Qb5+. } 10... Bd7
{ It's important to stop Qb5+. The plan is to go ...Be7, ...O-O, and then play ...Rfc8. We'll be able to reroute the e7-bishop to d8 and b6. Another plan would be to keep the rook on f8 and go ...Nh5 and ...f5. The position is balanced. }
