[Black "1.e4 d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Bd3 e5 4.c3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Bd3
{ This sideline is quite popular among positional players. White wants to develop with c3, Nf3, O-O and Nbd2 and play like in a Ruy-Lopez − Re1, Nf1-g3. White is staying flexible not playing Nc3, so that they can reinforce the d4-pawn with c3. }
3... e5 { The classic Philidor plan, gaining a foothold in the center. } 4. c3
{ This is the point of White's play. White wants to keep the pressure in the center and doesn't want to push d5. }
4... Nbd7
{ This rare sideline will certainly surprise your opponent. The point is to protect e5 with the knight and try to push ...d5 on the next move. If White prevents this, we can switch to the ...g6 and ...Bg7 setup.   We recommend  4...Nbd7  over  4...d5  or  4...Nc6  in order to play some fresh positions, where we can even fight for a win with Black. }
5. Ne2
{ Not the best place for the knight. However, White is better prepared against ...d5 and keeps options to play f4 later on. }
5... g6
{ We can be more ambitious here, considering the knight is misplaced on e2. We'll get a sound setup with the bishop on the long diagonal.   5...d5  is enough for equality, for example  6.exd5  Nxd5  7.O-O  Be7  8.Nd2  O-O  and so on. }
6. O-O Bg7 7. f4
{ The main move. Other moves are also possible, but it's hard to believe that White has something because we have the idea to go ...O-O, ...Re8, and ...d5.   If  7.Bg5  , we can go  7...h6  8.Bh4  g5  9.Bg3  h5  followed by ...h4 with a great position. }
7... O-O { Bringing the king to safety as usual. } 8. Nd2
{ White is trying to complete development.  8.fxe5  dxe5  would leave White's center vulnerable. }
8... exd4
{ Not the only move, but we can already act in the center. We also want our g7-bishop to be open. }
9. cxd4 c5 { This is important, we are undermining White's center. } 10. e5
{ White is trying to shut down the g7-bishop and is preparing Ne4.  10.d5  would lead to a great Benoni for Black after both  10...c4  or  10...Re8  . }
10... Ne8
{ An important move, controlling the d6-square so White doesn't have Ne4. If White doesn't do anything, their center will fall apart after ...cxd4. Instead, White went for an attack, which failed in 0-1 Dulenko-Chigaev, Sochi 2018. }
