1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Bd3
{ This sideline is quite popular among positional players. White wants to develop with c3, Nf3, O-O and Nbd2 and play like in a Ruy-Lopez − Re1, Nf1-g3. White is staying flexible not playing Nc3, so that they can reinforce the d4-pawn with c3. }
3... e5 { The classic Philidor plan, gaining a foothold in the center. } 4. c3
{ This is the point of White's play. White wants to keep the pressure in the center and doesn't want to push d5. }
4... Nbd7
{ This rare sideline will certainly surprise your opponent. The point is to protect e5 with the knight and try to push ...d5 on the next move. If White prevents this, we can switch to the ...g6 and ...Bg7 setup.   We recommend  4...Nbd7  over  4...d5  or  4...Nc6  in order to play some fresh positions, where we can even fight for a win with Black. }
5. f4 { An aggressive move, trying to stop our idea to play ...d5. } 5... c5
{ We're trying to put pressure by playing reversed symmetry! Of course, it's a risky approach, but White has to make some decisions.   5...Be7  is possible but a bit passive, and Black will have to play dynamically later on to avoid getting suffocated. }
6. dxe5
{ The strategic approach. White hopes to take advantage of the weakness of the c4 and d5-squares in the future. }
6... dxe5 7. Qe2
{ This is an improvement suggested by the computer. White is ready to go f5, when ...Nxe4 is not possible anymore. }
7... c4
{ We think that the best way is to sacrifice the pawn at once, without allowing White to get a grip on the position. In return, we'll be able to develop the bishop to c5, preventing White from castling. }
8. Bxc4 Bc5 { The bishop is strong on c5. We want to castle and play ...a6. }
9. f5
{ White closes the center according to plan, hoping to stabilize the position. If  9.Nf3  , we can defend the pawn with  9...Qc7  . }
9... a6 { We want to go ...b5 and ...Bb7, but  9...O-O  is also good. } 10. a4
{ Otherwise, we play ...b5. } 10... O-O
