{ This is what White wants to do, continuing with the development plan. } 5...
d5
{ A timely break in the center, exploiting the fact that e4 is unprotected. This is the main point of the line. }
6. dxe5 { The other possible capture, attacking our knight. } 6... dxe4
{ The only way to go.  6...Nxe4  looks like a very bad version of the Open Spanish, as White has a nice development lead. }
7. exf6 exf3
{ We take the knight in order to have access to the e5-square with our knight. }
8. O-O
{ A strong move. White is fighting for the initiative as our king is in the center. }
8... Ne5
{ An active knight jump.  8...gxf6  would lead to the same thing.  8...Qxf6  is also possible. }
9. Re1
{ The logical follow-up, putting pressure on the e-file.  9.fxg7  Bxg7  would only help us complete development faster. }
9... gxf6 { We need to support the e5-knight. } 10. Bf4
{ It's essential to play for the initiative and not bother about the f3-pawn. }
10... fxg2
{ We grab some more material and spoil White's structure. We want to follow up with ...Be6. }
11. Nd2
{ Somehow, the engine makes this bishop sacrifice possible because of the lead in development. }
11... Qxd3
{ We may as well take the bishop and accept the challenge. If you don't fancy these complications,  11...Be6  is also fine. }
12. Ne4
{ This is the point. The f6-pawn and the queen on d3 are attacked at the same time. }
12... Qxd1 { The only move. } 13. Nxf6+ { Forced. } 13... Ke7 { Obviously. }
14. Raxd1 Bg7
{ The position looks very dangerous for Black so we need to be very precise. This is the only move to stay in the game. The point is to meet  15.Bxe5  with  15...Bxf6  . }
15. Nd5+ { White saves the knight with tempo. } 15... Kd6
{ Strangely enough, the safest place for the king. The discovered checks lead nowhere. Objectively, the position is equal. }
