{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nge2
{ White is ready to take on d4 with the knight. There are several plans − f3, Be3 or h3, g4, Bg2 or even g3, Bg2. }
4... c6 { Trying to get ...b5. } 5. f3
{ Reinforcing the center and preparing Be3. } 5... b5
{ Whenever we can, we should go for this. We gain some space on the queenside, which will matter in the long term. Also, ...b4 is in the air. }
6. dxe5
{ White claims that the endgame is slightly better because they will have a4, forcing ...b4 and weakening the c4-square. }
6... dxe5 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. a4
{ This is the point of White's play, gaining control of the c4-square. } 8...
b4 { Forced. } 9. Nd1 { The knight is going to c4 via e3. } 9... a5
{ This is a useful move, protecting b4 and stopping White from playing a5. }
10. Bd2
{ White wants to play Nc1-b3, Ne3 and control the important squares in the position − c4, c5 and a5. }
10... Be6
{ The bishop belongs here anyway. We have to make sure White is not able to trade the light-squared bishops with Bc4. If White manages that, the knight will come to c4 with strong positional pressure. }
11. Nc1 { Preparing Ne3 and Bc4. } 11... Nbd7
{ This knight will come to b6 to stop Bc4. } 12. Ne3 { Threatening Bc4. } 12...
Nb6 { Controlling c4. } 13. Nd3 { White attacks e5 and prepares b3 and Nb2. }
13... Nfd7
{ Black successfully stopped White's threats and the endgame is promising. Our next moves could be ...h5, ...Kc7, ...f6. White lacks a clear plan. }
