[White "3) Philidor 3.Nc3 e5 − 4th Moves"]
[Black "Philidor 3.Nc3 e5 4.Nge2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nge2
{ White is ready to take on d4 with the knight. There are several plans − f3, Be3 or h3, g4, Bg2 or even g3, Bg2. }
4... c6 { Trying to get ...b5. } 5. f3
{ Reinforcing the center and preparing Be3. } 5... b5
{ Whenever we can, we should go for this. We gain some space on the queenside, which will matter in the long term. Also, ...b4 is in the air. }
6. Be3
{ The bishop belongs here, preparing Qd2. If White hurries with  6.g4  , then we can counter that with  6...b4  7.Na4  Nbd7  . }
6... Nbd7
{ We managed to get ...b5 on the board, and now we discourage dxe5 ideas since we can take back with the knight. }
7. g4 { Going for an attack. } 7... b4
{ As always after g4, we start our counterplay quickly. } 8. Na4 h6
{ We need to stop g5, and we want to break in the center open quickly. } 9. Qd2
{ Preparing O-O-O. } 9... Qa5
{ First, we activate the queen with tempo, and then ...d5 is next. } 10. b3 d5
{ We need to go for this quickly before White finishes development with O-O-O. The position is very unclear, but Black is fine. A sample line is  11.O-O-O  dxe4  12.dxe5  Nxe5  13.Bb6  Nd3+  14.Qxd3  Qg5+  . }
