1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. f4
{ This is good against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/3p1n2/8/3PP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nbd7  , but here the knight  gets to c6 after we take on d4. }
4... exd4 { Forcing White to take back with the queen. } 5. Qxd4 Nc6
{ We gain a development lead by attacking the queen. } 6. Bb5
{ White doesn't want to waste more time in the opening. } 6... Bd7
{ Renewing the threat on the queen. } 7. Qe3
{ Probably the best in order to stop ...d5 ideas. } 7... Be7
{ Going for quick development with ...O-O, ...Re8, ...a6. } 8. Bd2
{ Preparing long castle. } 8... O-O 9. O-O-O a6
{ First of all, we want to see what White does about the bishop. Afterwards, our plan is to play ...Re8, ...b5, and so on, with a possible attack on the queenside. Black is doing fine. }
