[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Philidor Endgame 4.dxe5"]
[Black "Philidor Endgame 4.dxe5 dxe5 5.Qxd8+ Kxd8 6.Nf3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. dxe5
{ White is trying to play for a better endgame, as our king will stay in the center. However, we're very confident in Black's resources. }
4... dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ The king in the center can be a little exposed, but it can also be an asset in the long term. If we manage to develop and coordinate our pieces, we'll get a good endgame. }
6. Nf3 { White is immediately attacking e5. } 6... Bd6
{ We have to be careful with the move order, as White was threatening Bc4 and Ng5. }
7. Be3
{ White wants to play h3 and O-O-O and is ready to meet ...Be6 with Ng5.   7.Bc4  Ke8  transposes to the 6.Bc4 variation, and there is also the additional option of  7...Ke7  . }
7... Ke7 { The king will be fine here. } 8. O-O-O Be6
{ The bishop is ideally placed on e6. We want to finish development with ...Nbd7. }
9. Ng5
{ The most ambitious move. If White plays something else we can go ...Nbd7 followed by ...h6 with a good position. }
9... Ng4
{ The most precise reply − we want to take the e3-bishop, and now some tactical complications will arise. }
10. Nxe6 Nxe3
{ It's important to capture the bishop before it runs away with Bg5+. } 11.
Rxd6
{ Now the position becomes really sharp. White is sacrificing an exchange counting on  11...cxd6  12.Nc7  or @@StartFEN@@rn5r/ppp1kppp/3RN3/4p3/4P3/2N1n3/PPP2PPP/2K2B1R b - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Kxd6  12.Ng5  .   11.Rd3  is met by  11...fxe6!  12.Rxe3  Bc5  and Black was slightly better in ½-½ Quesada Perez-Plat, Marianske Lazne 2020.   There is also the sacrifice  11.Nxg7  , but Black is already preferable after  11...Nxd1  12.Nf5+  Kf8  13.Nxd1  Nc6  followed by ...Ne7 or ...Nd4. }
11... Kxd6
{ This equalizes with a little bit of precision. We keep the pawn structure intact. }
12. Ng5 { The threat is Nxf7+. } 12... f6
{ Another accurate move. We keep the pawn alive, and we'll capture the knight on h8 later. }
13. Nf7+ Ke6
{ The only square for the king; otherwise, Nd5+ comes with a check later on. }
14. Nxh8 Nxf1 15. Rxf1 Na6
{ The last accurate move to remember. We're protecting the c7-pawn in advance, and we'll take the h8-knight on the next move. The endgame is completely equal. }
