[White "4) Philidor Endgame 4.dxe5"]
[Black "Philidor Endgame 4.dxe5 dxe5 5.Qxd8+ Kxd8 6.Bc4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. dxe5
{ White is trying to play for a better endgame, as our king will stay in the center. However, we're very confident in Black's resources. }
4... dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ The king in the center can be a little exposed, but it can also be an asset in the long term. If we manage to develop and coordinate our pieces, we'll get a good endgame. }
6. Bc4
{ The best and most played move. White is attacking f7 and developing with tempo. }
6... Ke8
{ Defending the pawn. We choose not to play  6...Be6  and ruin our pawn structure.  6...Bb4  is recommended by Pepe Cuenca in his Chessable course on the Philidor. It is an interesting option but more forcing.   After  6...Ke8  , there is no need to worry about  7.Nb5  , as we can count on  7...Bb4+  8.c3  Ba5  , and if  9.Nf3  a6  10.Na3  b5  11.Bd3  Nbd7  , with a fighting endgame ahead. }
7. f4
{ This was suggested by Anish Giri in his Chessable course. The idea is to open up the game since we cannot castle. }
7... Bb4 { Creating the threat of ...Nxe4. } 8. Bd2
{ One way to address the pin. } 8... Be6
{ If White accepts the trade, we won't have doubled f-pawns for long due to White's earlier f4. }
9. Bd3
{ After  9.Bxe6  fxe6  , Black is totally fine, as we will develop  with ...Nc6 and so on.  Also,  10.fxe5  is well met by  10...Bxc3  11.exf6  Bxd2+  12.Kxd2  gxf6=  . }
9... exf4
{ We need to do this before White plays f5. For instance, after  9...Nc6  10.f5  Bd7  11.Nf3  ,  White gains momentum on the kingside and can follow up with O-O-O, h3, g4, etc, when Black is under pressure. }
10. Nge2 Nbd7
{ Our knight is more useful here, so that we can play ...c6 as well. } 11. Bxf4
c6
{ Black has a comfortable position and went on to win in 0-1 Naiditsch-Navara, Sibenik 2009, after  12.h3  Ke7  13.O-O  Bc5+  14.Kh2  Bd6  15.g3  h5⩱  .  Now ...h4 is a threat, and the e4-pawn is also a liability in the long run. }
