[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. dxe5
{ White is trying to play for a better endgame, as our king will stay in the center. However, we're very confident in Black's resources. }
4... dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ The king in the center can be a little exposed, but it can also be an asset in the long term. If we manage to develop and coordinate our pieces, we'll get a good endgame. }
6. Bc4
{ The best and most played move. White is attacking f7 and developing with tempo. }
6... Ke8
{ Defending the pawn. We choose not to play  6...Be6  and ruin our pawn structure.  6...Bb4  is recommended by Pepe Cuenca in his Chessable course on the Philidor. It is an interesting option but more forcing.   After  6...Ke8  , there is no need to worry about  7.Nb5  , as we can count on  7...Bb4+  8.c3  Ba5  , and if  9.Nf3  a6  10.Na3  b5  11.Bd3  Nbd7  , with a fighting endgame ahead. }
7. f4
{ This was suggested by Anish Giri in his Chessable course. The idea is to open up the game since we cannot castle. }
7... Bb4 { Creating the threat of ...Nxe4. } 8. Bd3
{ White moves the bishop back to defend e4 and wants to develop the knight to f3. }
8... Nbd7
{ This is the right square for the knight, as it's headed towards c5. } 9. Nf3
{ Putting more pressure on e5.  9.fxe5  Nxe5  10.Nf3  Nfd7  is good for Black, as  White is saddled with an isolated pawn on e4, which is also nicely blocked. Black's moves come naturally: ...c6, ...f6, ...Ke7, etc., while it isn't so obvious how should White place their pieces after a potential Bf4 followed by O-O-O. }
9... Nc5 { We want to take on e4. } 10. Bd2
{ A modest move, addressing the pin. } 10... exf4
{ We take the pawn, as Nxe5 was a threat. } 11. O-O-O
{ This was tried by Jorden van Foreest in a couple of blitz games. } 11...
Nxd3+ { One of the possible moves. } 12. cxd3 Ng4
{ Creating some threats. ...Ne3 or ...Nf2 will come, and Black will get a comfortable position with the bishop pair.   If  13.Nd5  , there is  13...Bd6  , when  14.e5  doesn't work in view of  14...Nxe5  15.Nxe5  Be6!  , which is an important intermediate move, as  15...Bxe5?  instead runs into  16.Rhe1  . We have the same antidote against the immediate @@StartFEN@@r1b1k2r/ppp2ppp/3b4/3Nn3/5p2/3P1N2/PP1B2PP/2KR3R w - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Rhe1  Be6  . After  16.Nxe5  Bxd5  17.Ng6+  Kd7  18.Nxh8  Rxh8-+  , the powerful bishop pair and the two pawns outweigh White's exchange. }
