[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Philidor 4.Nf3 Nbd7 − 5th Moves"]
[Black "Philidor 4.Nf3 Nbd7 5.a4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. a4
{ An interesting idea suggested by GM Gustafsson & CM Nemec in their Chessable course. White wants to seize space quickly by pushing a5, and then play Be2 where it will be less exposed than on c4. }
5... Be7
{ Continuing development. We cannot stop a5 by playing  5...a5  because of  6.g4!  or  6.Bc4!  and Black is much worse. With  6.g4  , White will get a much better version of  the g4 lines, while with  6.Bc4  ,  White will go for the Ng5 and Bxf7+ lines,  where the white knight will escape from a8. }
6. g4
{ White can try this since taking on g4 is not so good on account of the g7-pawn hanging after Rg1. }
6... exd4 { We're countering the flank play by opening the center. } 7. Qxd4
{ White wants to castle long. } 7... O-O 8. g5
{ Removing the knight from the center. } 8... Ng4
{ The knight will be active here, and it can never be trapped since we always have ...Ne5. Our next move might be ...Nc5. Black is doing fine because White lacks cohesive development. }
*

