[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. a4
{ An interesting idea suggested by GM Gustafsson & CM Nemec in their Chessable course. White wants to seize space quickly by pushing a5, and then play Be2 where it will be less exposed than on c4. }
5... Be7
{ Continuing development. We cannot stop a5 by playing  5...a5  because of  6.g4!  or  6.Bc4!  and Black is much worse. With  6.g4  , White will get a much better version of  the g4 lines, while with  6.Bc4  ,  White will go for the Ng5 and Bxf7+ lines,  where the white knight will escape from a8. }
6. a5
{ White is counting on this pawn gaining them some edge in the long run. } 6...
O-O 7. Be2
{ Only this move makes a difference.  7.Bc4  would transpose to other lines. }
7... exd4
{ We're playing like in the other variations, opening the center quickly. We want to follow up with ...Nc5. }
8. Nxd4 { The most principled recapture. } 8... Nc5 { Our standard idea. } 9.
f3
{ Defending e4. On  9.Bf3  , there is  9...Re8  followed by ...Bf8 and ...c6. }
9... c6 { A useful move. In this case, we're preparing ...d5. } 10. O-O d5
{ A new direction. We want to change the pawn structure and restrict the c3-knight.  10...Re8  would transpose to the Gustafsson & Nemec Chessable course. }
11. e5
{ The only try for an advantage. White wants to follow up with f4 and Be3. However, the c3-knight will be restricted by the d5-c6 pawn chain.   If  11.a6  , there is  11...dxe4  . }
11... Ne8
{ It's important to put the knight here so that we can play ...f6. If the knight were on d7, ...f6 would be met with e6. }
12. f4 { Now f5 is a threat! } 12... f6
{ We need to attack the center as soon as possible. } 13. Be3
{ Just continuing development. } 13... fxe5
{ The idea is to open the f-file and weaken the e-pawn. } 14. fxe5 Nc7
{ We're bringing the knight into play. } 15. Qd2 N5e6
{ We want to trade the knight on d4 and bring the other knight to e6. Our pawn chain c6-d5 is strong, and e5 could be a weakness in the long term.   16.Nf5?  doesn't work because of  16...Rxf5!  followed by ...d4. }
