1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. Rg1
{ The modern approach. White is preparing g4 with a kingside attack. } 5... c6
{ We make a useful move, preparing ...b5 and ...Qa5. This also diverges from Pepe's LTR, which covers  5...g6  . }
6. g4 { This is the idea of White's last move. } 6... h6
{ It's important to stop g5 in order to secure the f6-knight. } 7. a4
{ White prevents ...b5 but loses an important tempo and makes queenside castling less attractive. }
7... exd4 { Considering that White wasted time, we act in the center. } 8. Nxd4
{ If  8.Qxd4  , then  8...Nc5  is quite pleasant for Black. } 8... Ne5
{ Attacking g4 and preparing ...d5. } 9. h3 { Defending g4. } 9... d5
{ The only move, breaking up the center. } 10. f4
{ White is counting on  10...Ng6  11.e5  , but we have something else in mind.   10.exd5  Bb4  is an idea we've already seen before. Black's position is to be preferred. }
10... Nfxg4 { The right time for this sacrifice. } 11. hxg4
{ One of the possible captures. The other capture  11.fxe5  leads to a forced draw after  11...Qh4+  12.Kd2  Qf2+  13.Nce2  Qe3+  . }
11... Qh4+ { Obviously. } 12. Kd2 Bc5
{ With a very unbalanced position. White is up a piece, but the king is poorly placed on d2. }
