1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. Rg1
{ The modern approach. White is preparing g4 with a kingside attack. } 5... c6
{ We make a useful move, preparing ...b5 and ...Qa5. This also diverges from Pepe's LTR, which covers  5...g6  . }
6. g4 { This is the idea of White's last move. } 6... h6
{ It's important to stop g5 in order to secure the f6-knight. } 7. Qe2
{ A tricky move, intending h4 and g5. Sometimes, White can develop the bishop to d2. This is a very rare move. We didn't even know about it until Leon got crushed in the Bundesliga in his game against Ivic. }
7... Qb6
{ This seems to be the most precise move. We are attacking the d4-pawn since the white queen is not defending it anymore.  7...b5  is also possible but more complex. }
8. d5
{ Forced. White is saving the pawn.  8.dxe5  instead is bad news for White after  8...Nxe5  .  The pawn is hanging on g4, and Black has an easy time developing the remaining pieces: ...Be6 and ...O-O-O can surely be considered. }
8... cxd5 9. exd5 Qa5 { An important move, attacking the d5-pawn. } 10. Nd4
{ Our reply is the same in the case of  10.Bd2  −  10...Nxd5  . } 10... Nxd5
11. Bd2 N7f6
{ We need to develop the pieces. We want to follow up with ...Bd7. The position is extremely complex. White has compensation for the pawn, but Black is also doing fine. A sample line goes  12.Rg3  Qc5  13.Nxd5  Nxd5  14.Nb3  Qc7  . }
