{ We make a useful move, preparing ...b5 and ...Qa5. This also diverges from Pepe's LTR, which covers  5...g6  . }
6. g4 { This is the idea of White's last move. } 6... h6
{ It's important to stop g5 in order to secure the f6-knight. } 7. Be3
{ The main move, and also a principled one. White wants to go Qd2 and O-O-O. }
7... Be7
{ Developing the bishop and leaving the f8-square empty for the knight in case we want ...Nf8-g6. }
8. Qd2 { A natural move, preparing O-O-O. } 8... b5
{ ...b4 is the threat, after which e4 would fall to ...Nxe4. } 9. a3
{ White needs to secure the c3-knight. } 9... Qa5
{ Renewing the threat of ...b4. } 10. Bd3
{ Overprotecting e4 and intending to meet  10...b4  with  11.Na2! } 10... Rb8
{ The rook is useful here, in preparation of the b-file opening after ...b4. }
11. h4
{ Getting ready for g5. Until here, we followed the online game 0-1 Kosakowski-Sanal, chess.com 2022. }
11... b4 { We need to act quickly since g5 was a threat. } 12. Ne2
{ 12.Na2  d5!  13.axb4  Bxb4⩱  highlights  the importance of having the rook on b8. }
12... c5
{ This looks very tempting, as after  13.d5  , we have  13...c4  followed by ...Nxe4. If White takes on e5 or c5, we take back with the knight, and g4 is under attack. We already prefer Black's position.   A sample line goes  13.dxe5  Nxe5  14.Nxe5  dxe5  15.f3  Be6  16.b3  c4!   The other break,  12...d5  , is also possible. }
