2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. Rg1
{ The modern approach. White is preparing g4 with a kingside attack. } 5... c6
{ We make a useful move, preparing ...b5 and ...Qa5. This also diverges from Pepe's LTR, which covers  5...g6  . }
6. g4 { This is the idea of White's last move. } 6... h6
{ It's important to stop g5 in order to secure the f6-knight. } 7. Be3
{ The main move, and also a principled one. White wants to go Qd2 and O-O-O. }
7... Be7
{ Developing the bishop and leaving the f8-square empty for the knight in case we want ...Nf8-g6. }
8. h4 { Going for g5. } 8... Nf8
{ White doesn't have h3 available anymore, so our f6-knight has a future home on g4. }
9. dxe5 { The natural move, opening the position. } 9... Nxg4
{ We were counting on this. } 10. exd6 { Clearing the center with tempo. }
10... Qxd6 { Activating the queen. } 11. Bd4
{ Saving the bishop and attacking g7. The endgame after  11.Qxd6  is completely fine, as there is  11...Bxd6  12.Bd4?!  Ne6! }
11... Qf4 { Obstructing White's development and setting up a nice trap. } 12.
Qd3
{ The only move.  12.Bxg7?  is tempting but loses on the spot to  12...Bxh4! }
12... h5
{ Securing our knight on g4 and making room for the queen on h6 in the case of  13.Ne2  .   12...Ne6  is also a good option. }
13. Bxg7 { White finally takes the pawn. } 13... Rg8
{ We sacrificed a pawn but activated our pieces and have huge compensation in return. }
14. Ne2
{ The only move, hitting the queen. The natural  14.Bd4?  fails to  14...Nh2!  15.Rxg8  Nxf3+  16.Kd1  Bg4!  with discovered check threats mixed with a little problem on the d-file @@StartBracket@@...Rd8 or ...O-O-O is on the way@@EndBracket@@. }
14... Qc7 { The best square for the queen. } 15. Bxf8
{ This looks like a concession, but White wants to exchange some pieces. Until here, it was 0-1 Antolak-Livaic, Kavala 2024.  15.Bd4  is the better move but after  15...Be6  followed ...O-O-O and ...Ng6, Black has more than enough compensation due to our excellent grip on the dark squares and White's weakened pawn structure. }
15... Rxf8
{ It's important to capture with the rook in order to keep options to castle long after ...Bd7. White's king is stuck in the center, and the f2-pawn is weak. }
