10. dxe5 { It's good for White to open the d-file. } 10... dxe5 11. Kb1
{ Improving the king's position and defending a2. } 11... Rb8
{ A novelty. The position is dangerous for Black, as we have not managed to castle. We overprotect b5 in preparation for ...Qc7, which will no longer run into the dangerous Bxb5 sacrifice. }
12. Bg5 { Putting pressure on our position; Bxf6 is an immediate threat. }
12... b4 { Not only attacking the knight but also defending e5 just in case. }
13. Na4
{ A typical move for this line − if Black takes the knight, then there is Nxe5 with a strong initiative. }
13... Be7
{ White blocked the g-file, so we can do this. With the a4-knight and e4-pawn hanging, we prioritize development instead of taking the offered material. }
14. Bh3 { Threatening Bxd7+. } 14... Rb7
{ Another fine point of @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p2n1ppp/2p2n2/qp2p3/4P3/2N1BN2/PPPQ1P1P/1K1R1BR1 b kq - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Rb8  is that we can use the rook for defensive purposes. White has compensation, but we managed to stabilize the position and can castle soon. }
