[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Philidor 4.Nf3 Nbd7 − 5th Moves"]
[Black "Philidor 4.Nf3 Nbd7 5.g4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. g4
{ A very aggressive move, sacrificing a pawn and playing for a quick initiative. }
5... Nxg4
{ We accept the challenge and take the pawn. It is also interesting to go  5...h6  with similar play as in the 5.Rg1 lines, but it gives White additional options like  6.h3  . }
6. Rg1
{ This was the point − to activate the rook on the g-file. It will be more difficult for us to develop the f8-bishop. }
6... Ngf6 { The knight goes back to safety. } 7. Be3
{ One of the two main approaches. White wants to go Qd2 and O-O-O quickly. }
7... c6 { Always a useful move, sometimes intending ...b5 and ...Qa5. } 8. Qd2
{ The most logical move, intending O-O-O.  8.Bc4  is met by  8...Qa5!  ,  threatening both ...Nxe4 and ...b5. }
8... b5
{ Threatening ...b4. We want to start our counterplay quickly.  8...Qa5  would most likely transpose. }
9. O-O-O { White is threatening dxe5 and we're not in time to play ...b4. }
9... Qa5
{ The only move, but it makes a lot of sense as we want to go ...b4 and ...Qxa2.   9...Qc7  instead runs into  10.Bxb5!  cxb5  11.dxe5  dxe5  12.Nxb5  and shockingly, Qa5 is coming next with unstoppable threats.   Also,  9...b4  is premature in view of  10.dxe5  bxc3  11.Qxc3  dxe5  12.Qxc6  Rb8  13.Nxe5  , which is bad news for Black. }
10. dxe5 { It's good for White to open the d-file. } 10... dxe5 11. Kb1
{ Improving the king's position and defending a2. } 11... Rb8
{ A novelty. The position is dangerous for Black, as we have not managed to castle. We overprotect b5 in preparation for ...Qc7, which will no longer run into the dangerous Bxb5 sacrifice. }
12. Bh3 { Another logical move, bringing the last piece into play. } 12... Qc7
{ The queen did its job on a5, and now it helps to defend our king.   The aggressive  12...b4  backfires in view of  13.Na4  Qc7  14.Qd3  ,  which prepares a very unpleasant Ng5+Qb3 combo. Black is walking a tightrope here. }
13. Bxd7+
{ Due to tactical tricks along the h2-b8 diagonal, we're forced to recapture with the knight.   The immediate  13.Nh4  can be met with  13...b4  14.Na4  g6  ,  denying White's knight access to the f5-square. }
13... Nxd7
{ The only move.  13...Bxd7?  14.Nxe5  Qxe5  15.Bf4  is not something we want as Black. }
14. Nh4 { White wants to go Nf5 or f4. } 14... Nb6
{ Opening up the c8-bishop and seeking to go ...Nc4. } 15. b3
{ Just stopping ...Nc4. } 15... b4 { We're driving the white knight away. } 16.
Ne2 { White wants to go f4 to open up the position. } 16... Ba6
{ We would meet the natural  17.Nf5  with  17...Rd8  , as after all the trades  on d8, we threaten the knight on e2, and thus White cannot recuperate the pawn on g7.   16...Be6  looks more logical, but it would be exposed after  17.f4  , so that's why we put the bishop here.  We also want to play ...Rd8 to trade a pair of rooks. White has compensation, but if we manage to trade some more pieces, we can take advantage of the extra pawn. }
