1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. g4
{ A very aggressive move, sacrificing a pawn and playing for a quick initiative. }
5... Nxg4
{ We accept the challenge and take the pawn. It is also interesting to go  5...h6  with similar play as in the 5.Rg1 lines, but it gives White additional options like  6.h3  . }
6. Rg1
{ This was the point − to activate the rook on the g-file. It will be more difficult for us to develop the f8-bishop. }
6... Ngf6 { The knight goes back to safety. } 7. Bc4
{ The main line. White is threatening Ng5. } 7... exd4
{ Freeing the e5-square for the knight. The most popular move is  7...h6  , but we want to recommend something more active. }
8. Nxd4
{ This capture is less logical as there is no more  8.Ng5?  Ne5  9.Qxd4  h6!  with a big fork incoming on f3. }
8... c6
{ Always a useful move, covering some important squares and introducing ideas of ...Ne5, ...Qb6. When combined together, Black threatens ...Qxd4! followed by ...Nf3+, etc.   Nicely,  8...c6  is also a novelty according to our database. }
9. Be3 { The most natural move, preparing Qd2 and O-O-O. } 9... Ne5
{ One of several possible moves, attacking the bishop and threatening ...Nfg4. }
10. Be2 { White needs to stop ...Ng4. } 10... h5
{ Renewing the threat of ...Nfg4. } 11. f3 { Stopping ...Ng4 ideas. } 11... b5
{ We're threatening ...b4, and White doesn't have  12.f4  because of  12...Nfg4!  with a counterattack on the e3-bishop and a secondary idea of ...Qh4+. }
12. a3 { Stopping ...b4. } 12... Bd7
{ Defending c6 in advance, so that we can push ...a5-b4 later on. The position is unusual and very unclear.   Another interesting, but riskier, idea is to go  12...a6  followed  by ...c5. }
