{ Preparing g5, with the idea of recapturing with the h-pawn. After  8.Be3  , there is  8...b5  ,  when the bishop on e2 is not very useful compared to the 5.Rg1 lines. }
8... Nf8
{ Attacking g4. A novelty in this position, but we've seen this idea multiple times in the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppn1ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Rg1  line. }
9. g5
{ White continues pushing. In case of  9.dxe5  Nxg4  10.exd6  Bxd6  11.e5  Nxe5  12.Nxe5  Bxe5  13.Qxd8+  Kxd8  , Black can't complain about being a pawn up in this endgame. }
9... hxg5 { It's good to open up the rook. } 10. hxg5 Ng4
{ This is the point. The knight is active on g4, preventing White from playing Be3. The other knight can go to g6. }
