[White "5) Philidor 4.Nf3 Nbd7 − 5th Moves"]
[Black "Philidor 4.Nf3 Nbd7 5.Be2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. Be2
{ White goes for a more modest approach. The bishop is less active here but also less exposed than on c4. }
5... Be7
{ The normal Philidor development.  5...c6  , trying  to immediately go ...b5 is also possible. }
6. O-O O-O 7. a4
{ A typical Philidor move, grabbing space on the queenside. This is similar to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppn1ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.a4  recommended by Gustafsson, but the pawn is  not yet on a5. }
7... exd4
{ This is a novelty. We will use the same plan as against the 5.a4 variation. }
8. Qxd4 { The other recapture. The point is to have e4 defended after ...Nc5. }
8... Nc5
{ The typical reply. We have useful moves like ...Re8, ...c6 and ...a5. } 9.
Rd1 { Introducing some e5 ideas due to the pin on the d-file. } 9... Re8
{ The rook belongs on the open file. We're not afraid of e5 because we can take ...dxe5.  9...a5  is also possible. }
10. h3
{ A prophylactic move preparing Be3. If  10.a5  , there is  10...Bd7  and Black is fine. }
10... a5 { Stopping White's a5 or b4. } 11. Be3 c6
{ We want to free some squares for the queen if e5 happens. } 12. e5
{ The only active idea for White in this position. } 12... Ne6
{ The only move, as the knight was hanging on c5. White has to keep the queen on the d-file, and then we can take on e5. The position is about equal. }
