[Black "Philidor 4.Nf3 Nbd7 5.dxe5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. dxe5
{ This trade is a poor strategic decision that releases the central tension and comes with several negative side effects. White cannot disturb our castling rights by trading queens, we didn't lose a tempo with ...Be7, and the dark-squared bishop can comfortably emerge outside the pawn chain in one go. }
5... dxe5 6. Bc4 Bb4
{ Now we have the chance to put the bishop on a more active square. We intend ...O-O, ...c6, and so on. We shouldn't hurry with taking on c3. Black has already solved all of their opening problems. }
*

