[Black "Philidor 4.Nf3 Nbd7 5.h3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. h3
{ A prophylactic move, with ideas to play Be3 or g4. It's a bit strange for White to make a pawn move so early on instead of developing pieces. }
5... c6 { Preparing ...b5. } 6. a4
{ Just stopping ...b5. We can meet  6.g4  with  6...h6  , while @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp1n1ppp/2pp1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N1P/PPP2PP1/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  transposes to the 5.Be3 line. }
6... Be7 { We're developing. } 7. g4
{ An ambitious try.  7.Be3  transposes to the 5.Be3 variation. } 7... h6
{ Stopping g5. This is also our approach in the Rg1 lines. } 8. Rg1
{ White still hopes to push the pawns on the kingside. } 8... exd4
{ When your opponent plays on the flank, it's good to break through in the center. }
9. Qxd4 { A logical move, intending Bf4 and O-O-O. } 9... Ne5
{ We need to act quickly, even at the cost of a pawn! If we play slowly, White will get a good position with our d6-pawn as a target. }
10. Nxe5 { White takes the pawn. } 10... dxe5 11. Qxe5 Be6
{ We go for quick development. We have ideas such as ...Bd6, ...Nd7 or ...Qb6. }
12. a5
{ Stopping ...Qb6. Anyway, it's hard for White to make such a move without completing development first.   For instance, after  12.Be3  Nd7!  , White is already having a tough time developing harmoniously.  13.Qxg7?  Bf6  traps the queen, while @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp1nbpp1/2p1b2p/4Q3/P3P1P1/2N1B2P/1PP2P2/R3KBR1 w Qkq - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Qd4  Qa5  puts a spell on White's long castle. }
12... Nd7
{ Regrouping our pieces. Obviously, the g7-pawn is untouchable.  12...Bd6  is also possible. }
13. Qg3 { Keeping ideas of g5. } 13... Bh4
{ We need to remove the queen from its active position. The position is unclear, but Black has enough compensation for the pawn.   14.Qd6  Be7  would be a move repetition, or @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/pp1n1pp1/2p1b2p/P7/4P1Pb/2N3QP/1PP2P2/R1B1KBR1 w Qkq - 3 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Qe3  b5!?  gives Black good counterplay. }
