1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. Bc4
{ The most played move. White is already threatening Ng5. } 5... Be7
{ Now we can parry Ng5 with ...O-O. } 6. a4
{ A very typical move for the Philidor, gaining some space on the queenside. }
6... O-O
{ Completing development. Don't play  6...a5  because then  7.Ng5  O-O  8.Bxf7+  Rxf7  9.Ne6  Qe8  10.Nxc7  Qd8  11.Nxa8  wins for White. After the knight  takes the a8-rook, it will not get trapped because White has Nb5. }
7. h3 { It's a bit strange to make all these pawn moves before castling. } 7...
exd4 { We do this before White goes Be3 and can take on d4 with the bishop. }
8. Qxd4
{ White defends the e4-pawn in advance. If  8.Nxd4  , there is  8...Nc5  ,  attacking the e4-pawn. }
8... Nc5 { Finishing development and preparing ...Be6 or ...c6. } 9. O-O
{ 9.b4  backfires in view of  9...Ncxe4  10.Nxe4  d5  , when Black regains the material with a much better position. }
9... Be6 { And we have transposed to the 7.a4 variation. } *

