[Black "Philidor 5.Bc4 Be7 6.dxe5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. Bc4
{ The most played move. White is already threatening Ng5. } 5... Be7
{ Now we can parry Ng5 with ...O-O. } 6. dxe5
{ After this capture, White can try Bxf7+ or Ng5 in a better version, as we won't have the ...exd4 option later on. }
6... dxe5
{ This is the more ambitious move. There is nothing wrong with  6...Nxe5  7.Nxe5  dxe5  8.Qxd8+  Bxd8  , but the endgame is very drawish. }
7. Bxf7+ { An interesting way to force events. } 7... Kxf7 8. Ng5+ Kg6
{ The only way to fight for an advantage, but Black is taking some risks as well, obviously. Black can bail out with  8...Kg8  9.Ne6  Qe8  10.Nxc7  Qg6  11.Nxa8  Qxg2  12.Rf1  Nc5  13.Qe2  Bh3  with an equal position. }
9. Ne6 { Very tempting, trying to take more material. } 9... Qg8
{ The advantage of moving the king to g6 is that we got the g8-square for the queen, and we don't lose the a8-rook. }
10. Nxc7 { It's already late for  10.f4  in view of  10...h6! } 10... Rb8
{ Saving the rook. } 11. Qf3
{ Trying to create some threats on the black king. } 11... Qc4
{ The most precise move. Black is a piece up. In a practical game  11...Kf7  was played and Black won easily. }
*

