[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Philidor 5.Bc4 − Main Line"]
[Black "Philidor 5.Bc4 Be7 6.dxe5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. Bc4
{ The most played move. White is already threatening Ng5. } 5... Be7
{ Now we can parry Ng5 with ...O-O. } 6. dxe5
{ After this capture, White can try Bxf7+ or Ng5 in a better version, as we won't have the ...exd4 option later on. }
6... dxe5
{ This is the more ambitious move. There is nothing wrong with  6...Nxe5  7.Nxe5  dxe5  8.Qxd8+  Bxd8  , but the endgame is very drawish. }
7. Ng5 { Attacking f7 right away. } 7... O-O { Forced. } 8. Bxf7+
{ The only way to justify the previous move. If White doesn't go for this, we have time to go ...c6, and afterwards, the knight on g5 will be misplaced. }
8... Rxf7 { There follows a sequence of forced moves: } 9. Ne6 Qe8 10. Nxc7 Qd8
11. Nxa8
{ Compared to the line without the exchange on e5, this is a better version for White, as the structure is already defined − in the other line, we could take back on e5 with the knight. }
11... b6
{ 11...b5  is also possible,  but we want to have the option to play ...Ba6. }
12. Nd5
{ This was seen most often in practice. White wants to save the a8-knight. }
12... Nxe4 { Taking a pawn and threatening ...Nxf2. } 13. Be3
{ Developing and defending f2. } 13... Bd6
{ So the a8-knight is not going to escape! } 14. Qe2
{ The idea is to castle long. } 14... Bb7 15. O-O-O Qxa8
{ The position remains very unclear, but objectively Black is fine.  15...Bxa8  is also possible. }
*

