[White "6) Philidor 5.Bc4 − Main Line"]
[Black "Philidor 5.Bc4 Be7 6.O-O O-O 7.Re1 | Alternative 7...exd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. Bc4
{ The most played move. White is already threatening Ng5. } 5... Be7
{ Now we can parry Ng5 with ...O-O. } 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1
{ The most played move. White is reinforcing the e4-pawn and the center. } 7...
exd4
{ Quite a rarely played move. This is one of the options we recommend. We want to quickly activate the d7-knight and develop the c8-bishop. }
8. Qxd4
{ One of the possible captures. By leaving the knight on f3, White doesn't allow ...Ne5 and wants to play Bf4 and Rad1. }
8... Nc5
{ As we cannot go to e5, we move the knight to c5 and want to follow up with ...Bg4 or ...Ne6 @@StartBracket@@against Bf4 or Bg5@@EndBracket@@. It's important to open up a path for the c8-bishop. }
9. Bg5 { A similar idea to Bf4, preparing Rad1 or Bxf6. } 9... Ne6
{ We're going to take a bishop. Don't fall for  9...Bg4?  , as after  10.Bxf6!  Bxf6  11.e5  , White is winning. }
10. Bxe6 Bxe6
{ Now we have to take with the bishop.  10...fxe6  is not good because White has  11.e5  ,  and the bishop is not hanging on f4. }
11. Rad1 h6
{ It's useful to include this move. The subtle difference with playing  11...c6  directly can be seen in the following variation:  12.e5  dxe5  13.Qxe5  Qb6  14.Ne4  Nxe4  15.Bxe7  Rfe8  16.Qxe4  Rxe7  17.Ng5!  With the pawn on h6, Ng5 is no longer an option, and Black is doing fine. }
12. Bh4 c6
{ We're controlling the d5-square.  13.Bxf6  Bxf6  14.Qxd6  is never an issue, as we get more than enough compensation for the pawn. }
13. h3
{ Slowly improving the position.  13.Bg3  attacking on d6 is parried by  13...d5! }
13... Re8
{ Another useful move. We can go ...Qa5 or ...Qb6 next. White has a bit more space, but we're counting on the bishop pair in the long run. }
