[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Philidor 5.Bc4 − Main Line"]
[Black "Philidor 5.Bc4 Be7 6.O-O O-O 7.Re1 | Alternative 7...exd4 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. Bc4
{ The most played move. White is already threatening Ng5. } 5... Be7
{ Now we can parry Ng5 with ...O-O. } 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1
{ The most played move. White is reinforcing the e4-pawn and the center. } 7...
exd4
{ Quite a rarely played move. This is one of the options we recommend. We want to quickly activate the d7-knight and develop the c8-bishop. }
8. Nxd4
{ By far the main move. White is centralizing the knight, and there are ideas of Nf5. }
8... Ne5
{ We're activating our knight with tempo.  8...Nc5?!  is not good because of  9.b4! }
9. Bf1 { The most natural retreat as White played Re1. } 9... Re8
{ Always a useful prophylactic move. } 10. h3
{ White doesn't want to worry about ...Ng4 or ...Bg4 tricks in the future. }
10... Ng6
{ We don't want f4 to come with tempo, and we're preventing Bf4 as well.  10...c6  or  10...Bd7  is possible, but the text is the most flexible move. }
11. f4 { Expanding anyway. } 11... Bf8
{ This is a move we want to play nevertheless. } 12. a4
{ Just gaining some space on the queenside. } 12... Bd7
{ Finishing our development, and sometimes having ideas of ...c5 and ...Bc6. It's important not to hurry with  12...c6  because  then ...c5 would lose a tempo. }
13. Nf3
{ This was recommended by Wesley So in his Chessable course. This move prevents the ...c5 push:  13...c5?  14.e5  dxe5  15.fxe5  Nh5  16.Ng5  Nhf4  17.Nxf7  Kxf7  18.Bxf4  Nxf4  19.Qf3  , when White regains the material with interest. }
13... a6
{ An important accuracy to remember − we want to play ...b5 and exploit the fact that e4 is hanging. }
14. a5 { Just stopping ...b5. } 14... Bc6
{ We're putting more pressure on e4. } 15. Bd3 { Defending e4. } 15... b5
{ Now we can finally go for this, as a6 is not hanging anymore − White would lose e4. }
16. axb6 { Stopping our expansion. } 16... cxb6 17. Nd4
{ White centralizes the knight with tempo. } 17... Bb7
{ We finally fianchetto the bishop! } 18. Qf3
{ Now e4 gets some extra support. } 18... b5
{ Improving the structure on the queenside and threatening ...b4. } 19. Bd2
{ Until here, this line was given by Wesley So in his course 1.e4 − Part 1. He was following the correspondence game ½-½ Tiemann-Malnar, ICCF 2018. }
19... Qc7
{ Slightly improving the queen's position and intending ...b4. The correspondence game continued with  19...d5  followed by some big complications, which eventually ended in a draw. }
20. Kh1 { Removing the king from the g1-a7 diagonal. } 20... b4
{ Forcing matters. There was no good way to further improve our position. } 21.
Nd5 Nxd5 { Forced. } 22. exd5 Qc5
{ A double attack on d4 and d5. The position is complicated but fine for Black. We analyzed that far because of Wesley So's course. A sample line goes  23.Nc6  Nh4!  24.Qh5  g6!  25.Qxh4  Qxd5  and we're taking back the piece. }
