[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. Bc4
{ The most played move. White is already threatening Ng5. } 5... Be7
{ Now we can parry Ng5 with ...O-O. } 6. O-O O-O 7. h3
{ White is preparing Be3 in order to take on d4 with the bishop. } 7... exd4
{ The alternative option, in case you want to play without a quick ...c6. } 8.
Qxd4 { White's idea is to follow up with Bf4. } 8... Nb6
{ Hitting the c4-bishop.  8...Nc5  is also possible, but White can play  9.Rd1  . }
9. Be2
{ White is afraid of ...c5-c4 ideas and places the bishop on a passive square. }
9... c6 { We want to go ...d5. } 10. a4 { Trying to harass the b6-knight. }
10... d5
{ We are in time with the break, and we would have played it against any other move on move 10 as well. }
11. e5
{ White gains a tempo but allows the c6-d5 pawn chain.  11.a5  dxe4  is fine for Black. For example,  12.axb6  exf3  13.Qxd8  Bxd8  14.Rxa7  fxe2  15.Re1  Rb8  16.Bf4  Bxb6  leads to an equal endgame. }
11... Ne8 { Forced. We need the d7-square for the other knight. } 12. a5 Nd7
{ Over the next few moves, we'll put the knights on better squares − c5 and c7. Afterwards, we can even undermine the e5-pawn with ...f6. Black is doing fine. }
