{ We're going for this anyway, as White cannot exploit the d6-weakness. The fight will revolve around the d5-square, but we need not worry since we have sufficient control over it. }
10. Nf3 { White keeps the knight more active, but f4 is not possible anymore. }
10... Ng6
{ We don't want to allow Bf4 or the knight trade. The idea is to go ...Bd7-c6 and ...Re8. }
11. a4 { A useful move, seizing some space on the queenside. } 11... Bd7
{ The bishop is going to c6 to attack the e4-pawn, although  11...Be6  is also possible. }
12. Re1 { Bringing the rook into play. } 12... Bc6 13. Bc4
{ Defending e4 and fighting for the important d5-square. } 13... Re8
{ We're also activating the rook. We're not afraid of  14.Ng5  because of  14...Ne5  . However, we want to  include ...h6 later on. }
14. Qd3 { Overprotecting e4 and preparing Bd2. } 14... h6
{ It's important to control the g5-square so that we can play ...Bf8 without allowing Bg5. Possible plans could be ...Nd7-b6, or ...Qc7 and ...Rad8. Black is solid, and we have enough control over the d5-square. }
