[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Philidor 5.Bc4 − Main Line"]
[Black "Philidor 5.Bc4 Be7 6.O-O O-O 7.Qe2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. Bc4
{ The most played move. White is already threatening Ng5. } 5... Be7
{ Now we can parry Ng5 with ...O-O. } 6. O-O O-O 7. Qe2
{ The idea is to go Rd1. } 7... c6
{ Always a useful move in the Philidor. The idea is to go ...b5, but  7...exd4  8.Nxd4  c6  is also possible. }
8. Rd1
{ White continues their plan. However, this is not so good, and Black can get a better position.  8.a4  transposes to the 7.a4 line and  8.dxe5  transposes to the 7.dxe5 move order. }
8... exd4
{ Surprisingly, this is rarely played. We're opening the center and want to follow up with ...Re8, when the white queen will be misplaced. }
9. Nxd4 { 9.Rxd4?  is just bad because of  9...b5  . } 9... Re8
{ Black is already better here, as White's pieces are misplaced.  10.Nf5  can be met with  10...b5  . }
