11... c5 { Again our trademark move. } 12. Nf3
{ White's idea is to play Ne2 and then c3, bringing the bishop into play. It is indeed a deep idea! }
12... Re8
{ A typical regrouping, we want to play ...Bf8. The position is non-standard, White has some space advantage, but Black is fine.  12...d5  was also tried here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Philidor 5.Bc4 − Main Line"]
[Black "Philidor 5.Bc4 Be7 6.O-O O-O 7.a4 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. Bc4
{ The most played move. White is already threatening Ng5. } 5... Be7
{ Now we can parry Ng5 with ...O-O. } 6. O-O O-O 7. a4
{ A good prophylactic move. White can play a5 to gain some more space on the queenside, and also after ...c6, there is no ...b5. }
7... exd4
{ One of the two options we recommend against White's setup. We want to break up the center to jump with the knight to either e5 or c5. }
8. Nxd4 { The main move, keeping ideas of Nf5. } 8... Ne5
{ Hitting the c4-bishop and activating the knight. Once we opened the center, we needed to act quickly. }
9. Ba2 { The most logical move, keeping the bishop on the long diagonal. } 9...
Nc6
{ Change of plans.  9...c5  is too slow because we don't  have ...c4 with tempo afterwards. With ...Nc6 we have ideas of ...Nb4 or ...Nxd4 and ...Be6. }
10. Nxc6 { This brings our pawn to c6, which will restrict the c3-knight. }
10... bxc6 11. Re1 Rb8
{ ...Nd7 and ...Bf6 is the plan. Black had a good game in Brkic- Livaic, Veli Losinj 2024. }
*

