2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. Bc4
{ The most played move. White is already threatening Ng5. } 5... Be7
{ Now we can parry Ng5 with ...O-O. } 6. O-O O-O 7. a4
{ A good prophylactic move. White can play a5 to gain some more space on the queenside, and also after ...c6, there is no ...b5. }
7... exd4
{ One of the two options we recommend against White's setup. We want to break up the center to jump with the knight to either e5 or c5. }
8. Nxd4 { The main move, keeping ideas of Nf5. } 8... Ne5
{ Hitting the c4-bishop and activating the knight. Once we opened the center, we needed to act quickly. }
9. Ba2 { The most logical move, keeping the bishop on the long diagonal. } 9...
Nc6
{ Change of plans.  9...c5  is too slow because we don't  have ...c4 with tempo afterwards. With ...Nc6 we have ideas of ...Nb4 or ...Nxd4 and ...Be6. }
10. Bf4 { The most played move. White develops everything quickly. } 10... a6
{ We want to go ...Nb4 followed by ...c5, but we cannot do this immediately because after ...c5, there is Ndb5 targeting the d6-pawn. }
11. Re1
{ Activating the rook. Black is fine after  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.e5  dxe5  13.Bxe5  Bd6  . }
11... Nb4 { The typical plan to follow up with ...c5 and ...Be6. } 12. Bc4
{ White preserves the bishop again, and in some variations, the bishop is more active here than on b3. }
12... c5 { The usual plan. } 13. Nf3 Be6
{ It's important to get rid of the c4-bishop. } 14. Nd5
{ Taking control of the d5-square. } 14... Bxd5
{ This move doesn't look logical at first. However, after a forced line, we can equalize. In case of  14...Nbxd5  15.exd5  Bf5  , the  bishop is actively placed on c4.   With the bishop on c4,  14...Nfxd5  is ill-advised in view of  15.exd5  Bf5  16.Rc1  followed by c3 next, and the knight is in trouble. The only way to save it is by playing  16...a5  , which is a big positional concession, as it kills all of Black's counterplay on the queenside. White is much better. }
15. exd5 { 15.Bxd5  Nbxd5  16.exd5  Qd7  is totally fine for Black. } 15... b5
{ The point of Black's play. We're going to take the d5-pawn. } 16. axb5 axb5
17. Rxa8 Qxa8 18. Bxb5 { 18.Rxe7  bxc4  is fine, as we will  take d5 next. }
18... Nbxd5 { We finally take the d5-pawn. } 19. Bg3
{ Keeping an eye on the d6-pawn. } 19... Rb8
{ We need to activate the rook as well. We're going to play ...Bf8 and ...h6. It's not easy for White to attack the d5-knight once more. The position is balanced. }
