[Round "?"]
[White "7) 5.Bc4 Be7 6.O-O O-O 7.a4 − Alternative 7...c6"]
[Black "5.Bc4 Be7 6.O-O O-O 7.a4 | Alternative 7...c6 8.h3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. Bc4
{ The most played move. White is already threatening Ng5. } 5... Be7
{ Now we can parry Ng5 with ...O-O. } 6. O-O O-O 7. a4
{ A good prophylactic move. White can play a5 to gain some more space on the queenside, and also after ...c6, there is no ...b5. }
7... c6
{ This is the alternative recommendation against the main line Philidor. We still want to take on d4, but not immediately. We will also prepare it by playing ...a5 and securing the c5-square for the knight. }
8. h3
{ White prepares Be3 and also delays putting the rook on e1 as it may be more useful on d1. }
8... exd4
{ The right time to trade in the center.  8...a5  is too slow here because of  9.Be3  and White can take  on d4 with the bishop. }
9. Qxd4
{ This is the point of White's play: to go for a quick Rd1 and Bf4.  9.Nxd4  Nc5  10.Re1  a5  transposes to the 8.Re1 variation. }
9... Nc5 { We want ... Be6 and also after Bf4, there is ...Ne6. } 10. Rd1
{ Now Bf4 is a threat because after ...Ne6, there is Bxe6 and Bxd6, and e5 is a threat as well. }
10... Be6 { Our usual plan − our next moves could be ...a5, ...Re8. } 11. Bf4
{ Putting pressure on d6, but there is no threat yet, as the c4-bishop is hanging. It's too early for  11.a5  because of  11...Bxc4  12.Qxc4  b5  and Black is fine. }
11... a5
{ It's important to fix the queenside to stop White's ideas of b4 or a5. } 12.
Bg3 { The main move, safeguarding the bishop. White wants to take on e6. }
12... Bxc4 { The start of a forced sequence of moves. } 13. Qxc4 b5
{ A very surprising idea, but somehow it works. With this pawn break we change the character of the position, and we're counting on the fact that e4 is hanging. }
14. axb5 cxb5 15. Qxb5
{ If White doesn't take, we can push ...b4. If  15.Nxb5  , there is  15...Ncxe4  16.Bf4  Qb6  17.Be3  Qb7  . }
15... Nfxe4
{ Here, it doesn't matter with which knight we take with,  15...Ncxe4  is just the same. }
16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Bf4 { Keeping the bishop a bit more active. } 17... Re8
{ We're activating the rook, and later, we'll decide if we want to go ...Bf8 or ...Bf6. The position is balanced. The correspondence game ½-½ Gröller-Fursa, ICCF 2023, ended in a draw after  18.c3  Bf8  19.Ra2  Nc5  . }
*

