[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) 5.Bc4 Be7 6.O-O O-O 7.a4 − Alternative 7...c6"]
[Black "5.Bc4 Be7 6.O-O O-O 7.a4 | Alternative 7...c6 8.Re1 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. Bc4
{ The most played move. White is already threatening Ng5. } 5... Be7
{ Now we can parry Ng5 with ...O-O. } 6. O-O O-O 7. a4
{ A good prophylactic move. White can play a5 to gain some more space on the queenside, and also after ...c6, there is no ...b5. }
7... c6
{ This is the alternative recommendation against the main line Philidor. We still want to take on d4, but not immediately. We will also prepare it by playing ...a5 and securing the c5-square for the knight. }
8. Re1 { This is the main move. } 8... a5
{ We make sure that White never has b4 after we take on d4 and play ...Nc5. }
9. b3 { The idea is to fianchetto Bb2 or even go Ba3. } 9... exd4
{ The good thing about this line is that the idea is always the same − clearing the center and then going ...Ne5 or ...Nc5. }
10. Qxd4 { One of the possible captures. } 10... Ne5
{ Not really a pawn sacrifice, as it's not good for White to take the pawn. The usual plan with  10...Nc5  is not good here because of  11.Ba3!  Be6  12.Bxc5  . }
11. Be2 { White avoids doubling the pawns. } 11... Nfg4
{ The idea is to play ...Bf6 and then ...Nxf3+. } 12. Bb2
{ White has to cover the dark squares. } 12... Bf6 { Following the plan. } 13.
Qd2 { The best square for the queen. } 13... Nxf3+
{ It's a good moment to release the tension a bit.  13...Qb6  was played, but White just defends with  14.Rf1  . }
14. Bxf3 Bg5
{ We want to play ...Ne5, but including this move makes sure f4 is not so easy in the future for White. }
15. Qd1 Ne5 { The only move, but it was our plan anyway. } 16. Be2 f5
{ We need to react quickly before White prepares and goes f4. Black has easy play and soon will take over. }
*

