{ Now we want to exploit the fact the bishop is more vulnerable after ...Nc5.   In this case,  11...d5?!  is worse due to line  12.exd5  Nfxd5  13.Nxd5  Nxd5  14.Bf4  Bf6  15.Be5  Be6  16.Rad1  Bxe5  17.Qxe5  Qb8  18.Nd4  ,  and we don't have ...Nc3 as in the variation with  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/1p2bppp/1npp1n2/p7/P1BQP3/2N2N1P/1PP2PP1/R1B1R1K1 w - - 1 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Ba2  . }
12. Bf4 { Putting pressure on d6. } 12... Nc5 { This is our idea. } 13. Qe3
{ The only move that gives White a slight advantage. It's important to keep the d4-square for the knight. White also stops our idea of ...Ne6. }
13... Nxb3 { This bishop is strong, so we get rid of it. } 14. cxb3 Re8
{ We're eyeing the queen on the e-file. } 15. Rad1
{ Bringing the last piece into play. White is threatening Bxd6 and e5. } 15...
d5
{ Defending against the Bxd6 threat and hoping to activate the b6-knight. Black has the two bishops, and the b3-pawn could be weak in the long run. For now White has the more active pieces, but it's not easy to make something out of it.   Black had no problems in the correspondence game ½-½ Baltar-Díaz Castañet, ICCF 2024, after  16.Be5  Be6  17.Bd4  Ra6!   Another possible line is  16.exd5  Nxd5!  We need to trade this knight.  17.Nxd5  cxd5  18.Qd3  Be6  and Black is fine. }
