[White "7) 5.Bc4 Be7 6.O-O O-O 7.a4 − Alternative 7...c6"]
[Black "5.Bc4 Be7 6.O-O O-O 7.a4 | Alternative 7...c6 8.Re1 #22"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ White is going for an open game, taking control of the center right away. }
1... d6 { We're preparing ...Nf6 without allowing the e-pawn to move forward. }
2. d4 { White takes control of the whole center. } 2... Nf6
{ We're attacking the e4-pawn, forcing White to make a decision. } 3. Nc3
{ The most popular move by far. } 3... e5
{ The Philidor Defense. With our last move, we gain a foothold in the center. }
4. Nf3 { The main move. } 4... Nbd7 { We're defending the e5-pawn. } 5. Bc4
{ The most played move. White is already threatening Ng5. } 5... Be7
{ Now we can parry Ng5 with ...O-O. } 6. O-O O-O 7. a4
{ A good prophylactic move. White can play a5 to gain some more space on the queenside, and also after ...c6, there is no ...b5. }
7... c6
{ This is the alternative recommendation against the main line Philidor. We still want to take on d4, but not immediately. We will also prepare it by playing ...a5 and securing the c5-square for the knight. }
8. Re1 { This is the main move. } 8... a5
{ We make sure that White never has b4 after we take on d4 and play ...Nc5. }
9. h3 { A logical move, preparing Be3. } 9... exd4
{ The time has come to take on d4. } 10. Qxd4
{ An ambitious move, preparing Bf4 and Rad1. } 10... Nb6
{ Quite a rare idea. We're attacking the c4-bishop and preparing ...d5.  10...Nc5  11.Bf4  is not what we had in mind. }
11. Ba2
{ The more accurate approach, as after  11.Bb3  , there is  11...Nfd7  . }
11... d5
{ We need to break the center before White consolidates with Be3 and Rad1. }
12. exd5 Nfxd5 { 12...Nbxd5  is the same thing. } 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 { Forced. } 14.
Bf4
{ This is a novelty. White delays taking on d5 and wants to finish development first. }
14... Bf6 { Just activating the bishop. } 15. Be5 Be6
{ Reinforcing the knight on d5. } 16. Rad1
{ Keeping the tension and bringing the last piece into play. If  16.Bxf6  Qxf6  17.Qxf6  gxf6  , the endgame is fine for Black. }
16... Bxe5
{ Here, we need to be precise since White's pieces are very active. However, we have a solid position. }
17. Qxe5
{ Threatening c4. We can meet  17.Rxe5  with  17...h6  , controlling the important  square g5. }
17... Qb8
{ Another precise move, helping us reduce the tension in the position. Black is fine and a useful move is ...h6. A nice sample line goes  18.Nd4  Qxe5  19.Rxe5  Nc3!  , trading some pieces. }
