[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 1.d4 d6 − Early Deviations"]
[Black "1.d4 d6 2.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. g3
{ White doesn't stop ...e5, but this is a tricky move order, and it was played several times by GM Nils Grandelius. }
2... e5
{ Considering White hasn't stopped us from doing it, we go for it! If you don't remember the details of this line, or if you want to avoid some forced variations, you can go for  2...Nf6  , and it will probably transpose to the other lines. }
3. Bg2
{ White continues development and doesn't go for an endgame.  3.Nf3  was played sometimes, but it's not good, as we go  3...e4  followed  by ...d5. }
3... exd4
{ We want to bring the white queen in the center so we can attack it. } 4. Qxd4
Nc6 { Hitting the queen. } 5. Qd1
{ White retreats the queen without blocking the c1-bishop.  5.Qd2  is also possible, but we can go  5...g6  , ...Bg7 and ...Nf6 as in the main line. }
5... Nf6
{ We want to finish the kingside development with ...g6, ...Bg7, and O-O. It is also possible to start with  5...g6  . }
6. Nc3
{ White avoids playing c4 and wants to get a grip in the center after e4 and Nge2.   6.Nf3  was played most often, but it would transpose to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/3p4/8/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c4  e5  after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/8/8/5NP1/PPP1PPBP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...g6  7.O-O  Bg7  8.c4  O-O  9.Nc3  Re8  . }
6... g6 { Continuing our plan. } 7. e4
{ White needs a foothold in the center. } 7... Bg7 8. Nge2 O-O 9. O-O
{ Both sides have developed their kingside. } 9... Re8
{ Putting the rook on an open file. } 10. h3
{ A useful move, controlling the g4-square. } 10... Rb8
{ Now that all the pieces are in good positions, we can try to push ...b5 or ...b6, without allowing e5. The position is about equal, but there is a lot of play ahead. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 1.d4 d6 − Early Deviations"]
[Black "1.d4 d6 2.g3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. g3
{ White doesn't stop ...e5, but this is a tricky move order, and it was played several times by GM Nils Grandelius. }
2... e5
{ Considering White hasn't stopped us from doing it, we go for it! If you don't remember the details of this line, or if you want to avoid some forced variations, you can go for  2...Nf6  , and it will probably transpose to the other lines. }
3. dxe5
{ The most principled move. This is one of the best cases when White can take on e5, as there is no pawn on c4 that may be weak. }
3... dxe5 4. Qxd8+
{ Of course, White trades the queens, hoping for a better endgame. } 4... Kxd8
5. Bg2
{ This was also often played, but it's less flexible because White doesn't have Bh3 options. }
5... c6 { Shutting off the bishop and controlling the important d5-square. } 6.
Nc3 { White is developing and wants to go f4 next. } 6... Nd7
{ We use the same setup as in the main line. } 7. f4
{ White opens up the game before we coordinate our pieces. } 7... Ngf6
{ Developing the other knight as well. } 8. Nf3 { Attacking e5. } 8... Bd6
{ We continue our development and protect e5. Compared to the main line it's important that White doesn't have Nb5 here. }
