3. dxe5
{ The most principled move. This is one of the best cases when White can take on e5, as there is no pawn on c4 that may be weak. }
3... dxe5 4. Qxd8+
{ Of course, White trades the queens, hoping for a better endgame. } 4... Kxd8
5. Nc3
{ This is more flexible than Bg2, as in some cases the bishop may go to h3. White intends to continue f4, or develop the bishop and go O-O-O. }
5... Nd7
{ The idea is to delay ...Nf6 for a moment so that White doesn't have Bg5. } 6.
f4
{ The critical continuation. White is intending to put a lot of pressure on the center with f4 and Nf3. }
6... Ngf6
{ We need to develop the knight quickly. If we manage to stabilize the position, we'll have a great game, but for now, we need to be precise; every tempo counts. }
7. Nf3 { Renewing the threat on e5. } 7... exf4
{ We must go for this; otherwise, we get a worse position.  7...Bd6  doesn't work because of  8.Nb5  . }
8. Bxf4
{ White is playing for a quick development but leaves weaknesses in the pawn structure. }
8... Bb4 { We want to take the knight before it comes to b5. } 9. O-O-O
{ Continuing the quick development. } 9... Bxc3
{ Destroying White's pawn structure even more. } 10. bxc3 Ne4
{ The knight is great here, and it's keeping our position together. White still has some lead in development, but in the longer term, we can take advantage of the weak pawn structure. }
*

