[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. Bg5
{ White is stopping our ideas of ...e5 and ...Nf6. However, the bishop is not threatening anything right now and can be attacked with ...h6 and ...g5. }
2... h6
{ Hitting the bishop at once. Of course, we don't play  2...Nf6  because we'd give White the option to double our pawns. }
3. Bh4 c5 { Challenging the center right away; ...Qb6 is our idea. } 4. dxc5
{ Otherwise ...Qb6 is annoying. } 4... g5
{ A good in-between move to prepare ...Bg7. } 5. Bg3 Qa5+
{ We're getting back the pawn using this check. It's important to keep the pawn on d6 to restrict White's bishop. Black has a comfortable position. }
