{ We also want to go for the double fianchetto, and we seize some space on the queenside. White cannot make good use of the discovered attack on the h1-a8 diagonal. }
7. a4 { White is immediately forcing us to make a decision with the b-pawn. }
7... b4 { A good move, getting some space and taking away the c3-square. } 8.
Ne1
{ White is clearing the long diagonal and wants to bring the knight to d3 to attack the b4-pawn.   8.Ne5?  is just bad because of  8...dxe5  9.Bxa8  exd4  with a dominating position. }
8... c6
{ We need to protect the rook. If allowed, we want to play ...a5 to secure the b4-pawn. }
9. a5 { The only critical continuation, isolating the b4-pawn. } 9... Bf5
{ Stopping e4 and developing the bishop. } 10. Nd3
{ The most ambitious move, attacking b4, and it seems there is no good way to defend it. }
10... Na6
{ We're sacrificing c6, but we'll open the c-file and be able to attack c2. It's important to keep the b4-pawn because it's restricting White's pieces. }
11. Bxc6 Rb8
{ Not only defending the rook but also preventing Bb7 as well. We want to follow up with ...d5 or ...Qc7 and ...Rfc8. Black is already preferable. }
