[White "8) 1.d4 d6 − Early Deviations"]
[Black "1.d4 d6 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. Nf3 { White is stopping ...e5 and does not want to commit to e4 yet. } 2...
Nf6
{ Now we stop e4, and we want to play ...g6 and ...Bg7 and reach a King's Indian where White's options are limited because the knight is already on f3. }
3. Bg5
{ A Trompowsky-style move. White is putting pressure on our center and can consider taking on f6. }
3... Nbd7
{ We want to be able to recapture on f6 with the knight. We're also preparing ...h6 to chase the bishop or ...e5. }
4. Nc3 { Trying to get e4. } 4... h6
{ We're chasing the bishop. There is nothing wrong with  4...e5  5.e4  transposing to the Philidor.   4...h6  is a smart move to include because it forces White to either give up the bishop pair  or retreat the bishop and give us options of ...g5. }
5. Bh4
{ White tries to keep the bishop for now. If  5.Bf4  , we can go  5...c5  and transpose to the main line with  an extra ...h6.   5.Bxf6  gives up any hope for an opening advantage, and after  5...Nxf6  6.e4  c6  7.e5  dxe5  8.dxe5  Nd5  , Black has no problems whatsoever. }
5... g5 { We go after the bishop. } 6. Bg3 Nh5
{ The bishop has nowhere to go, but we don't hurry to take it yet. } 7. e4
{ Getting the center, but we can target it later. } 7... Bg7
{ The bishop is targeting the white center from afar. } 8. Bc4 e6
{ It's good to shut off the light-squared bishop. We will take on g3 in the next moves. We have a comfortable position. We can go ...a6, ...Qe7, and so on. }
