{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. Nf3 { White is stopping ...e5 and does not want to commit to e4 yet. } 2...
Nf6
{ Now we stop e4, and we want to play ...g6 and ...Bg7 and reach a King's Indian where White's options are limited because the knight is already on f3. }
3. e3 { A modest approach, keeping the c1-bishop locked. } 3... g6
{ We continue with the usual King's Indian setup. } 4. Be2
{ The bishop is less exposed here than on d3.  4.c4  Bg7  5.Nc3  O-O  6.Be2  Bf5  would transpose. }
4... Bg7 5. b3
{ White wants to fianchetto the bishop. Again,  5.O-O  O-O  6.c4  Bf5  7.Nc3  would transpose. }
5... O-O 6. Bb2 Nc6
{ Our idea will be to play ...e5, but we need to prepare it first. The knight is well placed here, and it's not good for White to go  7.d5  in view of  7...Nb8  followed by ...c6. }
7. O-O Bf5 { We want to develop all the pieces. } 8. c4
{ White wants to follow up with Nc3. } 8... e5
{ This is an important move to remember, but it solves all the problems instantly. }
9. dxe5
{ Otherwise, we can go ...e4 or ...exd4 with a great position.   9.d5  Nb8  would lead to a great version of the KID. We can follow  up with ...a5 and ...Na6 later on. }
9... dxe5 10. Nxe5 { Too greedy, but Black was already better. } 10... Qxd1
{ The tactics work in Black's favor. } 11. Rxd1 Ng4
{ With a winning position for Black. White loses at least an exchange. } *

