1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. Nf3 { White is stopping ...e5 and does not want to commit to e4 yet. } 2...
Nf6
{ Now we stop e4, and we want to play ...g6 and ...Bg7 and reach a King's Indian where White's options are limited because the knight is already on f3. }
3. Nbd2 { A modest move compared to  3.Nc3  ,  but trying to go e4 anyway. }
3... Bf5 { A logical move, stopping e4. } 4. g3
{ White goes for a solid fianchetto setup. If  4.Nh4  , we go  4...Bd7  followed by ...e5. The h4-knight is misplaced. }
4... h6
{ A useful prophylactic move. We need the h7-square for the bishop to control e4. }
5. Bg2 Bh7
{ Preventing Nh4 and e4. If White gets e4 later on, it will not come with tempo. }
6. O-O c6
{ Considering that White played a passive setup, we can continue with ...d5 and ...e6. The point of our strategy is that our h7-bishop will be more active than its counterpart on g2. }
7. Re1 { Trying to go e4. } 7... d5
{ Even though we spent a move on ...d6-d5, our position is quite comfortable. We will follow up with ...e6, ...Be7, ...O-O, ...Nbd7, and all our pieces are on good squares. }
