1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. Nc3 Nf6
{ This looks natural, inviting White to transpose to the Philidor after  3.e4  . }
3. Bg5
{ With this move, White wants to make ...e5 more difficult for us because of the pin. }
3... Nbd7
{ We don't want to allow White to spoil our structure. Also, we want to play ...e5, or harass the bishop with ...h6 and ...g5. }
4. Nf3
{ Developing the pieces. If  4.e4  , we go  4...e5  , and we have a great version of the  Philidor, as the bishop is misplaced on g5. }
4... h6
{ We have transposed to the 2.Nf3 move order.   We're chasing the bishop. There is nothing wrong with  4...e5  5.e4  transposing to the Philidor.   4...h6  is a smart move to include because it forces White to either give up the bishop pair  or retreat the bishop and give us options of ...g5. }
