1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. Bf4
{ Very often, White players go for the London setup against everything. Considering we play ...d6, we're immediately trying to exploit White's setup by getting ...e5 with tempo. }
2... Nd7 { Preparing ...e5 at the right moment. } 3. Nf3
{ White parries ...e5 and develops the pieces. } 3... Ngf6
{ Considering we can't play ...e5 anymore, we switch to the ...c5 idea. We're also stopping e4 for now. }
4. Nc3
{ This is an ambitious and concrete move. White is already threatening to play e4 and take full control over the center. }
4... c5
{ We have to react quickly in the center; otherwise, we just get suffocated. }
5. e3
{ White can go for a setup with h3, Be2, O-O, Qd2, Rfe1, Rad1. However, it doesn't look very ambitious because the pawn is on c2, not fighting for the center. }
5... g6 { We can go for the fianchetto setup. } 6. h3
{ This is a useful move so that the bishop can go to h2 if attacked. } 6... Bg7
7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O { Both sides are finishing their development. } 8... a6
{ Trying to go ...b5. } 9. a4 { The only way to stop ...b5. } 9... cxd4
{ It is important to take on d4. If  9...b6  immediately, there is  10.d5! }
10. exd4 b6 { Going for the double fianchetto. } 11. Re1
{ The rook belongs on the open file. } 11... Bb7 12. Qd2 Rc8
{ Activating the rook, although there are no clear targets yet. } 13. Rad1 Re8
{ Both sides finished development and activated their pieces. The real fight is starting from now on, and Black is fine. }
