1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. Bf4
{ Very often, White players go for the London setup against everything. Considering we play ...d6, we're immediately trying to exploit White's setup by getting ...e5 with tempo. }
2... Nd7 { Preparing ...e5 at the right moment. } 3. Nf3
{ White parries ...e5 and develops the pieces. } 3... Ngf6
{ Considering we can't play ...e5 anymore, we switch to the ...c5 idea. We're also stopping e4 for now. }
4. h3
{ The more precise version of the London setup because we can't go ...Nh5 to take the bishop. }
4... g6
{ We intend to finish development with ...Bg7, ...O-O, and then ...b6 and ...Bb7. The double fianchetto setup cannot be bad! }
5. e3 Bg7 6. Be2
{ This is the best square for the bishop. Even if it looks more active on d3, the bishop may come under attack after ...e5 and ...e4, as it happens in many internet games. }
6... O-O 7. O-O b6
{ Going for the double fianchetto. White will not be able to go for e4 after this. }
8. a4
{ This is the other typical plan where White doesn't go for c4. It's also possible to play without including a4 and ...a5. }
8... a5 { Let's just stop the white pawn. } 9. c3
{ Typical London system setup; White is consolidating the center.  9.Nc3  is also possible, but the resulting positions don't change much, as we can continue with  9...Bb7  and ...Ne4. }
9... Bb7 { All according to plan. } 10. Bh2
{ Staying flexible. White keeps an option to develop the knight to either d2 or a3. }
10... Ne4
{ Our plan remains the same no matter what White does − we go ...Ne4 and ...e5. }
11. Nbd2
{ It makes sense to challenge our central knight.  11.Na3  is also possible, but it doesn't change our plan − we go  11...e5  . }
11... Nxd2 { We may as well trade the knights here. } 12. Nxd2 e5
{ The good old plan to shut off the bishop on h2. } 13. Bf3 Qc8
{ This is the typical move we recommend after Bf3. Our plan is to go ...Re8. In these positions, we refrain from playing ...e4 so as not to open up White's dark-squared bishop. }
