[White "10) KID Fianchetto 4.g3 and 4.Nc3 Bg7 5.g3"]
[Black "KID Fianchetto 4.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. Nf3 { White is stopping ...e5 and does not want to commit to e4 yet. } 2...
Nf6
{ Now we stop e4, and we want to play ...g6 and ...Bg7 and reach a King's Indian where White's options are limited because the knight is already on f3. }
3. c4 g6 4. g3
{ Here, we will see the lines in the fianchetto setup where White delays playing Nc3. }
4... Bg7 5. Bg2 Bf5
{ This is a good moment to play ...Bf5.   If  5...O-O  , there is  6.Nc3  Bf5  and here White has  7.Nh4  and we have to go back  7...Bc8  and then White can go  8.O-O  . With the given move order, we're trying to avoid this. }
6. Qb3
{ An interesting way to take advantage of the early bishop sortie ...Bf5. White is attacking b7, and it's not so easy to defend the pawn.   6.Nc3  Ne4  transposes to the 4.Nc3 line. }
6... Qc8
{ We're defending the b7-pawn and we can still react with ...Be4 to Nh4. } 7.
Nc3 { The most logical move, threatening Nh4. } 7... Nc6
{ We're covering the b7-pawn and put some pressure on the d4-pawn.   7...c6  8.O-O  Ne4  is also possible, but a bit passive. }
8. d5 { The only ambitious try, gaining space with tempo. } 8... Nd8
{ Black had to make a concession anyway. The knight is misplaced on d8, but it defends the b7-pawn.   8...Nb8  is also possible, but then after  9.Nd4  , we would have to go back  9...Bd7  . }
9. O-O O-O { Both sides bring their king to safety. } 10. Re1
{ A logical move, preparing e4. } 10... Ne4
{ We finally managed to play our idea. Now the g7-bishop is open. Black still needs to find a way to bring the d8-knight into play. Black went on to win a nice game in 0-1 Donchenko-Giri, Wijk aan Zee 2024. }
