[White "10) KID Fianchetto 4.g3 and 4.Nc3 Bg7 5.g3"]
[Black "KID Fianchetto 4.g3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. Nf3 { White is stopping ...e5 and does not want to commit to e4 yet. } 2...
Nf6
{ Now we stop e4, and we want to play ...g6 and ...Bg7 and reach a King's Indian where White's options are limited because the knight is already on f3. }
3. c4 g6 4. g3
{ Here, we will see the lines in the fianchetto setup where White delays playing Nc3. }
4... Bg7 5. Bg2 Bf5
{ This is a good moment to play ...Bf5.   If  5...O-O  , there is  6.Nc3  Bf5  and here White has  7.Nh4  and we have to go back  7...Bc8  and then White can go  8.O-O  . With the given move order, we're trying to avoid this. }
6. Nh4 { This was tried sometimes.  6.Nc3  Ne4  transposes to the 4.Nc3 line. }
6... Be4 { Of course, we want to trade the strong g2-bishop. } 7. Nf3
{ Going for the move repetition. } 7... c6
{ We're trying to keep the game going, but we can settle for a draw with  7...Bf5  . }
8. Nc3
{ Attacking the bishop and taking advantage of the fact that we don't have ...Ne4 anymore. }
8... O-O 9. O-O Nbd7
{ Bringing the last piece into play. Sooner or later White will take the bishop, then we will recapture with the knight and play ...f5 and maybe even ...e5; ...a5 is also a useful move in this position, especially after b3. White will get the bishop pair, but the position is playable for both sides. We think Black is fine. }
