[White "10) KID Fianchetto 4.g3 and 4.Nc3 Bg7 5.g3"]
[Black "KID Fianchetto 4.g3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. Nf3 { White is stopping ...e5 and does not want to commit to e4 yet. } 2...
Nf6
{ Now we stop e4, and we want to play ...g6 and ...Bg7 and reach a King's Indian where White's options are limited because the knight is already on f3. }
3. c4 g6 4. g3
{ Here, we will see the lines in the fianchetto setup where White delays playing Nc3. }
4... Bg7 5. Bg2 Bf5
{ This is a good moment to play ...Bf5.   If  5...O-O  , there is  6.Nc3  Bf5  and here White has  7.Nh4  and we have to go back  7...Bc8  and then White can go  8.O-O  . With the given move order, we're trying to avoid this. }
6. O-O { This was seen most often.  6.Nc3  Ne4  transposes to the 4.Nc3 line. }
6... O-O 7. Nc3
{ A very logical move. Here, we will only see the differences in the lines where the castle for both sides was not included. }
7... Ne4 { This is our idea. } 8. Nb1
{ The difference to the line without mutual castling included is that after ...c6, there is no more check on a5. All the other moves like  8.Nd5  or  8.Nh4  would most likely transpose. }
8... e5
{ An interesting way to keep the game going. If you want, you can repeat moves with  8...Nf6  . }
9. dxe5 { White takes the pawn, trying to go Nh4 after ...dxe5. } 9... Nc6
{ Bringing the last piece into play. We're sacrificing a pawn but getting a huge development lead in return. }
10. Nh4
{ Going after the f5-bishop. Of course,  10.exd6  is tempting, but then after  10...Qxd6  , all of Black's pieces are active giving a huge compensation. }
10... dxe5 { We're getting the pawn back. We still have a development lead. }
11. Qxd8
{ White is going for g4 to grab a piece. Now the h4-knight is not under attack anymore. }
11... Raxd8
{ This is the right recapture, as the rook is more useful on f8 than on a8. }
12. g4 { This is the idea − White wins a piece. } 12... Bxg4
{ We're taking some material back for the piece and counting on the development lead. }
13. Bxe4 Nd4
{ It's good to remember this precise move. It's better to take on e2 with the knight, if possible. Black has many threats, and surely enough compensation for the piece. }
