{ It's good to block the long diagonal since we give up the light-squared bishop. }
10. Nxe4 { White has to take the bishop sooner or later. } 10... Nxe4 11. Nd2
{ One of several options in this position. White wants to trade the knights and play the position with the bishop pair.   In case of both  11.Qc2  or  11.Qd3  , we can go for  11...d5  − the solid choice, reinforcing the knight, or even  11...f5  , and we can follow up  with ...e6 and ...d5. For example,  @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/pp1nppbp/2pp2p1/8/2PPn3/5NP1/PP2PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Qd3  f5  12.Ng5  Nxg5  13.Bxg5  h6  14.Bd2  e5  with a Dutch setup, which is good for Black. }
11... Nxd2 12. Qxd2 a5
{ We're seizing space on the queenside; ...a4 and ...Qb6 are useful moves. We have active pieces and a solid position, and it won't be easy for White to take advantage of the bishop pair. }
