[White "10) KID Fianchetto 4.g3 and 4.Nc3 Bg7 5.g3"]
[Black "KID Fianchetto 4.Nc3 Bg7 5.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. Nf3 { White is stopping ...e5 and does not want to commit to e4 yet. } 2...
Nf6
{ Now we stop e4, and we want to play ...g6 and ...Bg7 and reach a King's Indian where White's options are limited because the knight is already on f3. }
3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. g3
{ White is going for the fianchetto setup, one of the most solid and popular lines against the King's Indian. }
5... Bf5
{ We decided to recommend this rare sideline, considering it has a clear strategic idea we've seen before − taking control of the e4-square. }
6. Nh4 { White immediately reacts before we are in time to go ...Ne4. } 6...
Be6
{ This is a novelty. We're attacking c4 and hoping to disrupt White's normal development. }
7. e4
{ The more ambitious reply when compared to Bg2, which is considered in the next variation. However, it's not easy to develop the bishop on g2 because c4 is hanging. }
7... O-O 8. f4
{ White gets control of the whole center. If White goes  8.h3  to prevent ...Bg4, then we play  8...Bd7  followed by ...e5, with a good version of the King's Indian. }
8... Bg4
{ The white queen will be misplaced, and we can play either ...Nc6 or ...Na6 afterwards. In some positions, we can play ...e5 later on. }
