[Black "KID 1.d4 d6 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.c4 g6 4.Nc3 Bg7 5.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. Nf3 { White is stopping ...e5 and does not want to commit to e4 yet. } 2...
Nf6
{ Now we stop e4, and we want to play ...g6 and ...Bg7 and reach a King's Indian where White's options are limited because the knight is already on f3. }
3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. Bg5
{ An interesting sideline, trying to avoid the main line theory. White's plan is to follow up with e3, Be2, O-O and so on. This is given by GM Adrien Demuth in his Chessable course The Solid 1.d4 − Part 2. }
5... Bf5
{ This rare sideline was not analyzed in the aforementioned course. However, this move has a clear idea: stopping e4 and preparing ...Ne4. This is the same idea that we recommend against the setups with g3. }
6. Nd2
{ A logical move, stopping ...Ne4 and preparing e4. However, now we can get the dark-squared bishop. }
6... h6 { Going after the dark-squared bishop. } 7. Bh4 g5
{ We continue chasing the bishop. } 8. Bg3 Nh5
{ We'll take the bishop on the next move and play ...c5 to open up our bishop. We already prefer Black's position. }
