5... O-O
{ We cannot go  5...Bf5  yet because after  6.Bd3  , White would have some positional advantage. }
6. Be2
{ A good place for the bishop. On d3 the bishop would be exposed to ...e5-e4 @@StartBracket@@after ...Re8@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Bf5
{ Now we can go for our ...Bf5 setup. The idea is to play ...Ne4.   It's also possible to play in King's Indian fashion with  6...Nbd7  7.O-O  e5  . }
7. Nd2
{ White prevents ...Ne4 and can consider e4 at some point. However, the knight looks misplaced.   7.Nh4  is a possibility, but we can go  7...Bd7  with the idea ...e5 or ...a5. }
7... e5 { Black takes the opportunity to go for this. } 8. d5
{ The only logical move, seizing some space. } 8... a5
{ Now we want to play in a normal King's Indian fashion with ...Na6-c5. } 9. e4
{ Consolidating the center, but we have a favorable King's Indian. } 9... Bd7
10. Nf1 { Rerouting the knight and opening up the bishop. } 10... Na6 11. g4
{ Seizing space on the kingside and making sure that Black doesn't have ...f5. }
11... c6 { We want to open up the game. } 12. Ng3
{ The logical follow-up after g4. } 12... cxd5
{ We open up the position due to the lead in development. } 13. exd5
{ Trying to keep the c-file closed. } 13... Nc5
{ Black got a nice position in 1-0 Royal-Thybo, Nova Gorica 2022 but went on to lose. White's plan was slow, and the king would be unsafe wherever it went. We have some nice ideas like ...e4 or ...a4. }
