{ By far the main line of the King's Indian Defense, seizing the whole center. }
5... Bg4
{ This is the move we recommend. We chose a sideline with a clear strategic plan, in which, with precise play, White will be a bit better, but Black will always have good winning chances. We aim for positions where the center gets blocked after ...e5 and d5, and we trade the light-squared bishop for the knight. }
6. Qb3
{ White wants to exploit the moving of the bishop to g4 by immediately putting pressure on b7. }
6... O-O { We go for quick development, not bothering to defend the pawn. } 7.
e5
{ This was tried in 1-0 Morozov-Macovei, Vinnytsia 2016. Before taking on b7, White is hitting the f6-knight. Another idea of this move is that after taking on b7, White avoids the pawn doubling after ...Bxf3 since there is Qxf3. }
7... dxe5
{ It's good to open up the position, as the white king is still in the center. }
8. dxe5 Ne8
{ The best square for the knight in this case. After Qxb7, we need to have the d7-square available for the b8-knight. }
9. Qxb7 { White takes the pawn; if not, we go ...Nc6. } 9... Nd7
{ White is in trouble. The e5-pawn will fall, and White doesn't have development. }
