{ Now we stop e4, and we want to play ...g6 and ...Bg7 and reach a King's Indian where White's options are limited because the knight is already on f3. }
3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4
{ By far the main line of the King's Indian Defense, seizing the whole center. }
5... Bg4
{ This is the move we recommend. We chose a sideline with a clear strategic plan, in which, with precise play, White will be a bit better, but Black will always have good winning chances. We aim for positions where the center gets blocked after ...e5 and d5, and we trade the light-squared bishop for the knight. }
6. Be2
{ The main and most logical move. White wants to recapture with the bishop on f3. }
6... Bxf3
{ his is the strategic point of the line. We get rid of the knight in order to go ...e5 afterwards. }
7. gxf3
{ It's highly unlikely you'll ever see this move on the board, although it's not bad. White's idea is to stop  7...e5  due to  8.dxe5  dxe5  9.Qxd8+  Kxd8  10.f4  . }
7... Nfd7 { An important move to remember, trying to go ...Nc6-d4. } 8. f4
{ A good move, stopping  8...e5  because of  9.fxe5  dxe5  10.d5  , when White seizes a lot of space and gets rid of the doubled pawns. It has only been played once in practice so far. }
8... Nc6 { Attacking d4. } 9. e5
{ White is shutting off the g7-bishop and also stopping ...e5 once and for all.  9.d5  is not so good because of  9...Nd4  followed  by ...Nxe2 or ...e5. }
9... e6
{ Fixing the pawn structure and making the idea to play ...Ne7 available. If White doesn't play h4, we can go ...dxe5 followed by ...Qh4. }
10. Be3 { A normal developing move. } 10... dxe5
{ It's important to include this to prevent d5 @@StartBracket@@the e5-pawn would fall@@EndBracket@@. }
11. fxe5
{ The more ambitious capture, getting rid of the doubled pawns. If  11.dxe5  , there is  11...f6  and we break the center anyway. }
11... Qh4 { Activating the queen and preparing ...O-O-O. } 12. Qd2
{ Preparing to castle long. } 12... O-O-O
{ We're threatening ...Ndxe5 and we're not afraid of Bg5 ideas. The position is completely double-edged, but we like Black's position because of the safer king.   Just to eliminate any trace of worry, after  13.Bg5  Qxd4  14.Qxd4  Nxd4  15.Bxd8  Rxd8  @@StartBracket@@Not  15...Nc2+?  16.Kd2  Nxa1  17.Bg5  and the  knight is trapped on a1.  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@2kr4/pppn1pbp/4p1p1/4P3/2Pn4/2N5/PP2BP1P/R3K2R w KQ - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Rd1  Bxe5  , Black has two pawns for the exchange and well-coordinated pieces. The engines already consider White's position as nearly lost, as the positional exchange sacrifice will tell in the long run. }
