{ Now we stop e4, and we want to play ...g6 and ...Bg7 and reach a King's Indian where White's options are limited because the knight is already on f3. }
3. c4 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4
{ By far the main line of the King's Indian Defense, seizing the whole center. }
5... Bg4
{ This is the move we recommend. We chose a sideline with a clear strategic plan, in which, with precise play, White will be a bit better, but Black will always have good winning chances. We aim for positions where the center gets blocked after ...e5 and d5, and we trade the light-squared bishop for the knight. }
6. Be2
{ The main and most logical move. White wants to recapture with the bishop on f3. }
6... Bxf3
{ his is the strategic point of the line. We get rid of the knight in order to go ...e5 afterwards. }
7. Bxf3
{ The natural recapture, not spoiling the pawn structure. It was played in almost all the games. }
7... e5 { We're fighting for the center and we want to play ...Nc6. } 8. d5
{ The logical move, stopping ...Nc6. } 8... h5
{ Without this move, our strategy makes no sense. We will get rid of the dark-squared bishop by playing ...Bh6. }
9. Be3
{ This is surely not the most precise move because, after ...Bh6, White will have to spend one more move with the bishop. }
9... Bh6
{ This is a necessity, as after Qd2, we'll not be able to trade the bishops anymore. }
10. Bxh6 { White is forcing our rook to a bad square. } 10... Rxh6 11. Qd2
{ A natural move, attacking the rook with tempo. This was played in almost all the games from this position. }
11... Rh8 12. h4
{ It makes sense to go h4 and g3 to fix our pawns on the kingside. } 12... Nbd7
{ Black has a comfortable position. We will play ...Kf8-g7 to connect the rooks, then ...Qe7 and ...c6; ...a5 and ...Nc5 is also a good plan if White allows it. }
