{ Very tempting, immediately attacking our pawn. Instead,  13.Be3  would lead to similar positions after  13...Nc5  14.Qc2  Ke7  . }
13... Ke7
{ Obviously! The king is safe on e7, defending the pawn on d6. We intend to follow up with ...Nc5 and ...Bh6 if possible. }
14. Bd2
{ The idea is to play Bc3 or even b4 in some lines.  14.Be3  looks natural, but we just go for the same plan:  14...Nc5  15.Qc2  b6  followed by ...Qd7. }
14... Nc5 { This comes with tempo. } 15. Qc2 Qd7
{ We're ready to bring a rook to c8. } 16. O-O Bh6
{ This is a good moment to try to trade the bishops. } 17. Bc3
{ This is White's plan − to save the bishop. We're not worried about  17.Bxh6  Rxh6  18.Qd2  Rhh8  19.Qg5  , pinning our knight, because of  19...Qd8  20.Rfc1  b6  followed by ...Kf8. }
17... b6
{ Consolidating our queenside and preventing @@StartFEN@@r6r/1p1qkp2/3p1npb/pNnPp2p/P3P3/2B2B2/1PQ2PPP/R4RK1 w - - 9 18@@EndFEN@@  18.Bxe5  .  Even though White has the bishop pair, our h6-bishop is active and controls c1. We can follow up with ...h4, ...Kf8-g7, or put a rook on c8, depending on what White does. }
