[White "13) English Rat Defense 1.d4 d6 2.c4 e5"]
[Black "English Rat Defense 1.d4 d6 2.c4 e5 3.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. c4
{ White's idea is to play Nc3 and e4, and delay the development of the knight to f3. We are already happy to see this because it allows us to play ...e5. }
2... e5
{ Of course, we go for this. The whole point of ...d6 is to go ...e5 whenever possible and control the center. }
3. Nc3
{ This move was popular back in the day. White is trying to go for a quick development. However, people understood recently that Black is totally fine, but we need to be precise. }
3... exd4 { We take the pawn because our next move will come with tempo. } 4.
Qxd4 Nc6
{ This is our idea, forcing White to move the queen again. By putting the knight on c6, we won't have such good control over d5 in the longer term, so that's why we need to act quickly. }
5. Qd1
{ After this White is going to develop the bishop on the c1-h6 diagonal. } 5...
g6 { The bishop will be good on the long diagonal. } 6. e4
{ White is seizing space and taking control of the center, but also weakening the d4-square. }
6... Bg7 { Sometimes there are ideas to take on c3, although it's risky. } 7.
Be3 { This natural move allows us to destroy White's pawn structure. } 7...
Bxc3+
{ We're spoiling White's pawn structure and this works because of our lead in development. However, if you consider this risky, there is nothing wrong with the natural  7...Nf6  . }
8. bxc3 Nf6
{ Black is already a bit better because of the fractured pawn structure. We can attack the c4-pawn quite quickly. Also, it's not easy for White to develop. Our possible ideas are ...Be6, ...Qe7, or ...Ng4, depending on what White does. }
