[Black "English Rat Defense 1.d4 d6 2.c4 e5 3.Nc3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. c4
{ White's idea is to play Nc3 and e4, and delay the development of the knight to f3. We are already happy to see this because it allows us to play ...e5. }
2... e5
{ Of course, we go for this. The whole point of ...d6 is to go ...e5 whenever possible and control the center. }
3. Nc3
{ This move was popular back in the day. White is trying to go for a quick development. However, people understood recently that Black is totally fine, but we need to be precise. }
3... exd4 { We take the pawn because our next move will come with tempo. } 4.
Qxd4 Nc6
{ This is our idea, forcing White to move the queen again. By putting the knight on c6, we won't have such good control over d5 in the longer term, so that's why we need to act quickly. }
5. Qd1
{ After this White is going to develop the bishop on the c1-h6 diagonal. } 5...
g6 { The bishop will be good on the long diagonal. } 6. e4
{ White is seizing space and taking control of the center, but also weakening the d4-square. }
6... Bg7 { Sometimes there are ideas to take on c3, although it's risky. } 7.
Bd3 { Reinforcing the e4-pawn and trying to finish development with Nge2. }
7... Nf6 8. Nge2 O-O
{ Both sides are making natural moves, finishing development. Black has a sound setup. }
9. O-O Ne5
{ We want to take the bishop pair. Of course, other moves are possible as well, like  9...Re8  . }
10. b3
{ The plan is to save the bishop on the next move with Bc2, and if we take on d3 now, it's a bit early. White gets a grip in the center. }
10... b5
{ We recommend this novelty to destroy White's pawn center. The pawn sacrifice is just temporary, as White cannot really keep it. }
11. cxb5
{ White takes the pawn. The other capture  11.Nxb5?  is bad because of  11...Nxd3  12.Qxd3  Nxe4  13.Qxe4  , and now there is  13...Bf5!  with tempo, attacking the queen and defending  the a8-rook. On the next move we take the rook on a1, with a material advantage. }
11... a6
{ This is the point of the previous move. We're trying to activate our light-squared bishop and open the a-file. }
12. Bc2
{ White is trying to preserve the bishop and keep the pawn, but we will gain additional tempi. }
12... axb5 13. Nxb5 Ba6
{ This comes with tempo, and the bishop will be active here. } 14. Nbc3
{ The only move. } 14... c6
{ The idea is to play ...d5 or ...Re8. Even though we're a pawn down, our pieces are very active, and we have easy play. }
