[Black "English Rat Defense 1.d4 d6 2.c4 e5 3.Nc3 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. c4
{ White's idea is to play Nc3 and e4, and delay the development of the knight to f3. We are already happy to see this because it allows us to play ...e5. }
2... e5
{ Of course, we go for this. The whole point of ...d6 is to go ...e5 whenever possible and control the center. }
3. Nc3
{ This move was popular back in the day. White is trying to go for a quick development. However, people understood recently that Black is totally fine, but we need to be precise. }
3... exd4 { We take the pawn because our next move will come with tempo. } 4.
Qxd4 Nc6
{ This is our idea, forcing White to move the queen again. By putting the knight on c6, we won't have such good control over d5 in the longer term, so that's why we need to act quickly. }
5. Qd2
{ The most natural retreat; the queen is already developed here. White's idea is to go b3, Bb2 and get a grip on the position. }
5... Nf6
{ An important move to remember, but also the most logical one.  5...g6  allows White to achieve their setup after  6.b3  . In some  lines, we need the bishop to go to b4, as you will see further on. }
6. g3
{ This is the right strategy, as the bishop will be well placed on the long diagonal, putting pressure on our position. }
6... Be6
{ The c4-pawn is not defended, and White has to do something about it. There is also the idea to push ...d5. }
7. e4 { White defends the c4-pawn and prevents ...d5. } 7... Be7
{ In this case, the bishop is better here than on g7. } 8. b3
{ A natural move defending c4 and getting ready to fianchetto the bishops. However, this is a blunder because it allows us a nice tactical trick.   8.Nf3  is the better move, but Black has a nice position after  8...O-O  . }
8... Nxe4
{ A tactical strike out of the blue! We're opening up the game while White is still unprepared. }
9. Nxe4 d5
{ This is the point! We're opening up the position with multiple threats. White cannot parry ...Bb4 in a good way. Black is totally winning. }
