{ This move was popular back in the day. White is trying to go for a quick development. However, people understood recently that Black is totally fine, but we need to be precise. }
3... exd4 { We take the pawn because our next move will come with tempo. } 4.
Qxd4 Nc6
{ This is our idea, forcing White to move the queen again. By putting the knight on c6, we won't have such good control over d5 in the longer term, so that's why we need to act quickly. }
5. Qd2
{ The most natural retreat; the queen is already developed here. White's idea is to go b3, Bb2 and get a grip on the position. }
5... Nf6
{ An important move to remember, but also the most logical one.  5...g6  allows White to achieve their setup after  6.b3  . In some  lines, we need the bishop to go to b4, as you will see further on. }
6. e4
{ White takes good control over the center, but it's not so flexible because now there are no more options of g3 and Bg2. }
6... g6
{ The bishop will be good on the long diagonal.  6...a5  is still possible but not so effective, as the white pawn is not  on b3. }
7. b3
{ White switches to the fianchetto plan, considering that we have the pawn on g6 and ...a5-a4 is not so effective anymore. }
7... Bg7 8. Bb2 O-O
{ We brought the king to safety and are ready to create threats on the next moves. }
9. Bd3 { White is defending the e4-pawn and is finishing development. } 9... a6
{ Maybe surprising at first, but we want to play ...b5 before White finishes development. }
10. Nge2
{ The knight is better here than on f3, where it would have been exposed to ...Bg4. }
10... Ne5
{ We're taking advantage that White didn't play Nf3, and we're preparing ...b5. }
11. O-O { Finally White completed development, but we're ready to strike. }
11... b5 { This is what we have prepared with the last moves. } 12. cxb5
{ If White doesn't take, they will be left with a weak pawn on c4. } 12... Nxd3
{ Other moves are possible as well, but it makes sense to trade the bishop. }
13. Qxd3 axb5 14. Nxb5
{ White takes the pawn. If not, we could have defended it with ...c6. } 14...
Bb7
{ This is a clever move, attacking the e4-pawn. Black has a great position.   15.Nbc3?  doesn't defend it because of  15...Nxe4  and the b2-bishop is hanging.   And after  15.f3?  , there is  15...Ba6!  , when the pin proves decisive; e.g.  16.Rfc1  Qd7  17.a4  c6  wins the knight, as White doesn't have the saving  move Qf3 anymore. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) English Rat Defense 1.d4 d6 2.c4 e5"]
[Black "English Rat Defense 1.d4 d6 2.c4 e5 3.Nc3 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. c4
{ White's idea is to play Nc3 and e4, and delay the development of the knight to f3. We are already happy to see this because it allows us to play ...e5. }
2... e5
{ Of course, we go for this. The whole point of ...d6 is to go ...e5 whenever possible and control the center. }
3. Nc3
{ This move was popular back in the day. White is trying to go for a quick development. However, people understood recently that Black is totally fine, but we need to be precise. }
3... exd4 { We take the pawn because our next move will come with tempo. } 4.
Qxd4 Nc6
{ This is our idea, forcing White to move the queen again. By putting the knight on c6, we won't have such good control over d5 in the longer term, so that's why we need to act quickly. }
5. Qd2
{ The most natural retreat; the queen is already developed here. White's idea is to go b3, Bb2 and get a grip on the position. }
5... Nf6
{ An important move to remember, but also the most logical one.  5...g6  allows White to achieve their setup after  6.b3  . In some  lines, we need the bishop to go to b4, as you will see further on. }
6. b3
{ The main line by far. White wants to develop the bishop on b2 quickly and defends the c4-pawn in advance to be ready for ...Be6. }
6... a5
{ We need to create immediate problems for White without allowing a grip after Bb2. We're already threatening ...a4. }
7. e4 { White is trying to stop ...d5 once and for all. } 7... a4
{ We continue with our idea. } 8. Rb1 { What else, ...axb3 was a threat. } 8...
axb3 { It's good to open the a-file since we control it. } 9. axb3 d5
{ And yet this is possible, although d5 is the best-protected square! According to our database, this is a novelty; Black usually went for  9...g6  and ...Bg7. Due to White's lack of development and awkward piece placement, ...d5 is good. }
10. exd5
{ This is the best. White wants to play Bd3 and Nge2 to finish development.   Of course,  10.Nxd5  doesn't work because of  10...Nxd5  .   The other possible capture is  10.cxd5  , but after  10...Bb4!  @@StartBracket@@we're counting on this pin@@EndBracket@@  11.Bd3  Nd4  ,  Black has many threats and a strong initiative; ...Qe7 and ...O-O could be our next ideas. }
10... Qe7+
{ This is an important check to disrupt White's normal development. Basically, after exd5, our idea is to play ...Nb4 and ...Bf5. }
11. Be2
{ A very natural reply. White wants to continue with Nf3 and O-O.  11.Nge2  is quite bad because after  11...Nb4  , ...Bf5 is coming and Black is winning. }
11... Ne4
{ This is the most precise, exploiting White's undefended rook on b1.   11...Nb4  is not so effective because White goes  12.Nf3  Bf5  and here the exchange sacrifice is strong:  13.O-O  Bxb1  14.Nxb1  . Black is lagging in development because of the misplaced  queen on e7. }
12. Nxe4 Qxe4 13. Qe3 { The only move not to lose material. } 13... Bf5
{ The most ambitious move − we're fighting for an advantage with this. However,  13...Bb4+  is also good. }
14. Qxe4+ { Forced. } 14... Bxe4 15. dxc6 { Again, the only move. } 15... Bxb1
{ It looks to take some material, but somehow  15...b6  also works due to multiple threats  like ...Bxb1, ...Bxg2 or ...Ra1. }
16. cxb7 { This pawn is becoming dangerous. } 16... Rd8
{ The last important move to remember; otherwise, Black faces a difficult task. The idea is to have ...Bb4+ without allowing Bd2. If White spends a tempo to parry this with  17.Bd2  , we go  17...Be4  18.Bf3  f5  followed by ...Rb8 and the b7-pawn falls. }
