{ This is our idea, forcing White to move the queen again. By putting the knight on c6, we won't have such good control over d5 in the longer term, so that's why we need to act quickly. }
5. Qd2
{ The most natural retreat; the queen is already developed here. White's idea is to go b3, Bb2 and get a grip on the position. }
5... Nf6
{ An important move to remember, but also the most logical one.  5...g6  allows White to achieve their setup after  6.b3  . In some  lines, we need the bishop to go to b4, as you will see further on. }
6. b3
{ The main line by far. White wants to develop the bishop on b2 quickly and defends the c4-pawn in advance to be ready for ...Be6. }
6... a5
{ We need to create immediate problems for White without allowing a grip after Bb2. We're already threatening ...a4. }
7. Bb2
{ White holds on to their idea − e4 and Rd1 would be the next useful moves. }
7... a4
{ Continuing our idea and setting a trap because the pawn cannot really be taken. }
8. Rd1
{ White reinforces the center and makes room for the bishop to a1 in case of ...a3. }
8... axb3
{ It makes sense to open up the a-file since we have full control of it. There could be ideas of ...Nd7-c5 in the future and the b3-pawn will be weak. }
9. axb3 g6 { The bishop is best placed on the long diagonal. } 10. g3
{ It makes sense to go for a double fianchetto setup. However, some other moves are possible, like  10.Nf3  or  10.e3  , but it doesn't change the character of the position. }
10... Bg7 11. Bg2 O-O
{ Finally, we completed our development, and we can start considering ideas like ...Nd7-c5, targeting b3. }
12. Nf3 Nd7 { ...Nc5 is a real threat. } 13. Qc2
{ This is a blunder because it doesn't really defend the b3-pawn. Besides, the queen will be exposed to ...Nb4 or ...Bf5. }
13... Nc5
{ White is in big trouble. A sample line is  14.O-O  Bf5  15.e4  Nxe4!  16.Nxe4  Ra2  , when we get the piece back and win a pawn. }
