{ This will often happen when you play against a lower-rated opponent that tries to trade the queens early on. It's not good for White to release the tension in the center so early. }
3... dxe5 4. Qxd8+
{ This is the idea − to trade queens and keep our king in the center. } 4...
Kxd8
{ Our king is doing just fine in the center. It is not exposed, and we'll be able to play ...c6 and ...Kc7. The endgame is immediately preferable for Black. }
5. Nf3 { The second most played move, attacking our pawn on e5. } 5... f6
{ Now the f3-knight is misplaced and we continue our plan with ...Be6, ...c6 and ...Kc7. }
6. Nc3 Be6 { Attacking the c4-pawn. } 7. e3 c6
{ We already have a great position. Our next moves are ...Nd7 and ...Kc7. We have good control over the center, and White lacks a clear plan. }
