[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) English Rat Defense 1.d4 d6 2.c4 e5"]
[Black "English Rat Defense 1.d4 d6 2.c4 e5 3.e3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. c4
{ White's idea is to play Nc3 and e4, and delay the development of the knight to f3. We are already happy to see this because it allows us to play ...e5. }
2... e5
{ Of course, we go for this. The whole point of ...d6 is to go ...e5 whenever possible and control the center. }
3. e3
{ This rare sideline makes sense, as it reinforces the d4-pawn and White is trying to seize space with Nc3, Nf3, Be2 and so on. White is trying to keep the pawn structure flexible. }
3... f5
{ We seize space on the kingside, and we will try to develop with ...Nf6, ...Be7, ...O-O, and ...Qe8-h5. }
4. Nc3 Nf6
{ The knight belongs here. We're not concerned about  5.dxe5  , as the ending is completely fine for us, and we can  go ...c6, ...Kc7, and so on. }
5. Nf3
{ A very natural development move, already attacking e5. The downside is that it allows ...e4 with tempo. }
5... e4 { This is good, as it comes with tempo. } 6. Ng5
{ White is trying to be more active with this knight jump, trying to provoke us to play ...h6 and ...g5.   6.Nd2  transposes to the 3.Nf3 move order. }
6... Be7
{ Just continuing development. We should not fall for  6...h6  7.Nh3  g5  , which is very tempting because after  8.Ng1  , White is ready to  play h4 and exploit our weakened kingside. }
7. f3
{ White should challenge our pawn center as soon as possible. If White doesn't go for this, in the long term, we'll manage to keep our center intact after ...c6 and ...d5.   7.Nh3  c6  just transposes. }
7... O-O
{ We're sacrificing a pawn in order to get a better development and later exploit the f-file. }
8. Be2 { White is a bit more cautious and wants to castle first. } 8... c6
{ Of course with the idea ...d5. It's not so good to take on f3 because it gives White a slightly better position with good piece play. }
9. fxe4 { If not, we go ...d5 and consolidate the center. } 9... h6
{ An important intermediate move, dislodging the knight, and like this, we're saving the e4-pawn. }
10. Nh3 Nxe4
{ It's important to take like this in order to open the f-file in case of a knight trade. Our ideas could be ...Nxc3 to destroy White's structure or ...Bh4+ g3 ...Bg5 to weaken White's kingside. }
