{ The main move, immediately putting pressure on e5. This is more likely what stronger players will do. }
3... e4
{ We accept the challenge and chase away the knight; it would have been too passive to defend the e5-pawn. }
4. Nfd2 { A more passive approach, but the knight is not exposed here. } 4...
f5 { We seize space and protect e4, intending ...Nf6. } 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. e3
{ White is preparing f3 already. } 6... c5
{ After this move, the knight on d2 remains passive, and we're fighting for control of the center.  6...Be7  is also fine, but it allows  7.f3  . }
7. Nb3
{ White wants to take on d4 with the knight. However, the knight is passive on b3 and is not fighting for the e4-square anymore. }
7... g6
{ We intend to put the bishop on g7, although ...b6 is needed first to protect c5. }
8. Be2 b6 { Securing c5. We're ready to play ...Bg7. } 9. f3
{ White has to challenge the center, or they will get suffocated. } 9... Bg7
10. O-O Bb7
{ The point of this is to take back on e4 with a piece. d5 to shut off the bishop is again strategically very bad for White. Of course, Black has a very comfortable position because we have more space. }
