[White "13) English Rat Defense 1.d4 d6 2.c4 e5"]
[Black "English Rat Defense 1.d4 d6 2.c4 e5 3.Nf3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. c4
{ White's idea is to play Nc3 and e4, and delay the development of the knight to f3. We are already happy to see this because it allows us to play ...e5. }
2... e5
{ Of course, we go for this. The whole point of ...d6 is to go ...e5 whenever possible and control the center. }
3. Nf3
{ The main move, immediately putting pressure on e5. This is more likely what stronger players will do. }
3... e4
{ We accept the challenge and chase away the knight; it would have been too passive to defend the e5-pawn. }
4. Ng1
{ White loses two tempi but forces us to play ...e4. The plan is to go Bf4 and only then e3 in order to get a favorable French structure. }
4... c6 { We want to go ...d5 to reinforce the e4-pawn. } 5. Nc3
{ White attacks the e4-pawn. } 5... d5
{ We follow our idea, also opening up the dark-squared bishop. } 6. Bf4
{ This is White's point. After  5.e3  Nf6  ,  we get into the French Defense  (Advance Variation)  , where we have the white pieces. }
6... dxc4
{ This is a novelty. We immediately change the pawn structure, so as not to allow White a comfortable setup. }
7. Nxe4 { White takes the pawn back. } 7... Bb4+ { Developing with tempo. } 8.
Nc3
{ After  8.Bd2  , we go  8...Qxd4  9.Bxb4  Qxe4  and we're a pawn up, although there is compensation for it. }
8... Nf6
{ We have a comfortable position. Our pieces are active and the c4-pawn is not in danger − we can support it with ...b5. It's not easy for White to play e3 because of ...Nd5 and there is no Bd2 anymore. }
