5. h4
{ A useful move, trying to get some space and fix the kingside. It also stops ...h6 and ...g5. }
5... h6
{ Here, we can go after the h4-pawn.  6...c6  is also a good alternative. } 6.
Nh3 Qxh4
{ There is no turning back. We've got an important pawn, but White will have compensation because of piece activity, and also, White is a few tempi up. }
7. e3
{ A useful move anyway. White prevents  7...Nf6?  because of  8.Be2!   If  7.Nc3  , we can go  7...Qh5  and the queen is heading to f7 anyway. }
7... Qe7
{ The queen was rather exposed on h4, and now it's heading to f7. We're also ready to play ...Nf6. }
8. Nf4 { White brings the knight into play. } 8... Qf7
{ The queen reached its ideal square. We parried Ng6, and we want to go ...Nf6 next. }
9. Be2 { With the obvious threat of Bh5. } 9... Nf6
{ A developing move, preventing Bh5. So far, the threats have been parried, but White keeps compensation because of active pieces and development. However, in the long term, the extra pawn should count. }
