{ The best move, threatening h4. If  8.f3  , we go  8...d5  followed by ...Nf6 with a space advantage. }
8... Bg7
{ Actually, Black has to be quite accurate here not to fall into a bad position. We want to avoid the structures after h4 and ...g4. Although the position looks blocked at first, White has a free hand to play on the queenside and in the center. }
9. h4 Na6
{ This is the good square for the knight, leaving our c8-bishop open. } 10. Nh3
{ White puts more pressure on the g5-pawn, trying to provoke ...g4 and getting a favorable structure.   If  10.hxg5  hxg5  11.Rxh8  Bxh8  12.Nh3  , there is  12...Bf6  and  the g5-pawn is well defended. }
10... Qb6
{ We search for counterplay, attacking d4 and keeping an eye on the b2-pawn.  10...Bf6  is also interesting. }
11. e3 { White protects d4 but shuts out their bishop. } 11... Qd8
{ The queen did its job and returns to a better square to protect g5. We want to follow up with ...Nf6.   12.Qh5+  doesn't lead anywhere, as we have  12...Ke7  , obviously. :@@EndBracket@@ We like Black's position.   It is also possible to go  11...Nf6  if you are concerned about the check  on h5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) English Rat Defense 1.d4 d6 2.c4 e5"]
[Black "English Rat Defense 1.d4 d6 2.c4 e5 3.Nf3 #14"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second-most played move in practice. It's considered more solid than  1.e4  , when White usually aims for a long-term small edge from the opening. }
1... d6
{ Our usual reply, preparing ...e5 and waiting for White to show their plans. }
2. c4
{ White's idea is to play Nc3 and e4, and delay the development of the knight to f3. We are already happy to see this because it allows us to play ...e5. }
2... e5
{ Of course, we go for this. The whole point of ...d6 is to go ...e5 whenever possible and control the center. }
3. Nf3
{ The main move, immediately putting pressure on e5. This is more likely what stronger players will do. }
3... e4
{ We accept the challenge and chase away the knight; it would have been too passive to defend the e5-pawn. }
4. Ng5
{ The most played continuation, trying to keep the knight active. However, it has its drawbacks, as we'll be able to gain some tempi with ...Be7 or ...h6, attacking the knight. }
4... f5
{ We support the e4-pawn.  4...Nf6  is not so good because White can attack  the e4-pawn with  5.Nc3  Qe7  6.Qc2  . }
5. Nc3
{ White plays a normal developing move. Here, the knight controls good squares in the center. }
5... c6
{ This is a flexible move; we keep the c3-knight in check. In the future, we can even play ...d5. }
6. Nh3
{ White is rerouting the knight to f4 and is also trying to play Bg5 in some lines. }
6... Nf6
{ Continuing our development and preparing ...d5 later on.  6...Be7  is also possible, with the idea to  avoid Bg5. However, we are not impressed with White's plan of Bg5. }
7. Bg5
{ White first develops the bishop and then plays e3, followed by Nf4. Sooner or later White will have to trade the bishop for the knight on f6. }
7... Be7 { A useful move, we're getting rid of the pin. } 8. Nf4
{ The knight gets into play, stopping us from playing ...h6.   Sometimes White goes for  8.f3  , but it's not such a good idea. Our plan stays the same. We can play  8...O-O  followed by ...Na6-c7. }
8... O-O
{ The idea is to go for ...Na6-c7, but it's also possible to play  8...Na6  immediately. }
9. e3 { Simply connecting the pieces. } 9... Na6
{ Our important idea is to get rid of the f4-knight, which is White's strongest piece. We don't really want to play ...h6 to force the trade on f6 because we weaken the g6-square. We'd rather wait for White to take on f6. }
10. Be2 { White finishes development, and their next ideas can be O-O or h4. }
10... Nc7 { The knight is on its way to e6. } 11. O-O Ne6
{ After the knight trade, we have quite a comfortable position. We can follow up with ...d5, and we have more space. }
*

