1. c4
{ The English Opening. This move fights for the center, and also allows White more flexible setups. }
1... d6 { We're not impressed. We go  1...d6  against everything. } 2. e4
{ White is seizing more space in the center and tries to avoid the lines after  2.d4  e5  .  White can prepare d4 in better conditions, or just play d3. }
2... e5
{ We get a foothold in the center, and our idea is to continue with ...f5, ...Nf6. }
3. Nc3 { White continues to develop normally. } 3... f5
{ Challenging White's center. This is good because we break the symmetry and get some counterplay.  3...c5  is also possible but too drawish for our taste. }
4. d3
{ The most played move in this position. White opens up the dark-squared bishop and wants to take on e4 with the pawn. }
4... Nf6 { The knight belongs here. } 5. g3
{ Going for the fianchetto. Other moves like  5.Nf3  or  5.Nge2  are also possible but less ambitious. Our plan would remain the same. }
5... Be7
{ Now that White cannot go d4 in one move, the setup with ...Be7, ...O-O and ...c6 is very good. }
6. Bg2 O-O 7. Nge2 { The logical developing move. } 7... c6
{ We restrict the g2-bishop and control the important d5-square. } 8. O-O Qe8
{ The queen is heading towards h5. We have many useful moves like ...Kh8, ...a5, ...Na6. White has a normal setup but lacks a clear plan. Black is totally fine. }
