1. c4
{ The English Opening. This move fights for the center, and also allows White more flexible setups. }
1... d6 { We're not impressed. We go  1...d6  against everything. } 2. e4
{ White is seizing more space in the center and tries to avoid the lines after  2.d4  e5  .  White can prepare d4 in better conditions, or just play d3. }
2... e5
{ We get a foothold in the center, and our idea is to continue with ...f5, ...Nf6. }
3. Nc3 { White continues to develop normally. } 3... f5
{ Challenging White's center. This is good because we break the symmetry and get some counterplay.  3...c5  is also possible but too drawish for our taste. }
4. g3
{ The white bishop will be strong on the long diagonal. It's logical to play d3, but here White wants to keep options to push d4 in one move. }
4... Nf6 { It's time to develop the knights. } 5. Bg2 Nc6
{ Taking control of the d4-square for now. In this move order, it's also possible to play  5...fxe4  , but  5...Be7  should be avoided, as it allows  6.exf5  Bxf5  7.Bxb7  . }
6. Nge2
{ White wants to go d4 in one move. If  6.d3  , then we can also fianchetto the bishop with  6...g6  7.Nge2  Bg7  8.O-O  O-O  , when we get a normal position of the Reversed Closed Sicilian, which is playable for both sides. }
6... fxe4
{ We go for this because White skipped d3. We don't want to play  6...g6  because of  7.d4  . }
7. Nxe4 Be7
{ Just normal development, planning to recapture with the bishop on f6. We want to follow up with ...Bf5 and ...O-O. }
8. d4 { The ambitious break in the center, trying to go d5. } 8... Bf5
{ Developing with tempo is always good. White has to make a choice of what to do with the knight. If White takes on f6, our bishop becomes more active, or if White retreats to c3, we follow up with ...O-O, ...Qd7, and so on. }
