1. c4
{ The English Opening. This move fights for the center, and also allows White more flexible setups. }
1... d6 { We're not impressed. We go  1...d6  against everything. } 2. Nc3
{ A flexible move. White keeps the option to play g3 followed by Bg2 or push the pawns in the center.  2.g3  or  2.Nf3  would surely transpose to the lines in the course after  2...e5  . }
2... e5
{ The main point of 1...d6. We gain a foothold in the center and want to follow up with ...f5. }
3. g3
{ The typical English setup. White develops the bishop on g2 to put pressure on our position. }
3... f5 { Whenever possible, we get this setup. } 4. d4
{ White can go for this, as after ...f5, it doesn't make sense to take on d4 anymore. }
4... Be7
{ Normal development. In case of dxe5 followed by a queen trade, we are ready to take back with the bishop. }
5. Nf3 { White is provoking ...e4, hoping to take advantage of the f4-square. }
5... e4
{ We have to go for this, as it comes with tempo.  5...Nc6  is not so good in view of  6.d5  . }
6. Nh4
{ This was popular recently among strong GMs. The idea is to reroute the knight to g2-f4.   6.Ng1  is also possible, however, we play the same plan  with ...Nf6, ...c6, ...O-O, ... Na6-c7. It could lead to similar positions to  6.Nh4  . }
6... c6
{ This is part of our plan and it's useful to include it. White gets an initiative if we take on h4:  6...Bxh4?!  7.gxh4  Qxh4  8.Rg1  . }
7. Ng2 { White wants to play h4 first and then Nf4. } 7... Nf6
{ Normal development.  6...Na6  is the same because White can play  7.h4  , and then we have to go  7...Nf6  anyway. }
8. Bg5 { It's logical to first activate the bishop and then go e3. } 8... O-O
{ The positions are similar to the lines in the first chapter. We want to play ...Na6-c7. }
9. e3 { White opens up the light-squared bishop. } 9... Na6
{ The knight is heading to c7. } 10. Nf4 Nc7
{ Our plan is to go ...Ne6 or ...Ng4 to trade some pieces and then play for more space. Black went on to win a good game in 0-1 Matamoros Franco-Brkic, Baku 2023. }
