[Black "English Opening 1.c4 d6 2.Nc3 e5 3.g3 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ The English Opening. This move fights for the center, and also allows White more flexible setups. }
1... d6 { We're not impressed. We go  1...d6  against everything. } 2. Nc3
{ A flexible move. White keeps the option to play g3 followed by Bg2 or push the pawns in the center.  2.g3  or  2.Nf3  would surely transpose to the lines in the course after  2...e5  . }
2... e5
{ The main point of 1...d6. We gain a foothold in the center and want to follow up with ...f5. }
3. g3
{ The typical English setup. White develops the bishop on g2 to put pressure on our position. }
3... f5 { Whenever possible, we get this setup. } 4. Bg2
{ White continues with the typical English setup. There are many transpositions in this chapter, as White has different ways to reach the desired setups. If  4.Nf3  , we can go  4...Be7  . }
4... Be7
{ Our plan is to go ...Nf6, ...O-O, ...Qe8, ...c6, and so on.  4...Nf6  is the most played move and leads to the same thing. }
5. d4
{ This can be reached also via another move order: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp3pp/3p4/4pp2/2P5/2N3P1/PP1PPP1P/R1BQKBNR w KQkq f6 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d4  Be7  5.Bg2  . }
5... Nf6 { Our plan remains the same. } 6. Nf3
{ Forcing us to make a decision about the e5-pawn. } 6... e4
{ We go for this whenever it is with tempo. There was no good way to defend e5. }
7. Ng5 c6
{ A typical move. We want to have ...d5 at the right moment to support the center, and also, there is ...Na6-c7. }
8. d5 { White stops us from playing ...d5 by playing d5 themselves. } 8... h6
{ We want to play ...Nbd7-e5 without allowing Ne6. The trick with  8...Nxd5  is possible but leads to a slightly passive position after  9.Ngxe4  Nb6  10.Nd2  . }
9. Nh3 { What else?  9.Ne6  loses a pawn after  9...Bxe6  10.dxe6  Qc8  . }
9... Nbd7 { The knight is heading to e5. } 10. O-O Ne5
{ The knight looks great here, attacking c4. } 11. b3
{ Not so much to fianchetto the bishop, but to defend c4. } 11... h5
{ Considering we haven't castled yet, White cannot stop us from going ...h4. The position remains very dynamic. However, we like Black's chances as White lacks a clear plan. If you forget about this idea and go  11...O-O  , that's also totally fine. }
