1. b3 d6 { We intend to play ...e5 and shut off the bishop. } 2. Bb2
{ If White continues  2.d4  , we play  2...e5  . } 2... e5 3. d4
{ A very rare sideline. White tries to open up the bishop immediately but, in return, gives us a tempo with ...Nc6. }
3... exd4 { It's good to open up the center; ...Nc6 will be next. } 4. Qxd4
{ Taking like this keeps more options open. } 4... Nc6
{ We develop with tempo. } 5. Qe3+
{ An interesting check, hoping for ...Qe7 to play a slightly better endgame. However, the queen is misplaced because White cannot go e3 anymore. }
5... Be6 { We parry the check and develop a piece. } 6. Nh3
{ The only reasonable continuation, trying to go Nf4. } 6... d5
{ Immediately trying to exploit White's awkward development. } 7. Nf4 d4
{ Black already takes over the initiative, attacking the queen and shutting off the bishop.   8.Nxe6  loses to  8...dxe3  , and if White moves the queen,  we can continue with ...Nf6, and we have a huge development lead and good control over the center. }
