{ White continues their plan, hoping for  6...d4  , when after  7.Nb5  ,  the d4-pawn could become a target. }
6... Nf6 { Not falling for the trap and defending the pawn. } 7. O-O-O
{ Renewing the threat. } 7... Be6
{ Again, defending the pawn and developing a piece. } 8. e4
{ The most critical continuation. White opens up the center while still having a lead in development. }
8... Nxe4 { The most forcing continuation, getting rid of the knights. } 9.
Nxe4 dxe4 10. Qe3
{ Other queen moves don't make much of a difference because we can play ...Bd6 anyway. This is what White was counting on in order to get the pawn back and also try to take advantage of our king in the center. }
10... Bd6
{ A good developing move, and counting on a small trap: if  11.Bxg7?  , there is  11...Ba3+!  and Black wins. }
11. Qxe4 { White takes the pawn back. } 11... Qg5+
{ Now we take advantage of our development by means of this move. } 12. Kb1
O-O-O
{ This was our idea. The king is safe on c8 and the rook suddenly becomes active on d8. We already prefer Black. }
13. Nf3 { White develops with tempo. } 13... Qa5
{ One of the several good retreats for the queen. We want the queen close to the white king in order to create some threats, like ...Nb4 or ...Bf5. }
