1. b3 d6 { We intend to play ...e5 and shut off the bishop. } 2. Bb2
{ If White continues  2.d4  , we play  2...e5  . } 2... e5 3. e3
{ This is White's most flexible move, leaving their options with the central pawns open. }
3... Nf6
{ A normal developing move. It's important to remember not to go for the usual  3...f5  because of  4.d4!  and if  4...e4  , then  5.d5! }
4. Nf3
{ This move looks normal, but White doesn't really want to play d4 because of ...e4 and ...d5, transposing into a favorable French structure. However, White can start with c4 first. }
4... g6
{ We intend to fianchetto to counter White's bishop on b2 when the position opens up. }
5. d4 { White breaks the center open. } 5... e4
{ This is usually a good reply to d4 when the knight is attacked. We also gain some space. }
6. Nfd2 d5
{ Building up a strong center and making the d2-knight a bad piece. Our plan now switches − we want ...Bd6, ...c6, and so on.   An immediate  6...Bg7  followed by ...O-O and ...Re8 is also possible. Afterwards, the idea is to undermine the white center with ...c5. }
7. c4 { A typical French structure move to challenge the center. } 7... c6
{ We consolidate our center, and we want to recapture with the pawn on d5. We have a good version of the French Defense. Our next moves could be ...Bd6, ...Bf5 or ...h5. An interesting idea is also to play ... a6 and ...b5. }
