{ White is getting ready for an attack. It's not good for White to hurry up with  8.f5  because of  8...gxf5  9.Qh4  d5!  with an extra pawn for Black. Following  10.Bh6  dxe4  11.dxe4  fxe4  12.Ng5  , White  does threaten Bxg7 followed by Rxf6, which seems scary indeed, but we have a strong antidote:  12...Nd4!  13.Bxg7  Nxe2+   13...Kxg7  is less precise, as after  14.Rxf6  Nxe2+  15.Kf2  Kxf6  16.Kxe2  , Black is not out of the woods yet.  14.Kh1  Kxg7  15.Nc3  Nxc3  16.Rxf6  Kxf6  17.Rf1+  Ke5  18.Qf4+  Kd5  19.bxc3  Kc6  , finally reaching safety with an extra rook. If this variation feels too spine-chilling, there is also @@StartFEN@@r1bq1r2/pp2ppkp/5n2/2p3N1/4p2Q/2N5/PPP1n1PP/R4R1K b - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...h6  16.Nxe2  Qd5  17.Nh3  Qh5  18.Qg3+  Kh7  19.Nef4  Qg4  , which also stabilizes the position and secures Black a significant edge. }
8... e6
{ We're stopping f5 for now, and we have the idea to play ...Nd7 to trade the queens. Also, the ...b5 idea is still there.   A possible line goes  9.a4  Rb8  10.c3  a6  with the  idea ...b5, and if White stops us:  11.a5  , then we get  11...c4  . }
