{ White is fighting for the center immediately.  6.c4  transposes to  the 1.c4 chapter. }
6... O-O
{ Just continuing development. The pawn cannot be taken, as  6...fxe4  7.dxe4  Nxe4  fails to  8.Nxe5! }
7. exf5 { This only helps Black, as it develops our bishop. } 7... Bxf5
{ Now the idea is to play ...Nc6 and ...Qd7. Black is already preferable.  8.Nh4  is met with  8...Bg4  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) 1.Nf3 and Rare Moves"]
[Black "1.Nf3 d6 2.g3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 { A flexible move, allowing transpositions to different openings. } 1...
d6 { We go for this against everything. Here we're preparing ...e5. } 2. g3
{ White players very often go for the Réti setup with Nf3-g3, no matter what Black does. However, against 1...d6, this is not so effective because we have  2...e5  and get a hold of the center. }
2... e5
{ Of course, we take control of the center. After this move, White has some things to consider. For example, if White plays d4 to challenge the center, we will always play...e4, seizing more space and dislodging the knight with an advantage. Otherwise, we will play ...f5 and continue development. }
3. Bg2 { White goes on with their plan as well. } 3... f5
{ The plan is to go ...Nf6, ...Be7, ...O-O, ...Qe8, and so on, and maybe an attack on the kingside in the long run. }
4. d3
{ White gets a King's Indian setup.  4.O-O  leads to the same thing. And if White plays with  4.c4  instead of  4.d3  , it will transpose  to the 1.c4 chapter. }
4... Nf6 { A normal developing move, continuing with our plan. } 5. O-O Be7
{ We're going for a quick kingside development with ...Be7 and ...O-O. This is slightly preferable to ...g6 and ...Bg7, which would prevent our attacking ideas of ...Qe8-h5. }
6. e4
{ White is fighting for the center immediately.  6.c4  transposes to  the 1.c4 chapter. }
6... O-O
{ Just continuing development. The pawn cannot be taken, as  6...fxe4  7.dxe4  Nxe4  fails to  8.Nxe5! }
7. Nh4
{ With this move, White is forcing our hand. However, putting the knight on the edge of the board has its drawbacks. }
7... f4 { We go forward! } 8. gxf4
{ White grabs the pawn; otherwise, we would defend it with ...g5. } 8... exf4
{ No sacrifices, although  8...Nc6  is possible here. } 9. Nf5
{ The knight was hanging on h4. White cannot take the pawn with  9.Bxf4  because of  9...Nxe4! }
9... g5
{ It's important to defend the f4-pawn in order to restrict the c1-bishop. Our plan is to develop with ...Nc6. The position is unclear, but Black's king looks safer.   We can meet  10.h4  with  10...Ne8  ,  trying to go ...Ng7 and destroying White's only active piece. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Ante Brkic − Leon Livaic, Kaštel Novi 2024"]
[Result "*"]

{ Comments by GM Leon Livaic. } 1. e4
{ The game was played in the Croatian League 2024. GM Brkic is playing exclusively  1.e4  − a great chance to practice the Philidor! }
1... d6 { Versus everything! } 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. a4
O-O 7. O-O
{ My opponent repeats the main line, which he already played in the Croatian Cup earlier this year − in that game, I played  7...c6  . }
7... exd4 { One of the two options we recommend against White's setup. } 8.
Nxd4
{ I was expecting  8.Qxd4  more, but this is no surprise. Still following the course. }
8... Ne5 9. Ba2
{ Here, my opponent spent quite some time, so he was probably out of book. }
9... Nc6 { As we said, our idea is to play ...Nb4 followed by c5. } 10. Nxc6
{ This move was new to me at the time. At first, it felt illogical, as bringing the black pawn to c6 would restrict the c3-knight, and additionally, the b-file would be opened for my rook. My opponent said after the game that his logic was to try to develop as quickly as possible, as I spent 3 moves on ...Nbd7, ...Ne5, and ...Nc6. }
10... bxc6 11. Re1
{ The rook is useful here, and it will support the e5 break in the future. }
11... Rb8
{ I spent some minutes here calculating  12.e5  , which would spoil my pawn structure, but I concluded that after  12...dxe5  13.Qxd8  Rxd8  14.Rxe5  Bd6  15.Re1  Bf5!  I was pretty sure I had at least sufficient counterplay. Also, even @@StartFEN@@1rbq1rk1/p1p1bppp/2pp1n2/4P3/P7/2N5/BPP2PPP/R1BQR1K1 b - - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Nd7  is interesting. }
12. Bc4
{ Ante decides to play it slowly, trying to play b3 and Bb2, nullifying the rook on b8, but before that, he needs to put the bishop on c4 so it doesn't stay behind the pawn chain. }
12... Nd7
{ We have seen this plan several times in the course, rerouting the knight to c5 and freeing the f6-square for the bishop. }
13. b3 { Continuing with the plan. } 13... Bf6 { Attacking the knight. } 14.
Bb2 Nc5
{ The decision here wasn't easy for me, as  14...Be5  makes really a lot of sense,  immediately trying to put more pressure with ...Qf6. I was concerned about  15.Qd2  Qf6  16.g3  ,  where he is trying to play f4. I saw that I can play  16...g5  , but I thought it could become a weakness in the long run.  Still, that was probably the best option to complicate the game and play for a win.  The game move is preparing ...Be6; Black is fine, but the position becomes very dry. }
15. Qf3 { White develops the queen and prepares Nd1 to get rid of the pin. }
15... Be6 { Black is fully developed now. } 16. Bf1
{ 16.Bxe6  fxe6  would open the f-file, so the text move is probably better. }
16... Be5 { Preparing ...Qf6 or ...Qg5, developing the queen. } 17. Nd1
{ Finally, there is no more pin. } 17... Qg5
{ Threatening ...Bg4 and rerouting the queen to e5 after the exchange. } 18.
Bxe5 Qxe5 19. Qc3 { White goes for the endgame, but there is no advantage. }
19... Qxc3
{ I briefly considered keeping the queens on the board, but allowing Qa5 seems way too risky. }
20. Nxc3 a5
{ Fixing the white pawns on the light squares. Who knows, maybe some day they will become targets for my bishop in the endgame. }
21. f3 { White will improve his king and he is also reinforcing the e4-pawn. }
21... Rfe8 { If ...f5 happens, I will need the rook on the open file. } 22. Ne2
{ A very good move, preparing Nd4. The c3-knight was White's worst piece for a while now. Ever since White took on c6. }
22... Bd7 { A prophylactic move, I want c6 defended. } 23. Rad1
{ White brings the other rook into play. } 23... g6
{ I want to answer  24.Nd4  with  24...Ne6  without him having Nf5, although even that would be fine. }
24. Nd4 Ne6 25. Kf2 { The king is an important piece in the endgame. } 25...
Re7
{ The rook on b8 isn't useful anymore so I want to bring it to e8 and double. }
26. Nxe6 Bxe6 { After this trade, the position is even more dry. } 27. e5
{ White is hoping for either  27...d5  , when he would have a pawn majority on the kingside, or for  27...dxe5  , after which I would be left with a horrible pawn structure. But... }
27... Rd7 { After this simple move, I just want to double on the d-file. } 28.
exd6 cxd6
{ Here we agreed to a draw. I actually prefer Black a bit simply because the white pawns are on the light squares, but of course, it's completely equal. 1...d6 vs. everything holds even when White is a top 100 player! }
