[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Adam Kozak − Leon Livaic, Budapest 2024"]
[Result "*"]

{ Comments by GM Leon Livaic.  The game was played in mid-2024 in the Hungarian League. My GM opponent is playing everything as White, so it's good that I can play 1...d6 against everything. }
1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. g3
{ The first small surprise. The line is of course playable, but the bishop on g2 is usually not too active. }
5... c6
{ In the course, we suggested  5...g6  to transpose to the King's Indian fianchetto systems, but there is nothing wrong with this line either. }
6. Bg2
{ The real surprise. I was sure that my opponent would stop me from playing  6...b5  . }
6... b5
{ Usually, Black is very happy if this happens in the Philidor, seizing space on the queenside. You should, in general, do it whenever White doesn't have a clear refutation of it in the sense of d5 or a4 in view of ...b4. }
7. O-O { Opting for a quick development. } 7... Be7
{ I also need to finish development.  7...b4  8.Na4  Nxe4  would win a pawn, but it would open up the e-file and  the g2-bishop so it's way too risky. }
8. Re1 { Defending e4. } 8... O-O
{ The kingside is developed; now I want to go ...Bb7 and finish development. }
9. a4
{ Trying to disrupt Black's development, but it has its drawbacks, as White will have to 'undevelop' his knight too. }
9... b4 { Obviously. } 10. Nb1
{ White is claiming that he will be in time to go Nd2-c4 where it will be active. }
10... a5
{ Now the bishop will be better placed on a6 than on b7, but it's good to secure the b4-pawn first. }
11. c3
{ With this move, he wants to get rid of the b4-pawn and bring the knight back to c3. Not at all what I expected, but Black is fine after  11.Nbd2  Ba6  12.b3  Qc7  . }
11... Ba6 { Finishing development. } 12. b3
{ White wants to play c4 and just play for the space advantage.  12.cxb4  axb4  would weaken the center control, so I was not afraid of it. }
12... bxc3
{ I spent some good 20-30 minutes deciding whether to take or to play the position after  12...c5  13.dxe5  dxe5  14.c4  . Both choices are quite good, but this one looked attractive  as the b3-pawn might be a target. }
13. Nxc3 Rb8 { The point. } 14. Ba3
{ White finished development too, targeting d6. } 14... Re8
{ I want to develop with ...Qc7, but there was dxe5 preventing that. I need the e7-bishop defended. }
15. Rb1 { Prophylaxis, defending b3. } 15... Qc7 { Continuing the plan. } 16.
Qc2 { White wants to bring his other rook into the game. } 16... Qa7
{ Targeting d4 and removing my queen from the c-file − there were Nb5 or Nd5 moves looming. }
17. Red1 { Defending d4. } 17... Bf8 { Now I can move the rook from e8. } 18.
h3 { Creating luft for the king. } 18... Rec8 { Protecting c6 in advance. } 19.
Bb2 { Trying to put pressure on e5 later on. } 19... Re8
{ Now protecting e5 in advance. If he repeated, I would probably agree to a draw, as the position seems equal and hard to improve for both sides. }
20. Ba1 { Playing for a win. } 20... Rbc8
{ Now b3 is too well protected so I don't really need the rook on b8 anymore. }
21. dxe5
{ A big decision, giving up the c5-square and opening the f8-bishop. However, it creates a backward isolated pawn on c6. }
21... dxe5 22. Na2
{ This is a mistake. The knight on c3 was restricted by the c6-pawn, so White wants to improve it. }
22... c5
{ Taking over the initiative. Now White can't stop ...c4, and when everything opens up, his minor pieces will be worse placed than mine. }
23. Nc3 { Trying to go to b5 now when the pawn is not on c6 anymore. } 23... c4
{ Opening up the position. } 24. bxc4 { Forced. } 24... Bxc4 25. Nd2
{ Trying to chase the bishop away. } 25... Be2
{ Before going back to a6, it felt like a good idea to force the rook to e1.  26.Rdc1  Bc5  , of course, loses. }
26. Re1 Ba6 27. Qa2 { Getting away from the pin and preparing Nb5. } 27... Bb4
{ With time trouble becoming a factor, it was hard to play perfectly.  27...Bc5  would have been stronger. }
28. Nb5 { Pretty much forced. } 28... Qc5
{ The most active square for my queen; now ...Qc2 is in the air. } 29. Bf1
{ A good move, improving the worst-placed minor piece. Maybe he can think about Bc4 in the future. }
29... Bb7 { Attacking e4. } 30. Re3
{ This move frees the d2-knight so it can go to c4 next. } 30... Qc2
{ The point, I want to bring the queen to the second rank. } 31. Rb2
{ Trying to bail out with  31.Qxc2  Rxc2  32.Nc4  was probably better, but Black keeps the edge there too. }
31... Qd1 { Now it gets very dangerous as there is ...Rc1 coming. } 32. Rxb4
{ The final mistake. There was still hope after  32.Nd6!  Bxd6  33.Rxb7  Rc2  34.Rb2  Rxb2  35.Qxb2  Qxa4  , but it's a long-suffering in a pawn-down endgame. }
32... axb4 33. Nd6
{ White will get material back, but it's not all about material... } 33... Rf8
{ Defending f7 is forced. } 34. Nxc8
{ Regaining the exchange; however, it's too little, too late. } 34... Rxc8
{ Both ...Rc2 and ...Rc1 are threats and it's not possible to survive. } 35.
Nf3 { The only try. } 35... Rc1
{ Double attack on the bishop pair.  35...Bxe4  was also winning. } 36. Re1
Qxf3 { Now the gunshot wound on the long diagonal will be fatal. } 37. Rxc1
Bxe4 38. Rc8+ { It's just one check. } 38... Nf8
{ White resigned. A very nice win in the Philidor. A fun fact was that Mircea was playing for my opponent's team and was quite surprised to see 1...d6 on the board. I'm still not sure why. :@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
