[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Max Hess − Leon Livaic, Austria 2023"]
[Result "*"]

{ Comments by GM Leon Livaic.  This game was played in the Austrian League 2023/2024. For now, it's my only classical game in this line of the King's Indian, but there will be more in the future for sure. }
1. c4 g6 2. Nc3 Bg7 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. e4 Bg4 6. Be2 Bxf3 7. Bxf3 e5 8. d5
h5 9. O-O Nbd7 10. h4 a5 11. g3 Bh6 12. Bxh6 Rxh6 13. Qd2 Rh8
{ Thus far, it was all given in the 1.d4 chapter, but at the time, I didn't know or understand that  13...Rh7  is better than  13...Rh8  . You probably won't hold that against me, considering how artificial it looks. Still, the structure remains the same, and the plans used in the game are instructive. }
14. Bg2 { White wants the bishop on h3, where it will be more active. } 14...
Kf8
{ The good old plan of ...Kf8-g7. You have seen it many times in the course. }
15. Qg5
{ This move is ambitious, activating the queen and hinting on f4 with attacking play. }
15... Kg7 { We need the king here on safety. } 16. Bh3
{ Activating the bishop. } 16... Nc5
{ Attacking e4 and activating the knight. } 17. Rae1
{ Defending e4 and activating the last piece. } 17... Re8
{ We don't need the rook on h8 anymore. This is prophylaxis against f4 ideas, in which case e4 would be under attack one more time. }
18. Re2
{ Slowly improving the position. Now, it will be easier for White to double on any file that opens. }
18... c6 { Black needs some air for his pieces, especially the queen. } 19.
dxc6
{ The alternative was to allow ...cxd5, which is strategically risky. It was probably preferable to the game move, though, as that one opens the b-file and allows ...Ne6-d4 ideas in the future. }
19... bxc6 20. Rd1 { Targeting d6 − this was White's point. } 20... Qc7 21. Qd2
{ Obviously, there will be no attack anymore so the queen isn't needed on g5. }
21... Rad8 { Defending d6. } 22. Qc2
{ Defending e4 with the queen so that he can double the rooks on the d-file. }
22... Nh7 { Trying to reroute the knight to f8-e6-d4. } 23. Red2
{ Just doubling but no threats. } 23... Nf8 { Continuing the plan. } 24. Ne2
{ A preventive move; now ...Nd4 will not be possible anymore without ...c5. }
24... Qe7 { Hinting on ...g5 ideas, but it's probably too risky to allow Bf5. }
25. Kg2 Nh7
{ Shuffling the pieces back. Maybe the ...g5 ideas will be stronger if we can recapture with the knight. }
26. Nc3 Nf8 27. Ne2 { White wants a draw. } 27... Nfe6
{ I wanted to play for a win, but in return, I have to allow this trade. } 28.
Bxe6 Nxe6 29. Qc3
{ Attacking a5 and threatening the tricky @@StartFEN@@3rr3/4qpk1/2ppn1p1/p3p2p/2P1P2P/2Q3P1/PP1RNPK1/3R4 w - - 1 230@@EndFEN@@  30.Rxd6  Rxd6  31.Qxe5+  . }
29... Nc5 { Fortunately, this move easily covers both, as e4 is hanging. } 30.
Qe3 Qc7 31. f3 { White reinforces e4 but weakens the second rank. } 31... Ne6
{ Now the plan for Black is clear: triple on the b-file and take on b2. Also, it's always possible to play ...c5 and put the knight on d4. }
32. Rd3 { White wants to triple with Qd2. } 32... Rd7 33. Qd2 Red8
{ Passively defending for now, but ...Nc5 can always be played, kicking the rook. }
34. Ra3 { Attacking a5. } 34... Rb8 { Tactically defending:  35.Rxa5  Rxb2  . }
35. Rd3 { Again, going for a repetition. } 35... Nc5
{ Again, declining.  36.Rxd6  isn't really a threat,  as b2 is hanging. } 36.
Ra3 { Trying to provoke  36...a4  to weaken that pawn. } 36... Qb6
{ Forcing the issue. } 37. Rxa5 { The best defensive idea. } 37... Qxb2 38.
Rxc5
{ I saw all of this in advance and thought I had decent winning chances in the arising endgame. }
38... dxc5 39. Qxb2 Rxb2 40. Rxd7 Rxe2+ 41. Kh3 Rxa2 { This was all forced. }
42. g4 { A very good defensive idea, reducing a lot of material. } 42... hxg4+
43. Kxg4 Rg2+ { A useful check to include before going for the c4-pawn. } 44.
Kh3 Rc2 45. Rc7 { White needs to take one of the c-pawns. } 45... Rxc4 46. Rxc6
Rc1 { These moves were more or less forced. } 47. Kg4
{ White is trying to eliminate more pawns with h5. } 47... c4 48. h5
{ But in fact, this is a losing mistake! It's not easy to understand why, though. He had to defend passively by  47.Kg3  or  47.Rc8  . }
48... f6
{ Giving away the win. It was necessary to play  48...Kh6!  49.hxg6  fxg6  . You will see the difference compared to the game in a few moves. Also,  50.Kg3  c3  51.Kf2  c2  52.Ke2  loses to  52...Rh1  53.Rxc2  Rh2+  54.Kd3  Rxc2  55.Kxc2  Kg5  56.Kd3  Kf4  57.Ke2  Kg3  58.Ke3  g5  with an easy win. }
49. hxg6 Kxg6 50. Kg3 c3 51. Rc8 c2 52. Kg2
{ White needs to wait now, but there is no way to improve the position. However, if the pawn was on g6 and not f6, it would be possible to bring the king to f4 and undermine the white pawns with ...g4, eventually taking the e4-pawn as well with an easy win. }
52... Kg5 53. Rc6 Ra1 54. Rxc2 Kf4 55. Rc6 Ra2+ 56. Kf1 Kxf3 57. Rxf6+ Ke3 58.
Rb6 Rf2+ 59. Ke1 Ra2
{ Draw. It was a missed chance but also a good learning opportunity. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Sim Maerevoet − Leon Livaic, Budapest 2024"]
[Result "*"]

{ Comments by GM Leon Livaic.  This game was played in the final round of the 2024 Olympiad. It may be the last game I play in the Olympiads, so I wanted to make it a good one. }
1. c4
{ My opponent is a solid IM who is playing everything as White. So I decided not to prepare at all and just play  1...d6  . }
1... d6 2. Nc3 e5 3. Nf3 f5 4. d4 e4 5. Ng5 c6 6. g3 { A rare sideline. } 6...
Be7
{ We gave  6...h6  in the course, but in this game, I opted for the less forcing line. The structure is similar to many other lines, so you'll see some of the important moments and plans. }
7. h4 { Logical, preparing Nh3-f4 without having to worry about ...g5. } 7...
Nf6
{ As usual in this line, we go for the ...Na6-c7-e6 and we often play ...O-O too. }
8. Bg2 Na6 9. O-O Nc7 { Both sides are finishing their development. } 10. b3
{ 10.d5  was probably the critical move, stopping Black from going  both ...d5 and ...Ne6. The game move is a huge strategic mistake, as it takes away the b3-square for the queen. }
10... d5
{ Now Black gets a great French structure, the bishop on g2 is horrible and there is no Qb3 to put pressure on the d5-pawn. }
11. Bf4
{ White has to live with his position, developing the pieces. There is no threat though. }
11... h6
{ This felt like the right time to kick the knight away; that way, we can finish development with ...Be6 and ...O-O. }
12. Nh3 Be6 { Now c4 is hanging as well. } 13. Rc1
{ It was, of course, possible to take  13.cxd5  , but after  13...Ncxd5  , it wouldn't be much different than the game. }
13... Bd6
{ 13...dxc4  14.bxc4  Bxc4  15.Nxe4  briefly crossed my mind, but it doesn't work, so I need to execute the positional approach − exchange White's active pieces, don't exchange the passive ones. }
14. e3 { Fixing the pawn structure. } 14... Bf7
{ It could be useful to bring the bishop to h5 in the future as White's last move weakened a lot of squares. }
15. cxd5
{ White wants to get some pieces off the board. He lacks space so exchanges suit him. }
15... Ncxd5
{ It's important to take like this to keep the c-file closed; that way, White has no active play. }
16. Nxd5 Nxd5
{ We don't mind exchanging all the minor pieces, except the passive bishop on g2. There could also be attacking ideas like ...g5 in some lines. If White ever plays h5, that pawn will be very weak. }
17. Be5
{ Trying to unbalance the position after  17...Bxe5  18.dxe5  followed by Qd4. }
17... O-O { The bad thing for White is that there is no threat. } 18. Nf4
{ Now, at least the ...g5 ideas aren't so dangerous, as the rook is not on h8 anymore. }
18... Bxe5 19. dxe5 { White counts on  19...Qe7  20.e6  Bxe6  21.Ng6  . } 19...
Re8
{ The only move but good enough. Now, White will be unable to save the pawn. }
20. Nxd5
{ Black is objectively winning anyway, but bringing my pieces into play with tempo surely doesn't help much. }
20... Qxd5 21. Qxd5 Bxd5
{ The rest is just a matter of technique. Black will be a clean pawn up and White got strategically outplayed. }
22. Rfd1 Kf7
{ Why take on e5 with the rook when we can do it with the king and activate it along the way? }
23. Bf1 { Trying to play Bc4 and activate the rooks. } 23... Rad8 24. Rc5
{ 24.b4  was maybe a better try to exchange pawns and open more files. } 24...
b6 25. Rc2 Ke6
{ Now the position is playing itself basically. Take on e5, open up the files with ...g5, etc. }
26. Rcd2 Kxe5 { Finally, the pawn is gone. } 27. Bc4 g5
{ White will manage to open the c-file, but the rook endgame is completely lost. }
28. hxg5
{ One of the files will get open for sure for our rooks. White chooses the h-file. }
28... hxg5 29. b4 { Trying to undermine the bishop with b5. } 29... Rd6
{ This is the easiest. After  30.b5  , there is  30...Red8  31.bxc6  Bxc6  , and the idea is to double on the h-file. }
30. Bxd5 { White is desperate for some active play. } 30... cxd5
{ It's better to keep both pairs of rooks, as we can try to go for checkmate. }
31. Rc1 { Hoping for Rc7. } 31... f4
{ Now there is a big problem for White: will he allow ...f3 or bring the black king to f4? }
32. Rc7 { Both options are hopeless. } 32... f3 33. g4
{ Taking away the f5-square for the Black king. Now  33...Rh6  fails to  34.Rd7  , and @@StartFEN@@4r3/p1R5/1p1r4/3pk1p1/1P2p1P1/4Pp2/P2R1P2/6K1 b - - 0 33@@EndFEN@@  33...Rh8  to  34.Re7+  . }
33... d4 { Unfortunately for White, this is extremely strong. } 34. Rxd4
{ If White allows ...d3, his rook on d2 will be passive forever. } 34... Rxd4
35. exd4+ Kxd4 36. Rxa7
{ White regained material, but his king is just too weak. } 36... e3
{ The finishing touch. The king is heading to g3 via f4. } 37. fxe3+
{ 37.Rd7+  Ke4  makes no difference. } 37... Kxe3 38. Kf1
{ Or  38.Rf7  Re4  . } 38... Rh8 { Threatening mate in 1. } 39. Re7+ Kf4 40.
Kg1 Kg3
{ White resigned as ...f2+ is coming. A fitting way to end my first Olympiad. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Sven Tica − Leon Livaic, Kaštel Novi 2024"]
[Result "*"]

{ Comments by GM Leon Livaic.  This game was played in the final round of the Croatian Club Cup 2024. My team needed a win to win the event, which influenced some of my choices in this game. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O Bf5 6. c4 O-O 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Nxe4
Bxe4 9. Be3 Nd7
{ 9...e5  equalizes the easiest, as we have seen in the 1.d4 chapter, but I wanted to keep more tension on the board and not allow trades after  10.dxe5  . }
10. Qd2 { Preparing Bh6 ideas. } 10... c6
{ A flexible move, keeping the options of all pawn moves open in the future. I can imagine ...e5, ...d5, ...c5, ...b5 and ...a5 being playable in this position. }
11. Rad1
{ Bringing the rook to the central file, but I think Rac1 and Rfd1 is the more logical setup. }
11... a5 { Trying to seize space on the queenside with ...a5-a4. } 12. Bh3
{ A good idea, forcing my hand. White wants to play Ng5. } 12... Bxf3
{ Forced, but even though we are parting ways with the bishop, White's pawn structure gets messed up, and his pieces are temporarily misplaced. }
13. exf3 e6 { Creating a strategic threat of ...d5. } 14. Rfe1
{ This is a mistake.  14.d5  was needed no matter the consequences. I planned  14...exd5  15.cxd5  c5  followed by ...b5, while White tries for f4-f5. }
14... d5
{ After this move, Black is doing great; we can play ...a4  followed by ...Qa5 and maybe ...Nb6. }
15. Bf1 { This was a big surprise, I thought  15.b3  is the only try. } 15...
dxc4
{ Considering White doesn't fight for control over d5, we can bring the knight there. }
16. Bxc4 Nb6 17. Be2 Nd5
{ Black achieved everything; he has better structure and better pieces. } 18.
h4 { White lacks a plan. } 18... a4
{ Trying to go ...Qa5, and if the queens get traded, it should be possible to simply double on the d-file and attack the d4-pawn 4 times. }
19. Kg2 { White makes small improving moves, but he has no active play. } 19...
Qa5 20. Qc1 { Correctly keeping the queens on the board. } 20... a3
{ Trying to open the a-file or gain the c3-square. } 21. Bc4
{ Defending a2, but there are more problems. } 21... axb2
{ Time for a change of the structure. } 22. Qxb2 Nxe3+ 23. fxe3 b5
{ A very important move, forcing White to either give up a2 or allow ...c5. }
24. Bb3 { Saving the pawn. } 24... c5 25. Re2
{ White's position is extremely passive. } 25... Rfb8 26. Rc1 cxd4
{ 26...c4  was a much better move, but regarding the match situation where I just needed to draw to win the title, I went for a simpler position where I will never lose. In any other situation, I would have played  26...c4  27.Bd1  Qc7  ,  threatening ...e5, followed by either ...e5 or ...b4. }
27. exd4 Rd8
{ Black is still better as he has a safer king, and White has a weakness. } 28.
Rd1 Rd6 { We will hit d4 with everything we got. } 29. Qc2
{ So White gives it up immediately. } 29... Rxd4 30. Rxd4 Bxd4 31. h5
{ Searching for counterplay with hxg6 and Bxe6 ideas. } 31... Bg7 32. hxg6 hxg6
33. Qe4 Rf8 { Here we agreed to a draw. Black is still quite a bit better. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Kristof Pal Kolimar − Leon Livaic, Ajka 2024"]
[Result "*"]

{ Comments by GM Leon Livaic. } 1. Nf3
{ Although this was a rapid tournament, and I played against a lower-rated player, the game shows quite well the dangers of not knowing how to deal with  1...d6  as a positional player with White. }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. c4 Bf5 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bxb1 8. Rxb1
O-O 9. f4 c6
{ Thus far, it has all been covered in the 1.d4 chapter. Black already has quite a comfortable position. }
10. Qb3
{ This innocent-looking move is already a mistake. White should play  10.O-O  and try to develop quickly. If that happens, we should play the ...Re8, ...Nbd7 and ...e5 plan. }
10... Qb6
{ A very nice move, immediately putting pressure on d4. White can't castle, and  11.Qxb6  axb6  would activate the a8-rook. }
11. Nf3 { Best, defending d4 and improving the misplaced knight. } 11... Nbd7
{ Finishing development and preparing ...e5. } 12. e3
{ White has to try to hold everything together. } 12... e5
{ We can't let White consolidate with O-O and Bd2, where he would have a long-term bishop pair play. This quick reaction is just what the doctor ordered. :@@EndBracket@@ }
13. fxe5
{ After  13.O-O  e4  followed by ...d5, Black is also better due to more space. }
13... dxe5 14. O-O
{ Taking the pawn would ruin White's pawn structure, and after ...Ng4, he wouldn't be able to keep it anyway. }
14... Rfe8 { Now the plan is to double on the e-file and play ...exd4. } 15.
Qc2
{ Trying to keep the position more complex by keeping the queens on the board. }
15... Re7 16. c5 { A good move, forcing the queen on a more passive square. }
16... Qc7 17. e4
{ This is a big concession, as the e4-pawn will be isolated and weak in the future. }
17... Rae8
{ 18.d5  isn't possible yet, so there is no need to react for now. We can improve the position by bringing the last piece into play. }
18. dxe5 { Forced, as Black was threatening ...exd4 and ...Nxe4. } 18... Nxe5
19. Bf4
{ The point, but Black will soon get out of the pin, and the g2-bishop is bad. }
19... Nh5 { Trying to take on f4. } 20. Bg5
{ Maybe it was better to play  20.Nxe5  Bxe5  21.Bg5  , but after  21...f6  , Black is still better. }
20... Bf6 21. Bd2 { This is a big blunder. } 21... Nxf3+ { The point. } 22.
Bxf3 { Or  22.Rxf3  Rxe4  with a winning position. } 22... Nxg3
{ My opponent probably missed  23.hxg3  Qxg3  24.Bg2  Bd4+  . } 23. Rf2
{ A sad move, but the position is hopeless anyway. } 23... Bd4 24. Bc3
{ The rest is only a matter of technique. } 24... Bxc3
{ 24...Bxf2+  and  24...Bxc5  were also completely winning. } 25. bxc3 Nxe4
{ Now it's two clear pawns. } 26. Bxe4 { Or  26.Rff1  Nxc5  . } 26... Rxe4 27.
Qb3 Re1+ { The quickest way. } 28. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 29. Kg2 Qe7
{ Heading towards g5. } 30. Qc4 Qg5+ { White resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
