[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Balazs Martini − Leon Livaic, Hungarian Open Rapid Championship 2024"]
[Result "*"]

{ Comments by GM Leon Livaic. } 1. d4
{ This game is a good example of how dangerous the main line Philidor plan with ...Nc5 and ...Be6 can be against players who are not familiar with it. }
1... d6 2. e4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. h3 c6 8. a4 a5
9. Ba2
{ As we said, this sideline is not particularly challenging because this move usually becomes a waste of a tempo after ...Be6. }
9... exd4 10. Nxd4 Nc5 { Following our plan. } 11. Re1 Be6
{ All of this is, of course, covered in the Philidor chapter. } 12. Nxe6 fxe6
13. e5 dxe5 14. Be3
{ This is the first new move, but leaving the queens on the board should help Black; he might use it to attack b2 and f2 in the future. }
14... Nd5
{ A logical move, taking full control of the center. Even though Black's pawns are doubled, he has an extra pawn and White has no good targets. }
15. Qg4 { Threatening Bxc5 followed by Qxe6+ and Ne4. } 15... Kh8
{ A nice prophylactic move, as now f2 will be hanging. } 16. Rad1
{ White plays a logical move, bringing his last piece into action. } 16... Qb6
{ Now, b2 is hanging, and the queen could also do some damage on the diagonal after we take on e3. }
17. Ne4
{ Probably best − White is hoping to get an opposite-colored bishop endgame, which gives more chances of surviving. }
17... Nxe3 { It's time to cash-in. } 18. fxe3
{ 18.Rxe3  wouldn't change much. } 18... Nxe4 19. Qxe4 Qxb2
{ Now we are 2 pawns up − 2 ugly pawns, but 2 pawns. } 20. Bb1
{ White wants to play c3 or c4 and threaten checkmate, but  20.Bb3  was objectively better. }
20... Qc3 { Stopping White's idea. Now the bishop remains passive on b1. } 21.
Kh2 { A safer square for the king than g1. } 21... Rad8
{ It's always good to change your passive rook for an opponent's active one. Also, this prevents Rd3 followed by c3. }
22. Rxd8 Bxd8
{ Leaving the rook on f8 is better, as it can help with mating attacks. } 23.
Rd1 { White puts the rook on the open file. } 23... Bg5
{ Attacking e3. Black is winning. } 24. Rd3 { The last trick. } 24... Qe1
{ Now ...Rf1 is the threat. } 25. c3
{ 25...Rf1?  loses to  26.Rd8+  Bxd8  27.Qxh7#  . } 25... Qxb1
{ But simply taking the bishop is enough. } 26. Rd8 Qf1
{ White resigned. Very often, players who are lower-rated have very limited knowledge of the Philidor plans, as it's a rare opening, and it is studied nowhere near as much as @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR b KQkq e3 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...e5  or  1...c5  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Alexander Donchenko − Anish Giri, Wijk aan Zee 2024"]
[Result "*"]

{ Here is a recent game from an elite event. } 1. d4 d6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 g6 4.
Bg2 Bg7 5. c4 Bf5 6. Qb3 Qc8 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. d5 Nd8 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 Ne4
{ This is where we ended the analysis in the 1.d4 chapter. } 11. Nxe4 Bxe4
{ This trade was helpful as Black has less space. Now, it will be easier to find squares for the d8-knight. }
12. Bd2
{ White finishes development, probably trying to exchange the g7-bishop with Bc3 later on. }
12... b6 { The knight is heading towards c5 via b7. } 13. Bc3 e5
{ It was also possible to trade, but this gives White something to think about. He has to either exchange the d5-pawn and lose the space advantage, or let us have this structure and expand on the kingside in the future. }
14. dxe6
{ White doesn't want to risk much, but Black was more than fine anyway. } 14...
Nxe6 { The knight can now go to c5 via e6. } 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Qc3+
{ White managed to exchange the strong bishop on g7, but he can't attack on the kingside. }
16... Kg8 17. Nd4
{ Probably, Donchenko wanted to steer the game towards a draw by exchanging more pieces. }
17... Bxg2 18. Kxg2 { Forced. } 18... Ng5
{ This move secures the h3-square for our queen, connecting our rooks as well. }
19. h4 { Getting rid of the knight but weakening the king. } 19... Qh3+ 20. Kg1
Ne4 { Now White always has to think about ...Nxg3 motifs. } 21. Qf3
{ Holding everything together. } 21... Rae8
{ There are no clear targets to attack, so the next order of business is to include our inactive pieces − the rooks. }
22. Rad1 a6 { This eliminates Nb5 ideas. Black is in no hurry. } 23. Nc2
{ Heading towards d5. } 23... Qe6
{ Black can't really checkmate the white king as there are too few pieces, so the queen will be more useful in the center of the board. }
24. Ne3 { Defending c4 and trying to go Nd5. } 24... c6
{ Great strategic play from Giri. He understands that the d6-pawn will be very hard to attack, and now he also has ...b5 or ...d5 ideas in the air. }
25. Qf4 f5 { Reinforcing the knight on e4. } 26. Kg2 Rf7
{ Trying to triple on the e-file. } 27. f3
{ White kicks the annoying knight, but now there are some weaknesses in his position. }
27... Nf6 { Forced. } 28. Nf1
{ The knight was under attack, but this gives up control of the d5-square. }
28... d5 { Black uses the opportunity. } 29. b3
{ White doesn't want to play  29.cxd5  and bring the knight  to d5 with tempo. }
29... Rd7
{ Now we see how useful the prophylactic 26...Rf7 was. It's easier to double on either the e-file or the d-file. }
30. Rd3 { Trying to go Re3. } 30... Qf7 31. Qd2 Rde7
{ Now ...dxc4 becomes a real threat. } 32. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Black outplayed White strategically. } 33. Rd4 Re5
{ Now the idea is either to triple or to push ...f4, when the rook could be useful on the fifth rank. }
34. e4
{ At least there is no more backward e2-pawn, but there is no threat yet. }
34... a5
{ Giri plays a slow improving move, securing the b4-square if needed later on. It's hard to suggest a move for White. }
35. Qd3 { This is a mistake. } 35... c5
{ Now the rook can't stay on the d-file. } 36. f4
{ Of course,  36.Rxd5  Rxd5  loses, as the e1-rook is hanging. } 36... cxd4 37.
fxe5 Nb4
{ Now the inclusion of ...a5 really helps because the knight won't be hanging. }
38. Qb5 Rc8 { Giri wants to go to ...Rc2 and play for mate. } 39. Kg1
{ A mistake, but the position was very hard anyway. } 39... f4
{ Now the f-file will open, and the queen joins the attack. } 40. gxf4 Qxf4 41.
Qd7 { Desperation. } 41... Rf8 { White resigned since ...Qf2+ is coming. } *

