[Black "Gawain Jones − Ding Liren, chess24.com 2022"]
[Result "*"]

{ Let's learn from the World Champion! } 1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3
Nbd7 5. Rg1 c6 6. g4 h6 7. Be3 Be7 8. Qd2 exd4
{ In the course, we suggested  8...b5  in this exact line, but this also leads to similar structures we have in other lines. }
9. Qxd4
{ 9.Nxd4  Ne5  10.f4  @@StartBracket@@only  10.f4  , otherwise 10...c5@@EndBracket@@ is critical, but it comes with a pawn sacrifice. }
9... Qa5 { Activating the queen and intending ...b5-b4. } 10. Be2
{ Finishing development. } 10... Ne5 { Ding also needs to finish development. }
11. h3 { Defending g4. } 11... Be6 12. a3
{ White puts the pawn here so he can play O-O-O without it hanging. } 12...
Nfd7 { The known plan − the bishop will go to f6 and the knight to b6 or e5. }
13. Qd2 { The queen will be less exposed here. } 13... Nxf3+ 14. Bxf3 O-O-O
{ Now the queen is awkwardly placed on d2; ...d5 ideas are in the air. } 15.
Be2 { ...Ne5 will not be a tempo now. } 15... Bf6 { This is the typical idea. }
16. f4 { Trying to trap the bishop with f5. } 16... Bxc3 17. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 18.
bxc3 { After this trade, the structure is quite bad for White. } 18... Rhe8
{ Counting on  19.f5  Bd5  . } 19. O-O-O { Attacking d6. } 19... Nb6
{ The idea is to push ...c5 and put something on c4.  19...Bd5  was probably better, forcing the trades. }
20. f5 { Attacking the bishop and maybe trying to play f6 to make h6 weak. }
20... Bd5 { 20...Bc4  was also good. } 21. Bd4
{ White will try to exchange both minor pieces and save the rook endgame. }
21... f6 { Forced, as g7 was hanging. } 22. exd5 Rxe2 23. Bxb6 axb6
{ Black has all the winning chances with a better structure and the active rook on e2. }
24. Rge1 Re5
{ A great move, hoping to get the protected passed pawn on e5 after the trade. }
25. c4 { Protecting d5. } 25... Kc7 26. Rxe5
{ This is a big blunder, but it was hard to defend passively too. } 26... dxe5
{ Now there will be too many targets to attack for Black. } 27. Kb2 b5
{ This wins on the spot. } 28. Kb3
{ 28.cxb5  Rxd5  is also completely lost. The protected passed pawns are a huge asset in any endgames, especially pawn endgames. }
28... bxc4+ 29. Kxc4 Rxd5 30. Rxd5 cxd5+ 31. Kxd5
{ No matter how active the White king is, it can't get more active as the e-pawn will go down the board. }
31... Kb6 { The rest is very easy. } 32. Kc4 Ka5 33. Kb3 Kb5 34. Kc3
{ 34.c4+  Kc5  35.Kc3  loses after  35...e4  . } 34... Ka4 35. Kb2 e4
{ White will lose both of the queenside pawns in exchange for the e-pawn, and the b-pawn decides the game. }
36. h4 e3 37. Kc3 Kxa3 38. g5 b5 39. gxf6 gxf6 40. Kd3 Kb2
{ White resigned. It was a high-quality rapid game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Francisco Vallejo Pons − Magnus Carlsen, Sao Paulo/Bilbao 2012"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ This ending can also be played for a win with Black, as the game shows. } 6.
Nf3 Bd6 7. Bg5 Be6 8. O-O-O Nd7 9. Nb5 Ke7 10. Nxd6 cxd6 11. Bb5 Rhd8
{ Until here, it was given in the course, and the conclusion was that Black is already preferable. But let's see how the game went on. }
12. Nd2
{ White defends the e4-pawn in order to keep the dark-squared bishop after ...h6. }
12... h6
{ It's good to play this before White further reinforces the e4-pawn with f3. }
13. Bh4
{ Keeping the bishop, but  13.Bxf6+  Nxf6  14.Rhe1  Rac8  also looks more pleasant for Black despite the reduced material. }
13... g5 14. Bg3 a6
{ It's good to attack this bishop as well, asking White more questions. } 15.
Bxd7
{ Paco decides to trade this bishop. It was possible to keep it with  15.Be2  , but then after  15...Rac8  16.f3  Nh5  , Black's pieces are very active. }
15... Rxd7
{ Despite the opposite-colored bishops, White's position looks quite unpleasant. And it doesn't seem he did anything wrong thus far. }
16. f3 { It's good to consolidate the position this way. } 16... Rc8
{ Magnus is bringing all the pieces into play. } 17. Kb1
{ White defends the a2-pawn in order to be able to reroute the knight with Nf1-e3.   Obviously,  17.Nf1  immediately is a reckless decision due to  17...Bxa2  18.b3  Bxb3  . }
17... Nh5 { The threat of ...f5 is strong. } 18. Nf1
{ The knight is heading towards e3. } 18... f5
{ Black is just in time to go for this before the knight gets to e3. } 19. exf5
Bxf5 20. Ne3 Bg6 { From here, the bishop puts pressure on c2. } 21. Rd2
{ Paco defended for the time being, but his position remains passive. } 21...
Ke6 { And Black is ready to push the pawns: ...d5 and ...b5. } 22. b3
{ A smart idea to improve the king's position − now it can go to b2. } 22... b5
{ Let's push! } 23. Kb2 d5 { And then push some more! } 24. Re1
{ Eyeing the e5-pawn, which became weak after the ...d5 push. Both Bxe5 and Ng4 are being threatened. }
24... Nxg3 { It's time to get rid of the attackers of the e5-pawn. } 25. hxg3
h5 { And stop Ng4. } 26. c3
{ A good move, aimed against the ...d4 push. Note that Paco defended very well until this point, but his position still looks a bit unpleasant. }
26... d4
{ This breakthrough should lead to an equal position with correct play. It was possible to keep the status quo after  26...Rcd8  , although it's not easy to improve the position further. }
27. cxd4 Rxd4 28. Rxd4 exd4 29. Nc2+
{ Forced. White needs to keep the c2-square under control. The knight attacks d4, and after ...Kd5, it will go to b4 with tempo. }
29... Kd5 30. Nb4+ Kd6 31. Rc1
{ Here comes the decisive mistake. As it happens, after a long defense, you miss something, and then the position is just lost.   31.Rd1!  was the only way to stay in the game. If  31...a5  , there is  32.Rxd4+  , or after @@StartFEN@@2r5/8/p2k2b1/1p4pp/1N1p4/1P3PP1/PK4P1/3R4 b - - 5 31@@EndFEN@@  31...Ke5  only now  32.Rc1!  Rxc1  33.Kxc1  . This endgame is equal, as  33...a5  is met with  34.Nc6+  . }
31... Rxc1 32. Kxc1 h4 { The endgame is hopeless for White. } 33. gxh4 gxh4 34.
Nxa6 Bd3
{ This is the point − the g2-pawn will fall after ...Bf1xg2, and then the h-pawn will be unstoppable. }
35. Nb4 { The knight needs to come back into play, but it's all too late. }
35... Bf1 36. Kd2 Bxg2 37. Ke2 Bh3
{ The last important detail − the bishop comes back into the game, and then the h- and d-pawns supported by the king and bishop will decide the game. }
38. a4 Bf5 39. axb5 d3+ 40. Ke3 h3
{ It's just not possible to stop the pawns. } 41. Nxd3 Bxd3
{ The bishop will go back to f5, and Black will collect the b-pawns. White resigned. A very instructive game, showing that the Philidor endgame is full of possibilities. Paco Vallejo got a passive position and defended well but blundered under pressure. }
*

