1. Nf3
{ In this game, we'll see how the interesting move 6...b5 works in practice against White's double fianchetto setup. }
1... Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. d4 d6 6. b3 b5 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. Nbd2
Nbd7 9. c4 bxc4 10. Nxc4 a5 11. Rc1 c5
{ 11...Ra6  is the recommended move in the course, but  11...c5  makes sense as well. Black is breaking the center right away. }
12. dxc5 Nxc5
{ Black has more pawns in the center, which is a good thing. But the a5-pawn may need protection. }
13. Bd4 Ncd7 14. a4 { White is fixing the a5-pawn but weakens b3 in return. }
14... Ra6
{ A good way to activate the pieces. The queen will go to a8, putting pressure on the long diagonal, and the other rook goes to c8. }
15. Na3
{ A good maneuver, rerouting the knight to b5. The c-file is now open, and both sides will fight to control it. }
15... Qa8 16. Nb5 Rc6
{ The rook did its duty on a6, and now it moves away to avoid the fork on c7. }
17. Rxc6 Bxc6 18. Ne1
{ It's understandable that Georg wants to release the pressure on the long diagonal. }
18... Bxg2 19. Nxg2 Rc8 20. Na7 Rd8
{ 20...Rb8  looks more natural, but Magnus wants to push the central pawns. }
21. Qc2
{ I guess White didn't understand what his opponent wanted to do and just decided to take control of the c-file.   In hindsight, it was better to retreat the knight  21.Nb5  , when the pawn push loses its strength, as after  21...e5  22.Bc3  d5  , there is  23.Nc7  attacking the queen, and Black cannot defend  both a5 and d5-pawns. }
21... e5 { It's time to push! } 22. Be3 { Forced. } 22... d5
{ Black got a nice center, and there is a threat of ...d4. } 23. Nc6
{ A tempting move, aiming to take the a5-pawn. However, it was better to first activate the queen  23.Qc7!  and then go Nc6. }
23... Re8 { The best square available for the rook, stopping Ne7+ ideas. } 24.
Bd2
{ The a5-pawn is doomed, but Black's position is better due to the strong center. }
24... Ne4
{ The knight is strong here, but even so, it was better to play  24...Bf8  in order to bring the rook  to c8 afterwards. }
25. Nxa5
{ This is just wrong, as it allows the black rook to come to c8.   25.Bxa5  looks scary, but that's the way to go. After  25...Re6  , there is  26.Nd8!  , and here after  26...Qxa5  27.Nxe6  fxe6  , a position with material imbalance arises, where White has his own chances due to the a- and b-pawns, while after @@StartFEN@@q2N2k1/3n1pbp/4r1p1/B2pp3/P3n3/1P4P1/2Q1PPNP/5RK1 b - - 2 26@@EndFEN@@  26...Ra6  27.b4  Bf6  , White is in time to get counterplay on the c-file with  28.Rc1  . }
25... Rc8
{ Now White's pieces lose coordination. The white knight is stranded on a5, while Black's knight is dominating on e4. }
26. Qa2 Ndf6 { With several ideas like ...Nxd2 or ...Bf8. } 27. Be1
{ A sad necessity. The bishop is needed to defend the a5-knight. } 27... Nc3
{ A good decision @@StartBracket@@it's Magnus with Black after all@@EndBracket@@, forcing the trade of the knight for the bishop. However, there is another knight that can get to e4. }
28. Bxc3 Rxc3 29. b4
{ The only move to save the knight. However, White's pieces are completely uncoordinated here. }
29... Bf8
{ Not a bad move, but  29...d4!  was just winning, for example,  30.Nb3  Qd5  31.Rb1  Ne4  with total domination. }
30. Qb2
{ White understandably defends the b4-pawn. In such positions, it's said that if you suffer, at least have some material for it.   Nevertheless,  30.Nb3!  giving back the pawn,  30...Bxb4  31.a5  would have offered good chances to survive. White can then bring the other knight into  play with Ne1-f3. }
30... d4
{ Black is winning now, but Georg will get some chances to stay in the game later on. }
31. e3 Ne4 32. exd4 exd4 33. Nb3 d3
{ Black is just winning because of the d3-pawn and the very active pieces. There are many threats like ...Rc2, ...Qxa4, or ...Bg7. }
34. Rc1 { Trying to trade a rook to ease the pressure. } 34... Rxc1+
{ 34...Bxb4  is a bit more precise, just to keep the pieces active. } 35. Qxc1
Qxa4 36. Qc4 Nc5 { A nice-looking and strong move. } 37. Nd2 Qa1+
{ Probably Magnus was in time trouble here. After this check, White is again in the game.  37...Bh6!  was very strong, with an easy win. }
38. Nf1 d2 39. Ne3 Ne6 40. Qb3 Qe1 41. Kg2 Bxb4
{ The time trouble is over. Black is up the d2-pawn. However, the pawn is blocked, and it's not easy to make progress. }
42. Qb2
{ 42.Qxb4?  was not possible due to  42...d1=Q  43.Qb8+  Qd8  with an extra queen for Black. }
42... h5 43. h4 Ba5 44. Qb8+ Nf8 45. Qa8 Bc3 46. Qc6
{ 46.Qd5  immediately was more precise. Obviously, the queen in the center is more active.  White can then play Qd3, and try to bring the f1-knight into play via Nh2-f3. }
46... Qc1 47. Qd5 Ne6 48. Qc4 Ba5 { 48...Nd4!  was strong. } 49. Qd5 Bb4 50.
Qb5 Qc3 51. Qd5 Qc1 52. Qb5 Bc3 53. Qa4
{ 53.Qb3!  was called for, and if  53...Bd4  like in the game, then  54.Qd3  is good.  White apparently can hold, but with a pawn on d2, you never know. }
53... Bd4
{ Threatening ...Bxe3. White's queen is misplaced on a4, as it cannot attack the d2-pawn. }
54. Nd1 Kg7 55. Kf3 Bf6
{ It was better to keep the bishop on the a7-g1 diagonal in order to prevent Nfe3. }
56. Ke2
{ The final mistake. After  56.Nfe3  , White can still hope to stop the d-pawn. }
56... Nd4+ 57. Kd3 Qb1+ 58. Kxd2 Qe4
{ The d-pawn is gone, but there are just too many threats due to the weak white king. White resigned. A nice fighting game, not without mistakes. It shows the potential of the line with ...b5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Mai Narva − Inna Gaponenko, European Club Cup 2024"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ This game features the Philidor endgame, and you'll see that things can easily go wrong for White there. }
1... d6 2. e4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bg5 c6
{ The idea is to limit the c3-knight.  6...Nbd7  is the move we recommend in the course. }
7. Bc4 Ke8 8. O-O-O Nbd7 9. Nf3 { The game transposed again to the course. }
9... Bc5
{ This is tempting as it comes with tempo, attacking the f2-pawn. However, in the course, we gave the immediate  9...b5!  , which is a bit more precise.  The c5-square may actually be more useful for the knight later on. }
10. Bh4 { A good way to defend the f2-pawn. } 10... b5
{ Black is starting the pawn push on the queenside. } 11. Bb3
{ The sacrifice  11.Nxb5  cxb5  12.Bxb5  Rb8  13.Bc6  leads to a very unusual position. White has compensation for the piece, but it's not enough to claim an advantage. }
11... a5 12. a4
{ White has to go for this. The knight will be pushed back, but the c4-square becomes available for it in the long run. }
12... b4 13. Nb1 Ng4
{ A good move, attacking the f2-pawn and keeping e5 defended. Black wants to continue with ...f6 to reinforce e5 and shut off the dark-squared bishop. }
14. Rd2
{ But this looks wrong, as the knight on b1 has no squares! It was better to defend the pawn with  14.Rhf1  , and then bring the knight into  play with Nbd2. }
14... f6 { Now both the h4-bishop and the b1-knight are out of play. } 15. h3
Nh6 16. Rdd1
{ Back to the right plan of bringing the b1-knight into play, but with a few tempi down! }
16... g5 17. Bg3 Nf7
{ Over the next moves, both sides bring their pieces into play. } 18. Nbd2 Nd6
{ An ideal square for the knight, controlling important squares like f5, e4, and c4. }
19. Rhe1
{ It's tempting to activate the rook and defend the e4-pawn. However much better was  19.Ne1!  with the idea Nd3. At some point, White could play f3 and hope to bring the bishop into play. }
19... Ke7 { Obviously, the king is well placed in the center. } 20. h4
{ Trying to do something. } 20... h6 21. Nh2
{ It's difficult to find a plan for White. The idea of what she played is to bring the knight to e3 via f1. }
21... Nf8 { Black is also rerouting the knight to f4 via g6. } 22. Nhf1 Ng6
{ The h4-pawn is attacked. } 23. h5
{ It was better to play  23.hxg5  in order to gain a tempo and after  23...hxg5  to play  24.Nc4  . Black is much better, but it's not over yet. }
23... Nf4
{ Black is winning now. The knight is attacking both g2 and h5. And if White takes the knight, a strong pawn will take its place. }
24. Bxf4 { What else? } 24... gxf4 25. f3 Ba6
{ Now White loses an exchange. Note the domination of Black's pieces. White can barely move any piece here. }
26. Nh2 Bf2 27. Rh1 Be2 { The rook is trapped. } 28. Ng4 Bxd1
{ Black wins an exchange, and there is no compensation for it. } 29. Rxd1 Bb6
{ 29...Be3  was even stronger. } 30. Nf1 Rad8 31. g3 Nf7
{ Of course, Black doesn't take on g3 to activate the white knight. } 32. Rxd8
Bxd8
{ It was good for Black to exchange one pair of rooks. The rest of the game is just a matter of technique. }
33. Kd2 Bb6 34. Ke2 Bd4 35. gxf4 exf4 36. Bxf7 Kxf7 37. Nd2 Bxb2 38. Nc4 Bd4
39. Nxa5 { Hoping to get some counterplay with the a-pawn. } 39... c5 40. Nb3
Bg1 41. Kd3 Ke6 42. Kc4 f5
{ The only move; otherwise, White gets real counterplay. } 43. exf5+ Kxf5
{ The black king will collect the h5-pawn soon, and afterwards, White's position falls apart. }
44. a5 Kg5 45. Ne5 Kxh5
{ Now the h-pawn is ready to push, and the knights cannot stop it. } 46. a6
{ Meanwhile, the a-pawn is going nowhere. The rook and bishop will easily stop it. }
46... Ra8 47. Kb5 Kh4 { Black showed good technique and won convincingly. } 48.
Nc1 Be3 49. Ne2 h5 50. Ng6+ Kg5 51. Ne5 h4 52. Ng4 h3 53. Nh2 Kh4 54. Ng4 c4
55. Kxb4 Rxa6 56. Kxc4 Rd6 57. Nc3 Rc6+ 58. Kd3 Rxc3+ 59. Kxc3 Kg3 60. Kd3 h2
{ Black showed nice technique in this game! White played seemingly active moves in the opening but then got into a bad position without a good plan. Keep in mind Black's plans in this game, and you can also win many Philidor endgames! }
