[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Alex Krstulovic − Marko Nenezic, Bajina Bašta 2023"]
[Result "*"]

{ Comments by GM Leon Livaic.  This was the first time I have seen this line being played, and my teammate IM Marko Nenezic employed it very successfully against a strong opponent. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 d6 3. Nf3 g6 4. Nc3 Bg7 5. e4 Bg4 6. Be2 Bxf3 7. Bxf3 e5 8. d5
h5 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Bg5
{ As we said in the course, this is not accurate, as it loses a tempo compared to the main lines where we go ...Bh6 even when the bishop is on c1. }
10... Bh6 11. Bxh6 Rxh6 12. Qd2 Rh8 13. b4
{ This is how White players often react, seizing space on the queenside where they already have more space. }
13... a5
{ With  13...a5  14.a3  included, Black will be able to open the a-file whenever he wants. }
14. a3 { Forced, as otherwise the black knight will get the c5-square. } 14...
Kf8 { The typical plan continues. } 15. h3
{ Maybe White was worried about ...Ng4 ideas, but h3 is the square for the bishop, not the pawn. }
15... Kg7 16. Qe3
{ With this move, it will be easier to play c5 in the future. } 16... Qe7
{ Continuing the plan and stopping c5. } 17. Rfc1 Rhc8
{ Now Black will get to play ...c6 or ...c5. } 18. Na4
{ White lacks a clear plan. } 18... c6 19. b5
{ Strategically, it was a bad move, as now the position will get closed on the queenside, and the play on the kingside favors Black in this structure.   However, it's understandable that White didn't want to play  19.dxc6  bxc6  ,  when Black would have the idea of ...Nf8-e6-d4. Playing a quiet move also wouldn't help White, as then Black can always play ...c5 again, forcing either b5 or bxc5 and ...Nxc5. }
19... c5 20. Qg5
{ I suppose this move isn't so much about attacking as there is nothing to attack with, but more about setting a trap.  20...Nxd5  21.Qxe7  Nxe7  wins a pawn but after  22.Rd1  , Black will lose it, and the position opens up. }
20... Rh8
{ Black will now slowly maneuver all of his pieces to the kingside, bring his king to the safe queenside, and open up the position with ...f5 while White doesn't have a plan at all. }
21. h4 Ng8
{ Exchanging the queens would help Black, as it's easier to open the position without the queens. }
22. Qg3 Kf8 23. Re1 b6 24. Kf1 Ke8 25. Ke2 Kd8 26. Qg5 Kc7
{ The first step of the plan is complete. } 27. Qxe7 Nxe7
{ Probably it wasn't too smart to trade, but even without it, Black had the easy idea of ...Rf8 followed by ...f5. }
28. Nc3 { White brings his stranded knight back into the defense. } 28... f5
{ The second stage of the plan is complete. Now the idea will be to double on the f-file and maybe in the future play ...fxe4 to bring the knight to f5-d4. }
29. g3 Raf8 30. Bg2 fxe4
{ He does this before doubling. This part of the game wasn't played perfectly because of the time trouble, but still Black is always the one putting pressure. }
31. Nxe4 Nf5 32. Kd3 Nd4
{ There is no way White can ever get rid of this knight. } 33. Ra2 Nf6
{ If the knights get exchanged, then what is left behind is the great knight against a bad bishop. }
34. Ng5 Nh7 35. Ne4 Rf5 36. Bh3 Rf7 37. Bg2 Rg8
{ Black is waiting to get to move 40 for the extra time, plus he is considering ...g5. }
38. Rh1 { Prophylaxis against ...g5. } 38... Rf5 39. Ke3 Rgf8
{ Finally, the doubling on the f-file is completed. } 40. Rf1 R5f7 41. Kd3
{ With extra time, Black understands what the right plan is. } 41... Kd7 42.
Bh3+ Ke7 { The king will be needed on this side now. } 43. Bg2 Rf5 44. Ke3
{ This helps Black, as there will be ideas of ...Ng4+ attacking f2 as well. }
44... Nf6 45. Nxf6 { A sad neccesity. } 45... R5xf6 46. Be4 Rf3+
{ A beautiful exchange sacrifice, leaving White completely paralyzed. } 47.
Bxf3 Rxf3+ 48. Kd2 Kf6
{ No way for White to untangle and open up the files for his rooks, while Black can play ...e4, ...Ke5 and infiltrate the position. This is why the king is better here than on c7. }
49. Kc1 e4 50. Re1 Kf5 51. Kd1 Rd3+ 52. Kc1 a4
{ Now Black improved everything he could, and it's time to start taking material. }
53. Rb2 { White stays passive. } 53... Rc3+ 54. Kb1 Rxc4 55. Re3 Ke5 56. Rd2
Nf3 57. Rdd3 Rd4 58. Rc3 Rxd5
{ Total collapse. Now, the central pawns will just roll down the board. } 59.
Kc1 { The rest is just a matter of technique. } 59... Rd4 60. Re2 Kd5 61. Kb2
c4 62. Rxe4 Rd2+ 63. Kc1 Kxe4 64. Re3+ Kd4 65. Rxf3 Re2 66. Rf6 d5 67. Rxb6 Kd3
68. Rf6 Re1+ 69. Kb2 c3+
{ White resigned. With 1...d6, you don't get suffocated; you suffocate your opponent! }
