[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "A.R. Ilamparthi − Leon Livaic, Kavala 2023"]
[Result "*"]

{ Comments by GM Leon Livaic.   This was my maiden  1...d6  game. It was played way before we started making the course. }
1. Nf3 d6 2. g3 e5 3. e4 Nf6 4. d3 c5 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. O-O Be7
{ As we said, this line is extremely rare, and Black has absolutely no problems out of the opening. }
7. Nc3 O-O 8. h3
{ White wants to remove the knight from f3 and then try to push f4 and attack on the kingside. }
8... Rb8 { Preparing ...b5. Our play is on the queenside. } 9. a4
{ It's useful for White to open the a-file as his rook is there, so including  9.a4  a6  makes a lot of sense. }
9... a6
{ The idea remains the same, to push ...b5-b4 and remove the knight from c3. }
10. Nh2 b5 11. axb5 axb5
{ Both sides play their ideas and the game is heating up. } 12. Ng4
{ I expected  12.f4  , but maybe White was worried about  12...b4  13.Ne2  d5  with counterplay. With the game move, White wants to secure  the d5-square for his c3-knight so exchanging the f6-knight surely helps. }
12... Nxg4 { A quick reaction is desireable. } 13. hxg4 Be6
{ Controlling the d5-square so that sometimes I have the option to take the knight there. }
14. f4
{ This is too ambitious now, White surely had a pleasant position after  14.Nd5  . }
14... b4 15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. exd5 Nd4
{ This is what White underestimated. Now the knight will be hard to remove as after c3, I can always go to b5, attacking c3, and ...exf4 followed by Bf6 will come. Note that without f4 from White, it would be way harder to activate the e7-bishop. }
17. Ra7
{ White makes use of the a-file as he planned 8 moves ago with @@StartFEN@@1rbq1rk1/pp2bppp/2np1n2/2p1p3/4P3/2NP1NPP/PPP2PB1/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.a4  .   I expected  17.g5  though, but after  17...exf4  18.gxf4  Re8  , Black has a great position.   17.fxe5  dxe5  would allow ...Bg5 ideas in the future. }
17... exf4 18. gxf4 Nb5
{ With this, I can play ...Bf6-d4, and the bishop will be active. } 19. Ra6 Bf6
20. Be4
{ White will try to attack either on the h-file or with g5 and f5 pushes. }
20... g6 { A prophylactic move, restricting the bishop. } 21. Kg2 Bd4
{ This was my idea, but here it's inaccurate. I missed White's next move. It was better to search for counterplay with  21...b3  . }
22. f5
{ I thought this could never be good, as it allows the dark-squared blockade, but White's play is quick. }
22... Bf6 23. Bh6
{ 23.Qf3  was stronger. I would be forced to play  23...g5  24.Rh1  Kg7  25.Qh3  h5  26.Qxh5  Rh8  where White is better, maybe not much but still better. }
23... g5
{ A well-timed exchange sacrifice. If White takes, there will be no more attack and b2 will be weak forever. There are really a lot of weak dark squares. }
24. Qd2
{ This is better, as there is a slow idea of putting the rook to h5 and attacking g5. Still, that takes time. }
24... Re8
{ It's not so much about keeping the rook, more about preparing the ...c4 counterplay. }
25. Rh1 c4 26. Rh5 c3
{ 26...b3  was the alternative, but it made more sense to open the b-file. Now there  will be ...Nd4 and ...Rb2 ideas. }
27. bxc3 bxc3 28. Qc1 { Necessary to keep the threats. } 28... Nd4
{ Black can't defend the pawn, so counterplay is needed. } 29. Bxg5 Rb2
{ Creating big threats. Surprisingly, the position is dynamically balanced if White plays accurately. }
30. Bxf6 Qxf6 31. Rxd6
{ Not like this.  31.Qg5+  was holding, as White can create enough problems for the king  when he plays f6.  31...Qxg5+  32.Rxg5+  Kh8  33.f6  Rxc2+  34.Kg3  Rc1  35.Rg7  c2  36.Rxh7+  with a perpetual. }
31... Qxd6 32. Qg5+ Kf8
{ Of course not  32...Kh8  33.Rxh7+  followed by f6+ and Qg7#. } 33. Rxh7 Rxc2+
34. Kh1 Qe5
{ This is the resource White missed. Now there is no more Rh8+ and f6 is also not possible. }
35. d6 { Creating the threat of Qh6+ perpetual. } 35... Rb8
{ Now I am the one threatening mate. } 36. Qh6+ Kg8 37. Qg5+ Kxh7
{ White tries his last trick. } 38. f6+ Qxe4+
{ Sadly, this comes with check. White resigned due to ...Rb1# next move. A hard-fought and well-earned win. }
