[Black "Nichita Morozov − Jorden van Foreest, Batumi 2018"]
[Result "*"]

{ Comments by GM Leon Livaic. } 1. d4 d6 2. e4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4
Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4 exd4
{ The  7...exd4  line is sometimes played by very strong GMs too. } 8. Nxd4 Ne5
9. Ba2 Nc6 10. h3 Nb4 11. Bb3 c5 12. Nf3 Be6 13. Bxe6 fxe6
{ As we said, it would be better for White to have Re1 instead of h3 in this position. }
14. e5
{ An ambitious approach, However the c2-weakness will be a bigger problem than e6. }
14... dxe5 15. Qe2 { Exchanging the queens would leave c2 undefendable. } 15...
Nc6 { The knight on b4 is good, but on d4 it's even better. } 16. Nxe5
{ Regaining the pawn. } 16... Nd4 17. Qc4
{ Trying to be active and keeping an eye on the e6-pawn. } 17... Bd6
{ But now we can get rid of the knight. } 18. Nd3 Nxc2
{ Facing a lower-rated opponent, Black probably didn't want to play  18...Nd5  19.Nxd5  Ne2+  20.Kh1  Ng3+  with a perpetual. }
19. Nb5 { Now some wild tactics arise. } 19... Nxa1 { Black has to go for it. }
20. Qxe6+ Kh8 21. Nxd6
{ White is an exchange down, but the knight on a1 is bad, and there are threats like Nxc5 or Ne5-f7+ in the position. }
21... Ne4
{ The only move, but Black is fine after it.  22.Nxe4  Qxd3  is important. }
22. Qxe4 Qxd6 23. Bf4 { The critical line, attacking d6 and a1. } 23... Qc6
{ This is important. The queen is White's best piece, so exchanging it will give a lot of activity. }
24. Qc4
{ The losing blunder.  24.Qxc6  bxc6  25.Rxa1  was needed, as  25...c4  26.Bd6  Rfd8  @@StartBracket@@or ...Rf6@@EndBracket@@  27.Ne5  saves both pieces due to  the Nf7+ idea. So Black would have to play a drawish endgame after  @@StartFEN@@r4r1k/p5pp/2pB4/8/P1p5/3N3P/1P3PP1/R5K1 b - - 1 26@@EndFEN@@  26...cxd3  . Another important thing is that @@StartFEN@@r4r1k/p5pp/2p5/2p5/P4B2/3N3P/1P3PP1/R5K1 b - - 0 25@@EndFEN@@  25...Rad8  fails to  26.Nxc5  Rxf4  27.Ne6! }
24... Nb3 { White probably didn't see this idea.  25.Qxb3  c4  wins. } 25. Re1
Rad8 { The rest should be easy. } 26. Re7 Qf6 27. Rc7
{ Surprisingly,  27.Rxg7  was still giving some hope.  27...Rxd3  28.Qxd3  Kxg7  doesn't win due to  29.Qg3+!  and Be5 next, and after  @@StartFEN@@5r1k/pp4Rp/5q2/2p5/P4B2/1n1Q3P/1P3PP1/6K1 b - - 0 28@@EndFEN@@  28...Qxg7  , there is a very difficult move to see:  29.Qe4! }
27... Rxd3 { White resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Pierre Villegas − Romain Edouard, Barcelona 2015"]
[Result "*"]

{ Comments by GM Leon Livaic. } 1. d4 d6 2. e4 Nf6 3. f3 e6
{ This line is little known, but still very usable by strong players when they want to avoid the drawish  3...e5  4.dxe5  . }
4. Nc3 Be7 5. Be3 a6
{ We suggested  5...O-O  in the course. However, this move order confused White in the game quite nicely. }
6. a4
{ A big decision, as after this move, it will be way harder to play the Qd2 and O-O-O plan. }
6... O-O 7. d5
{ Realizing that, White panicked and neglected development. Now Black gets to develop everything with tempo. }
7... exd5 8. Nxd5 { 8.exd5  would open the e-file after  8...Re8  . } 8... Nxd5
9. Qxd5 Nc6
{ Black's position plays itself, ...Be6, ...Bf6 is next; also, there are ...f5 ideas to try to attack the uncastled king. }
10. Ne2 { Trying to finally develop. } 10... Bf6 { Attacking b2. } 11. c3 Be6
{ Black is in full control. } 12. Qd1 Bg5
{ Before opening up the position with ...f5 or ...d5, it's good to exchange this bishop, as it now only hits the well-defended c3-pawn. }
13. Bxg5 Qxg5 14. Qd2 { Trying to bail out. } 14... Qh4+
{ Of course, we don't trade the queens with such a big development lead. This move also provokes more weaknesses. }
15. g3 Qe7 16. Nf4 { Trying to block the ...d5 break, but... } 16... d5
{ The king is exposed. That's why we put the queen on e7. } 17. exd5
{ 17.Nxe6  was necessary. } 17... Bxd5+ 18. Kf2 Rad8
{ All the pieces get into play. } 19. Nxd5 Qc5+ 20. Qe3 Qxd5
{ White even resigned here, as there is not much to do against ...Rfe8 and ...Qd2+ later. }
