[Black "Karolis Juksta − Vahap Sanal, Riga 2021"]
[Result "*"]

{ Comments by GM Leon Livaic.  In this game, we are going to see that it's not so easy to draw the Philidor endgame, even if White tries to be very solid. }
1. d4 d6 2. e4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. dxe5 dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Bc4 Ke8 7. f3
{ The most solid option, trying not to risk anything. } 7... c6 8. a4 a5 9. Be3
Na6
{ We suggested  9...Nbd7  , but it won't change the nature of the position,  as we are preparing ...Bc5 anyway. }
10. Nge2 { White finishes development. } 10... Bc5 11. Bxc5 Nxc5
{ The knight on c5 can never be removed, only exchanged, and even then Black can play ...Nd7 and bring the other knight to its place. }
12. Nc1 Ke7 13. Nd3
{ At this point, White probably understood he has no advantage and is trying to exchange everything and make a draw vs. his GM opponent. }
13... Nxd3+ 14. Bxd3 Be6
{ Black successfully finished his development. If anyone is to be preferred, it's Black as the white pawns are fixed on the same color as his bishop. }
15. Nd1
{ The knight is restricted on c3 so it's logical to bring it to e3 to support Bc4. }
15... Nd7 { Heading towards c5. } 16. Ne3 Nc5 17. Bc4
{ White continues to exchange pieces, but Black is using that time to improve the remaining pieces. }
17... Rhd8 18. Bxe6 Kxe6
{ All White did was to exchange a bishop, and Black improved the rook, the knight, and the king. }
19. Ke2 g6
{ A nice idea, preparing ...f5, when White will have to take and improve our central control, as e4 will be hanging. }
20. b3 { White needs to protect a4. } 20... f5 21. exf5+ gxf5
{ Now, the g2-pawn is a potential target. } 22. Rhd1 Rxd1 23. Rxd1 b5
{ The white rook on d1 has no access squares on the file, so Black is trying to create the passed a-pawn. }
24. Ra1
{ A passive move, but there was no better alternative. Black outplayed White. }
24... f4
{ Seizing more space, fixing the g2-weakness, and kicking the knight. } 25.
axb5
{ It's a strange decision to do this now. Of course, White wants the counterplay after ...fxe3, but Black will just recapture and have a potential passed pawn. }
25... cxb5 26. Nd1 Nb7
{ The knight will temporarily protect the a5-pawn, making it possible to activate the rook. }
27. Nc3 Rc8 { Step one is to force the king to d2. } 28. Kd2 Rg8
{ Step two: now the fixed g2-pawn has to be either sacrificed or defended with the passive  29.Rg1  Nd6  , where White has a hard time finding a move. }
29. g4 fxg3 30. hxg3 Rxg3 31. Rh1
{ White is counting on the reduced material, hoping he will be able to exchange many pawns. }
31... Rxf3 32. Rxh7 Nd6
{ The endgame is, of course, long-suffering for White. } 33. Ra7 a4
{ 34.bxa4  Nc4+  loses a piece. } 34. Ra6 Kd7 35. Nd5
{ White parts ways with another pawn. Now it's just a matter of technique. }
35... axb3 36. cxb3 Rxb3 37. Nf6+ Ke7 38. Nd5+ Ke6 39. Nc3 Rb4 40. Kc2 e4 41.
Ra7 Rc4 42. Kb3 Rc5 43. Rh7 Re5 44. Rh6+ Kd7 45. Ne2 Kc6 46. Rg6 Kc5 47. Rg4
Nf5 48. Kc3 b4+ 49. Kd2 Kc4 50. Rf4 Nd4 51. Ng3 e3+ 52. Ke1 Kd3
{ White resigned. A very nice positional/technical win! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Eric Prie − Maxime Vachier-Lagrave, Guingamp 2010"]
[Result "*"]

{ Comments by GM Leon Livaic.  Let's see how the London System gets punished by a super GM by using the setup we suggested. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Nf3 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. O-O Nbd7 7. h3 b6 8. c4
Bb7 9. Nc3 { The move order was different, but the setup is the same. } 9...
Ne4 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. Nd2 Bb7 12. Bf3 Qc8
{ This is where we finished the line in the course. Black is very fine. Let's see how we can build the positional pressure from here. }
13. Bxb7 Qxb7 14. Qf3 { White isn't very ambitious in this game. } 14... Rab8
{ This is surely more precise than taking on f3, as the rook on b7 can be used to help the ...b5 break in the future. }
15. Bg5 { Attacking e7, but that's easily defended. } 15... Rfe8 16. Qxb7 Rxb7
17. b3 { White solidifies his position. } 17... e5
{ When the position opens up, it's very clear that the g7-bishop is way stronger than its counterpart. }
18. Nf3
{ Defending d4. Pushing d5 was the alternative, but then Black gets the c5-square for the knight, plus he gets a free hand to push everything on the kingside, starting with ...f5. }
18... h6
{ This is surely useful, as it makes the bishop go to h4 where it's less active and can never go back to e3 if we take on d4 at some point. }
19. Bh4 e4
{ MVL decides to change the nature of the position. He probably didn't want to allow taking on e5. }
20. Ne1 b5
{ This break may seem illogical as it creates the weakness on c7 and the b3-pawn is protected for now. However, when the knight comes to d5, it will protect c7 and can never be dislodged from there. }
21. cxb5 Rxb5 22. Nc2 Nb6 23. Rfc1 Nd5 { Black achieved his first goal. } 24.
Na3 { White improves his knight. } 24... Ra5 25. Nc4 Ra6
{ The rook seems weird here, but it ties the rook to a1. If White ever plays a4, the b3-pawn will be weak. }
26. Bg3 f5
{ White has no active play so we are free to expand on the kingside, trying to weaken the e3-d4 pawn chain by pushing ...f4. }
27. a3 f4 { Not the only way, but surely a good one. } 28. Bxf4
{ White sees this as a chance to eliminate the knight on d5, which is Black's best piece. }
28... Nxf4 29. exf4 Bxd4
{ The bishop is better than the knight, and Black has full central control and a better structure. }
30. Rab1 Rf8 { Eyeing the f4 and f2-pawns. } 31. Ne3 c5
{ Solidifying everything in the center. } 32. g3 g5
{ It was also possible to take the pawn. } 33. fxg5 Rxa3
{ This is the idea, now ...Ra2 is a threat. With the f-file opened, f2 is extremely weak. }
34. gxh6 Ra2 35. Ng4 { 35.Rc2  Rxf2!  doesn't help. } 35... Bxf2+ 36. Kh1 Bd4
{ The rest is easy, just push the pawns. White's pawns can't do any harm. } 37.
Rf1 Rxf1+ 38. Rxf1 e3 39. h7+ Kxh7 { White resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Jonas Buhl Bjerre − Leon Livaic, Petrovac 2024"]
[Result "*"]

{ Comments by GM Leon Livaic.  After a slow start in the European Individual Championship 2024, I recovered and in round 5 faced the #1 player from Denmark, GM Jonas Bjerre. }
1. e4
{ Jonas played all the first moves, but recently he was playing  1.e4  regularly. }
1... d6 { As  1...d6  became my main weapon in 2024, this was expected. } 2. d4
Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Be2
{ My opponent prepared this line for the game. However, he played it in some online blitz games so I expected it. }
5... Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. a4 c6
{ In the course, we suggested  7...exd4  , but I wanted my opponent to play @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1nbppp/2pp1n2/4p3/P2PP3/2N2N2/1PP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.a5  so that we surely transpose to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppn1ppp/3p1n2/4p3/3PP3/2N2N2/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@  5.a4  . }
8. a5 exd4 9. Nxd4 Nc5 10. f3 d5
{ Now we reached the analysis covered in the 5.a4 variation but via a different move order. }
11. e5
{ 10...d5 came as a surprise to my opponent, which suggests he may have been using the Gustafsson-Nemec Chessable course which doesn't mention it. }
11... Ne8 12. Be3 { A new move. Now a head vs. head battle starts. } 12... f6
{ The same plan used against @@StartFEN@@r1bqnrk1/pp2bppp/2p5/P1npP3/3N4/2N2P2/1PP1B1PP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 1 12@@EndFEN@@  12.a6  or  12.f4  , trying to break the white center. }
13. exf6
{ An interesting decision, forcing my knight to f6 where it's restricted by the f3-pawn.  13...Bxf6  fails to  14.Nxc6  , and @@StartFEN@@r1bqnrk1/pp2b1pp/2p2P2/P1np4/3N4/2N1BP2/1PP1B1PP/R2Q1RK1 b - - 0 13@@EndFEN@@  13...Rxf6  looks very artificial. }
13... Nxf6 14. a6
{ Undermining my pawn chain, hoping that c6 will be weak in the future. } 14...
Qc7
{ Finishing development. White played f3 so it makes sense to try to attack with ...Qc7 and ...Bd6 later on. }
15. axb7 { The logical continuation. } 15... Nxb7
{ My first idea was to take with the queen, however, I realized there is  15...Qxb7  16.b4!  followed by b5, with some uncomfortable ideas for White. }
16. Kh1
{ A normal prophylactic move; now White can always defend h2 with Bg1. } 16...
Bd6 17. Bg1 Bd7
{ The best available square for the bishop. Both sides finished their development. }
18. Re1 { Rooks belong on the open files. } 18... a5
{ When you are unsure of the plan, it's usually good to seize more space with the pawns. Also, the pawn is safer on a5 than on a7, and it stops b4 after I bring the knight back to c5. }
19. g3
{ This move surprised me because it weakens the light squares. However, now there will be no more threats on h2 or ...Nh5-f4 ideas. }
19... Nc5
{ The idea is to push ...a4 and fix the b2-pawn, and then try to double on the b-file to attack it. }
20. Bf1 { Opening the rook. } 20... a4
{ During the game, I actually thought I made a mistake with this move, as I wasn't sure what to do if White goes Ra2 followed by Qd2 and Rea1. I would bring the rook to the b-file but my a4-pawn would be quite weak. Still, I am not worse, as White can never take on a4 without dropping b2. }
21. Qd2 Qb7 22. Nd1
{ This was a big surprise as I expected only  22.Ra2  . However, the move makes sense since  the knight is badly placed on c3 and is headed towards e3 and f5. }
22... Rfe8
{ This rook is my worst-placed piece, so let's activate it. Also, the f8-square will surely be needed in the future.   The engine's top move for Black was  22...Nfe4  , but... how to even comment on that? I didn't even consider it during the game. }
23. Ne3 { 23...Qxb2  24.Reb1  loses, so why not play this immediately? } 23...
Bf8
{ I decided to make a prophylactic move so that Nf5 doesn't come with tempo. }
24. Rab1 { A passive move, but it defends b2 nicely. } 24... Ne6
{ This move seizes the initiative. White lost coordination and Black will take the center with ...c5. }
25. Ng2
{ The ugly  25.Nxe6  Bxe6  26.c3  would probably be better objectively, but White is trying to keep a lot of pieces on the board to keep it messy. }
25... c5 { As planned. } 26. Nf5
{ This was White's idea, but there are no threats. } 26... Kh8
{ Another prophylactic move, which makes ...g6 possible in the future without Nh6+.   26...Bc6  was, of course, also possible but I wanted to  keep e6 defended and see what White does next. }
27. Ngh4
{ It's very hard to suggest a move. Black wants to play ...Bc6 and ...d4, so White needs to defend with Bg2. Still, the knights look very ugly here and there are still no threats at all. }
27... Bc6 28. c3 { At least now it's not so easy to play ...d4. } 28... d4
{ Or is it? I was counting on  29.cxd4  Bxf3+  30.Bg2  @@StartBracket@@  30.Nxf3  Qxf3+  is lost because  the f5-knight drops.  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3rb1k/1q4pp/4nn2/2p2N2/p2P3N/5bP1/1P1Q2BP/1R2R1BK b - - 1 30@@EndFEN@@  30...Bxg2+  31.Qxg2  Qxg2+  32.Nxg2  g6  with a pawn-up endgame since d4 would drop there.   Still, White has chances to hold and objectively  28...Rad8  bringing the last active piece into play was much better,  followed by ...g6 and ...d4 ideas. }
29. Bg2
{ This is the final mistake. It makes sense to defend f3, but I believe Jonas missed my next move. }
29... g5 { This is extremely strong, as the knight is trapped. } 30. cxd4
{ I thought  30.Rxe6  Rxe6  31.Qxg5  is forced, but I correctly evaluated that there is no real attack there, as my queen controls the seventh rank, and after  31...dxc3  , White's position will fall apart soon since he can't bring more pieces into the attack. }
30... gxh4 { Now this is just a free piece. } 31. Nxh4 Nxd4
{ Forcing the matter. } 32. Qg5
{ 32.Bxd4  cxd4  33.Qxd4  Bg7  was possible, but the position is hopeless anyway. }
32... Qg7 { The easiest, defending everything. } 33. Qf4
{ A queen exchange is basically resignation, so White has to hope for my blunder in time trouble. }
33... Nd5 { Chasing the queen away from my king. } 34. Qd2 Be7
{ This wins very easily, but some tactics needed to be calculated. } 35. Bxd4
{ Allowing ...Bxh4 is very bad so White tries his last shot. } 35... Qxd4 36.
Qh6
{ But he doesn't go for  36.Ng6+  , as there is  36...Kg7!  and he has to exchange the queens and minor pieces with a lost endgame. Note that  36...hxg6  isn't so clear after  37.Qh6+  Kg8  38.Qxg6  Qg7  39.Qxc6  . }
36... Qf6 { Again, chasing the queen away. } 37. Qh5 Nf4
{ The killer blow. Now more pieces get exchanged and the attack diminishes. }
38. Qg4 Rg8 { Any move wins at this point. } 39. Qf5 Nxg2
{ White resigned. Of course, I was very happy with this win and also with the fact the course line held very well against a strong GM. }
*

[Event "?"]
