[Black "Agoston Botond Juhasz − Mircea Parligras, Petrovac 2024"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. h3
{ My opponent certainly didn't expect me to play 1...d6, so he's trying to get me out of book. }
6... O-O 7. a4 { Again, continuing with the same strategy. } 7... exd4
{ Just opening the center, as my opponent lacks development. } 8. Qxd4 Nc5
{ The usual reply, preparing ...Be6 or ...c6. } 9. Bf4
{ This looks weird without castling. What is he going to do?  9.O-O  Be6  would lead to the course. }
9... Ne6 { I'm going to take one of his bishops. } 10. Bxe6 Bxe6
{ This looks very natural, just completing development. However,  10...fxe6  was more precise, but it wasn't clear to me what happens after  11.e5  . It seems that after  11...c5  12.Qd3  dxe5  13.Qxd8  Rxd8  14.Nxe5  Nd5  , Black is fine. }
11. O-O-O
{ There we go. The plan with long castle, which is quite rarely seen in the Philidor @@StartBracket@@apart from the g4 or Rg1 lines@@EndBracket@@. Here, White has the pawn on a4, which is a weakness, but can I really make use of it? }
11... Nd7
{ This regrouping looks natural. I want to play ...Bf6, ...Re8, and then push on the queenside with ...a6 and ...b5. }
12. Kb1 { The king feels safer here. } 12... Bf6
{ Here and on the next moves, I wanted to make ...a6 and ...b5 work, but I was concerned about e5 breaking the center. }
13. Qe3 Re8
{ Activating the rook, which will be useful if White ever pushes e5. } 14. Rhe1
{ White has a bit more space and is threatening e5. Also, g4-g5 is another plan. }
14... Qc8
{ A difficult move, removing the queen from the d-file, thus stopping e5. The problem is that it's quite passive, and I cannot afford to make many moves like this. White will just push the pawns and I could get suffocated. }
15. g4 { The threat is g5, attacking the f6-bishop. } 15... g6
{ It's not good to push the pawns in front of your king, but I wanted to save the bishop.   I was calculating lines like  15...a6  16.g5  Bxc3  17.Qxc3  Nc5  18.Bc1  and it seemed to me that Black could be in trouble here.  There is an easy plan of b3 and Bb2.  18...Bd7  is the only move to keep the balance. }
16. Bg5
{ Offering a bishop trade, which would obviously be bad for me since I just played ...g6. }
16... Bh8 { I didn't want to allow Bh6 with tempo. } 17. Nd4
{ White's plan is very primitive and strong − just to push f4-f5. } 17... b5
{ The only move to stay in the game and a very beautiful one. Until now, I only thought about playing ...a6 and then ...b5. However, at this moment I realized there was simply no time for that, as f4-f5 is crushing. With this move, I want to open the b-file and get an attack of my own. }
18. Nxe6
{ A good move, forcing me to make a decision. Here and on the next move, my opponent took a deep thought as he was clearly not expecting my counterplay. }
18... Rxe6 { I wanted to keep the rook active. } 19. Nxb5
{ This is a mistake, as it opens the b-file, and I'll get an attack and easy play.   During the game, I thought  19.a5!  is the only move to close the b-file, and then I wasn't sure how to continue.  19...Qa6  20.Nd5  Qxa5  21.Qa3!  Qxa3  22.bxa3  Rc8  23.Ne7+  Rxe7  24.Bxe7  leads to a position where I have compensation for the exchange but probably nothing more.   Also interesting is  19...Ne5  20.Qg3  Nc4  , and here White can sacrifice a pawn with  21.e5  with a very unclear position. }
19... Qb7
{ I wanted to activate my queen and create threats on b2. However,  19...Nc5!  is the more precise way to go,  with a double attack on a4 and e4. }
20. b3
{ This loses, as it weakens the a1-h8 diagonal.  20.Qa3!  was essential, to bring the queen into defense. }
20... Nc5 { The double attack on e4 and a4 is even stronger now. } 21. f3 Nxa4
{ Taking back the pawn and now the white king is very exposed. } 22. Nd4 Qb4
{ The queen goes near the white king. Actually, the computer claims that  22...c5  23.Nxe6  Qb4!  is the easiest win for Black. }
23. Rd3 Ree8
{ Here I thought for a long time, as the intended  23...c5?  is parried by  24.Qd2!  The best way to continue was @@StartFEN@@r5kb/p1p2p1p/3pr1p1/6B1/nq1NP1P1/1P1RQP1P/2P5/1K2R3 b - - 3 23@@EndFEN@@  23...Nc5!  , removing the rook from its active position  on d3. }
24. Qd2 { Bringing the queen into defense. } 24... Qb6
{ Here,  24...Qa3  25.Qc1  Qc5  was more precise, but mistakes are normal, as we were both getting low on time. }
25. Be3 { Missing a good chance to complicate matters with  25.Nf5! } 25... Nc5
26. Ne2 Qa6 27. Rc3
{ The rook is covering the long diagonal. I cannot really take it right away, but it also cannot move away. }
27... Ne6 { A good move since I need to control the d4-square. } 28. Nd4 c5
{ Just as planned, clearing the long diagonal. } 29. Nxe6 Rxe6 30. Qd3
{ White wants to play Bd2 to defend the rook better. } 30... Qa5 31. Bd2 Rb8
{ Here I missed a beautiful win after  31...d5!  I saw it on the next move though, and I realized the game could have ended here. The line goes  32.Qxd5  Ra6!!  I missed this rook switch  33.Qxa8+  Kg7  and the mate  on a1 is unavoidable. }
32. Kb2 { Preparing Ra1. } 32... d5
{ This is still very strong but not as clear as 1 move before. } 33. Ra1 dxe4
{ It's important that I have this move and open the position. } 34. Rxa5 exd3
35. cxd3 Re2 36. Kc2
{ The ending is lost for White, but there is still some work to be done. }
36... Bxc3
{ Actually,  36...Bd4!  was the best move here,  threatening ...Be3. } 37. Kxc3
Rf2 38. Rxc5 Rxf3 39. Kc4 Rxh3 { Collecting as many pawns as possible. } 40. g5
Rh2 41. Bc3 Rf2
{ 41...h6  or  41...h5  are better moves here, creating two connected passed pawns. }
42. b4 Rf5
{ This was my idea. I'm activating the rook, but I lost some time, and I cannot take on c5. }
43. d4 f6 { Finally! A good decision to create the passed pawns. } 44. gxf6
Rxf6 45. d5 Rf4+ { I'm gaining a tempo with this move. } 46. Bd4 Rb7
{ 46...Re8!  was the most precise. } 47. Rc6
{ Only  47.Rc8+!  could put some problems, but after  47...Kf7!  , Black is winning anyway. }
47... Kf7 48. Kc5 Rf5 49. b5 h5
{ I'm winning, but tempi are important, as White is also ready to get some counterplay if he can bring the king to c6. }
50. Ra6 Rd7
{ The only winning move, but it's enough. I don't have to allow White to play Kc6. }
51. Rd6 Rxd6 52. Kxd6 h4
{ White resigned, as the endgame is lost for him after  53.Bxa7  h3  54.Bg1  Rg5  55.Bh2  Rg2  56.Be5  h2  57.Bxh2  Rxh2  58.b6  Ke8  . A nice fighting game. I was very happy to see the move @@StartFEN@@r1q1r1kb/pppn1p1p/3pb1p1/6B1/P2NP1P1/2N1Q2P/1PP2P2/1K1RR3 b - - 3 17@@EndFEN@@  17....b5!!  on the board. }
