1. c4 d6 2. Nc3 e5 3. g3 f5 4. d4 Be7 5. Bg2 Nf6 6. e3 c6 7. Nge2 O-O 8. O-O e4
9. f3 d5 10. Qb3
{ A slight inaccuracy, as the queen will be misplaced here.  10.cxd5  is the main move given in the course. }
10... Kh8 { Avoiding the pin on the a2-g8 diagonal. } 11. fxe4 dxe4
{ Only like this, and it's important to remember it.  11...fxe4?  is just awful, for example,  12.cxd5  cxd5  13.Rxf6!  Bxf6  14.Qxd5  and  the e4-pawn will fall too. }
12. Bd2 Na6
{ A good way to develop the knight. In some cases, ...Nc5 may be a threat, as the d2-bishop is hanging. }
13. Rad1
{ White developed all the pieces, but he doesn't have a good plan to continue. }
13... Qe8 14. a3 Rb8
{ A useful move, defending the b7-pawn, and there are also ideas to push ...b5. Black is doing great strategically − he has more space, and the g2-bishop is closed. }
15. Bc1
{ It was better to remove the queen from b3 in order to prepare b4. For example,  15.Qa2  was a better move. }
15... b5 { Very strong. Black has a big advantage on the queenside as well. }
16. cxb5 cxb5 17. Qa2 { Hoping to get b4. } 17... b4
{ But it's Black who is going for it. } 18. axb4 Nxb4
{ White's position is just collapsing. } 19. Qxa7 Ba6 20. Qc7 Nfd5 21. Qe5 Nxc3
22. Nxc3 Bxf1 { Black is up an exchange while keeping a dominating position. }
23. Bxf1 Bg5
{ It was better to play  23...Qd8  and only then ...Bg5, in order to avoid the queen trade. }
24. Qa5
{ Now White's position is just lost.  24.Qxe8  still gave some chances to stay in the game. }
24... Nc2 25. Nd5 Qh5 26. Qd2 Nxe3 { White's position is falling apart. } 27.
Be2 Nxd5 28. Bxh5 Bxd2 29. Bxd2 Rxb2 30. Kf1 e3 31. Be1 f4
{ An instructive game, just showing how strong the plans shown in the course can be! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
