[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Benjamin Bok − Arjun Erigaisi, chess.com 2024"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5 2. g3 d6 3. Bg2 Be7 4. Nc3 f5 5. b4 Nf6 6. d3 O-O 7. Nf3 a6 8. O-O h6
9. a4 Qe8 10. e3
{ 10.Bb2  was mentioned in the course. Anyway, in this game, both players were happy to get some playable position out of the opening since it was a rapid game on the internet. }
10... Be6
{ This is possible because the g5-square is under control; ...Nbd7 will follow. }
11. Bb2 Nbd7 12. b5
{ White gained some space on the queenside, but it's not clear what he is going to do next. }
12... Qf7 13. Nd2 { A typical regrouping move, opening up the bishop. } 13...
Rab8 { 13...d5  could be considered as well. } 14. Qe2 c6
{ I like this move, fighting for the center. White cannot take twice on c6 because the b2-bishop is hanging. }
15. bxc6 bxc6 16. Ba3 d5
{ Now Black has a nice center, and more importantly, the g2-bishop is shut off. }
17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. cxd5 cxd5 19. d4
{ Putting the pawns on dark squares in order to keep the bishop active. } 19...
Rfc8 { Black starts activating his rooks. } 20. Rfc1 Rb2 21. Nd1
{ White decides to trade the active rooks. It was possible to go  21.Qxa6  ,  attacking the c8-rook.  21...Nb8  , and now a nice line goes  22.Qxc8+!?  Bxc8  23.Nxd5  Nxd5  24.Rxc8+  Kh7  25.Bxd5  Rxd2  26.Rxb8  with a balanced position. }
21... Rbc2 22. Rxc2 Rxc2 23. Qd3 { A good move, forcing the black rook back. }
23... Rc6 24. dxe5
{ The start of White's problems. It's tempting to take on e5 in order to create some weaknesses in Black's position, but it will also activate his pieces. It was better to stay put with  24.Qb3  . }
24... Nxe5 25. Qd4 Qc7
{ Black's pieces are very active. He controls the c-file and the knights can jump to either e4 or c4. }
26. Nf3
{ It was better to bring the passive knight into play:  26.Nb2  with the idea Nd3. The d2-knight was controlling the important squares e4 and c4. }
26... Nxf3+ 27. Bxf3 Rc4
{ Now this move is possible, and we can see that the d1-knight is out of play. }
28. Qb2 Rc2 29. Qd4 Ne4 30. a5
{ Too slow. White tries to fix a weakness on a6, but he'll never get a chance to attack it.   The only way to stay in the game was to try to trade the c2-rook. So  30.Rb1!  had to be tried. The point is that  30...Nd2  is met with  31.Bxd5  , or if @@StartFEN@@6k1/2q3p1/p3b2p/3p1p2/P2Qn3/4PBP1/2r2P1P/1R1N2K1 b - - 6 30@@EndFEN@@  30...Kh7  , then  31.Rb2! }
30... Kh7
{ A good prophylactic move, removing the king from any potential checks. } 31.
Bg2 Bf7
{ Another good move; if White goes Qb6, the bishop will not be attacked. In the meantime there is the strong threat of ...Rd2 followed by ...Qc2. }
32. Bh3 Qc8
{ 32...Rd2!  was more precise here, not allowing the white  queen to go to e5. }
33. Qe5 { At least White managed to keep the queen active. } 33... Be6 34. Bg2
Rd2 35. h4 Bd7 { 35...Re2!  was essential, with the idea ...Re1+. } 36. Bh3 Kg8
37. Rb1
{ Understandably, White tries to bring the rook into play, threatening Rb8. However, this fails for tactical reasons.   After  37.f3!  Nf6  38.Bf1  , White would have had a slightly worse but playable position. }
37... Qc2
{ The b1-rook, d1-knight, and the f2-pawn are hanging, and White is not in time to create threats. }
38. Rb8+ Kf7 { White has no checks. } 39. Bxf5 Rxd1+ 40. Kg2 Qxf2+ 41. Kh3
Bxf5+ { A fighting game, and a good example of showing Black's plans. } *

