{ Comments by GM Leon Livaic. } 1. e4
{ The game was played in the German Bundesliga 2024/2025. It's time to see if  1...d6  can hold vs. top 10 players. }
1... d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. h3 c6 8. a4
exd4 9. Qxd4 Nc5 10. Rd1 Be6
{ Up to this point, it's all covered in the course. } 11. b4
{ Here Alireza plays a novelty. We only mentioned the critical  11.Bf4  and  11.a5  . White's idea is obvious, though; he wants to seize a lot of space on the queenside. }
11... Bxc4
{ Surprisingly enough, this is not the most accurate reply, although Black should be fine.  11...Ncxe4  equalizes immediately, as after  12.Bxe6  , there is  12...Nxc3  13.Bxf7+  @@StartBracket@@only move not to lose material@@EndBracket@@  13...Rxf7  14.Qxc3  Ne4!  followed by ...d5 with a very good position.   12.Nxe4  d5!  regaining material and opening the position is immediately better for Black. }
12. Qxc4 Ne6
{ My idea was this, similar to other lines we analyzed in the course. In general, this setup with the knights is very flexible, as it's hard for White to attack d6 and Black can make improving moves like ...Re8, ...Qc7, ...Bf8... }
13. Be3
{ The bishop is better placed here than on the long diagonal, as it is eyeing the a7-pawn. Because of that, I have to either keep the rook on a8 or play a weakening move like ...a6 or ...a5, which gives up squares.   Note that  13.e5  d5  14.exf6  dxc4  15.Rxd8  fails to  15...Bxd8  . }
13... Re8
{ In this position, e5 is still not a threat so I can make useful improving moves. }
14. a5 { White keeps seizing space on the queenside. } 14... Qc8
{ I was a bit worried about White playing a6, so I wanted to protect the c6-pawn.   14...Qc7  was, of course, also possible, but I didn't want the queen to come under some Nb5 attack if White ever plays Nd4 and exchanges the e6-knight. Also, with the game move I can play ...Nc7 and ...Qe6 if needed. }
15. Qb3
{ ...d5 wasn't really my idea, but it's surely useful to make the queen less exposed. }
15... Bf8
{ Another improving move, as now the rook will be attacking e4 later on. } 16.
Nd2
{ The known plan, trying to bring the knight to c4 and protecting e4 in advance. }
16... Nc7
{ It feels like the right time for this maneuver, as now  17.Nc4  can be met with  17...d5!  or even  17...Qe6  . }
17. Bd4 { Trying to ruin the pawn structure with Bxf6. } 17... Qe6
{ 17...Nd7  was probably also fine, but why not exchange queens? Black has less space, so fewer pieces should favor him, and there is no way to exploit this move for White. }
18. Rab1 { A very nice move, preparing b5 and activating a new piece. } 18...
Nd7 { The idea is not so much to stop Bxf6, more to play ...b5 myself. } 19. b5
{ What else? It's hard to find a better way to play for a win, but it does give me the c5-square. }
19... Qxb3 20. Rxb3 Ne6 { It's time to bring the pieces into play with tempo. }
21. Be3 Ndc5 22. Rbb1 g6
{ I was a bit concerned about a6 or Nb3 ideas for White, but this move is very nice, as it is threatening to attack c3 with ...Bg7, and then the e4-pawn could remain very weak. }
23. bxc6
{ I actually expected  23.a6  bxa6  24.bxc6  Rec8  25.Nd5  . Black is probably fine, but there are still problems to solve. }
23... bxc6 24. Nc4
{ This was a relief. I was worried about  24.Nb3  where I would have to go  24...Bg7  25.Rxd6  Bxc3  26.Nxc5  Nxc5  27.Bxc5  , when it seemed to me it was uncomfortable to defend, but with correct play, Black is fine after both  27...Bxa5  and  27...Rxe4  . }
24... Rad8
{ Probably Alireza missed this resource. After  24...Bg7  25.Ne2  Nxe4  26.Nxd6  , White is indeed better. But after @@StartFEN@@r3rbk1/p4p1p/2ppn1p1/P1n5/2N1P3/2N1B2P/2P2PP1/1R1R2K1 b - - 1 24@@EndFEN@@  24...Rad8  , there is not much White can do against the  incoming ...Bg7 and ...d5. }
25. e5
{ Here White offered a draw. I knew I should be at least preferable, if not better after  25...d5  26.Nd6  Bxd6  27.exd6  Rxd6  28.Ne2  Rd7  29.Nd4  , but White has counterplay, and with 8 minutes against 30 on the clock, I decided to accept. An interesting fight. }
